te Night Tales: Agnes Obel'''''\n*Artist: [[Agnes Obel]]\n*Released: 25 May 2018\n*Cat no: ALNLP49\n*Singles: \"Poem About Death\"\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''''Late Night Tales: Floating Points'''''\n*Artist: [[Floating Points]]\n*Released: 29 March 2019\n*Cat no: ALNLP52\n*Singles: \"Sweet Time Suite Opening (Exclusive [[Kenny Wheeler]] Cover Version)\"\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Back to Mine]]\n* [[DJ-Kicks]]\n* [[Fabric discography]]\n* [[Solid Steel]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{official website|http://www.latenighttales.co.uk/}}\n* {{discogs label|LateNightTales}}\n\n{{Late Night Tales}}\n\n{{italic title}}\n\n[[Category:Late Night Tales| ]]\n[[Category:DJ mix album series]]\n[[Category:Compilation album series]]\n", "name_user": "Aeternus", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAlbums", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Late_Night_Tales"}
{"title_page": "Tulum cheese", "text_new": "{{short description|A traditional Turkish goat's milk cheese ripened in a goatskin casing}}\n{{Infobox cheese\n| name = Tulum\n| image = \n| othernames =\n| country = [[Turkey]]\n| regiontown = [[Erzincan]], [[Izmir]], Divle, \u00c7ini, [[Karg\u0131]]\n| region = [[Eastern Anatolia Region|Eastern Anatolia]], [[Aegean Region|Aegean]], [[Central Anatolia Region|Central Anatolia]], [[Mediterranean Region|Mediterranean]], [[Black Sea Region|Black Sea]]\n| town = \n| source = [[Goat]]s\n| pasteurized = No\n| texture = Soft-ripened\n| fat =\n| protein =\n| dimensions =\n| weight =\n| aging = 6 months (conventional)\n| certification = \n}}\n[[File:Tulum cheese.jpg|thumb|Tulum peyniri from [[Erzincan]], [[Turkey]].]]\n[[File:Otlu tulum peyniri.jpg|thumb|Varieties of tulum, center \"Otlu tulum peyniri\", or Tulum with herbs, in [[Ankara]]]]\n'''Tulum cheese''' ({{lang-tr|tulum peyniri}}) is a traditional [[Turkey|Turkish]] [[goat cheese|goat's milk cheese]] ripened in a goatskin casing, called ''tulum'' in Turkish. Due to its unique flavor, it is preferred as [[meze]] to [[rak\u0131]] in Turkey.{{Clarify|date=June 2015}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gurmerehberi.com/gurme-rehberi/yiyecekler/raki-mezeleri/ |publisher=Gurme Rehberi |title=Rak\u0131 Mezeleri |language=Turkish |accessdate=2011-11-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401035633/http://www.gurmerehberi.com/gurme-rehberi/yiyecekler/raki-mezeleri/ |archivedate=2012-04-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Cheesemaking==\n\n===Conventional===\nTulum cheese is made by heating high-fat goat's milk to a temperature of {{convert|30|C|F}} and subsequently [[souring]] it through addition a starter culture. The milk then starts to coagulate. After about an hour, the milk is entirely converted into [[curd]]s and [[whey]].<ref name=\"l\">{{cite web |url=http://lezzetler.com/tulum-peyniri-vt10020.html |publisher=Lezzetler |title=Tulum Peyniri |author=Atabay, Banu |language=Turkish |accessdate=2011-11-12 }}</ref>\n\nThe curd is drained and repeatedly cut by special knives into smaller cubes allowing the whey to drain. The temperature is kept constant throughout this process. The curds are collected in hemp [[cheesecloth]], which have been cleaned, cooled and wetted before use. The bundles of curd are then hung for eight hours to allow them to drain and cure. The curds in the cheesecloth are then pressed into a form with a wooden cover. A weight is placed on the cover for several hours allowing more whey to be expressed. The curd is subsequently cut in pieces the size of bar of soap and immersed in [[brine]]. The pieces are then arranged on a counter, and cured for 24 hours.<ref name=\"l\"/>\n\nThe next day, the curds are crushed by hand, kneaded with raw goat's milk and then tightly stuffed into a goatskin casing, which has been cleaned and salted. The curd filling is topped with salt, and the casing's opening is fastened with a cord. The goatskin casing is stored in a cool place such as a cave or cellar at temperatures of {{convert|10|to|12|C|F}} for about six months to ripen. The casing may be perforated at its sides to allow any residual whey to drain.<ref name=\"l\"/>\n\n===Commercial===\nContrary to homemade cheese, commercial tulum is made of goat's milk with a lower fat content, and kneaded with [[water buffalo]] or [[sheep milk]], ripened in cowskin casings, and produced in an accelerated process that makes it, however, less durable. Its flavor is slightly different and it may become [[Mold (fungus)|mold]]y.<ref name=\"l\"/> Ripening of commercially produced tulum is commonly also carried out in plastic barrels.<ref name=\"h\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.hayyam.com/haberler/cesitli-yerli-peynirler/ |publisher=Hayyam |journal=G\u0131da Dergisi |title=\u00dclkemizde \u00fcretilen \u00e7e\u015fitli tip yerli peynirler |date=March 1999 |author=Anar, \u015eahsene |language=Turkish |accessdate=2011-11-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130125170033/http://www.hayyam.com/haberler/cesitli-yerli-peynirler/ |archivedate=2013-01-25 }}</ref>\n\n==Tulum cheese by location==\nTulum cheese is differentiated in Turkey by location. Cheese originating from different parts of the country differs in taste due to variation in production techniques. The most notable tulum cheeses are:<ref name=\"h\"/>\n\n;Tulum cheese of [[Erzincan]]:\nMade in [[Erzincan Province]] in [[Eastern Anatolia Region]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tarimziraat.com/gida/peynir_cesitleri/erzincan_tulum_peyniri/erzincan_tulum_peyniri_nasil_yapilir/ |publisher=Tar\u0131m ve Ziraat Bilgi Bankas\u0131 |title=Erzincan Tulum Peyniri - Erzincan Tulum Peyniri Nas\u0131l Yap\u0131l\u0131r |language=Turkish |accessdate=2011-11-12 }}</ref>\n\n;Tulum cheese of [[Izmir]]:\nThe tulum cheese of Izmir differs from other regional tulum cheese varieties in processing and characteristic.\nProduced in [[Aegean Region]] provinces like \u0130zmir, [[Ayd\u0131n]], [[Manisa]], [[Mu\u011fla]] and [[Bal\u0131kesir]], it is made of raw milk heated to {{convert|60|-|65|C|F}}, and cooled immediately down to acidifying temperature. Curds are brined in 16-percentage solution and cured for one night. The curd is filled then in cans with 12-percentage solution of brine for ripening.<ref>{{citation |author=K\u0131l\u0131\u00e7, S. |author2=G\u00f6n\u00e7, S. |author3=Uysal, H. |publisher=V. S\u00fct ve S\u00fct \u00dcr\u00fcnleri Semp. Geleneksel S\u00fct \u00dcr\u00fcnleri |title=Geleneksel Y\u00f6ntemle ve K\u00fclt\u00fcr Kullan\u0131larak Yap\u0131lan \u0130zmir Tulum Peynirinin Olgunla\u015fma S\u00fcrecinde Meydana Gelen De\u011fi\u015fikliklerin K\u0131yaslanmas\u0131 |date=1998-05-22 |place=Tekirda\u011f |language=Turkish |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n;Tulum cheese of Divle\nDivle is a village in the [[Ayranc\u0131]] district of [[Karaman Province]] in [[Central Anatolia Region]].\n\n;Tulum cheese of \u00c7imi:\n\u00c7imi is a village in the [[Akseki]] district of [[Antalya Province]] in [[Mediterranean Region]].\n\n;Tulum chese of Karg\u0131:\nProduced in [[Karg\u0131]] of [[\u00c7orum province]] in [[Black Sea Region]], this variety comes closest to conventional{{Clarify|date=June 2015}} tulum cheese. The annual production of 25 tons is mostly consumed in [[\u00c7orum]] and its neighbouring provinces [[Kastamonu]], [[Samsun]] and [[Ankara]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goletkargi.tr.gg/TULUM-PEYNiRi.htm |publisher=G\u00f6let Karg\u0131 |title=Tulum Peyniri |language=Turkish |accessdate=2011-11-12 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food}}\n* {{annotated link|Brined cheese}}\n* {{annotated link|List of cheeses}}\n* {{annotated link|List of goat milk cheeses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Cuisine of Turkey}}\n{{Turkish cheeses}}\n\n[[Category:Goat's-milk cheeses]]\n[[Category:Turkish cheeses]]\n[[Category:Meze]]\n[[Category:Brined cheeses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A traditional Turkish goat's milk cheese ripened in a goatskin casing}}\n{{Infobox cheese\n| name = Tulum\n| image = \n| othernames =\n| country = [[Turkey]]\n| regiontown = [[Erzincan]], [[Izmir]], Divle, \u00c7ini, [[Karg\u0131]]\n| region = [[Eastern Anatolia Region|Eastern Anatolia]], [[Aegean Region|Aegean]], [[Central Anatolia Region|Central Anatolia]], [[Mediterranean Region|Mediterranean]], [[Black Sea Region|Black Sea]]\n| town = \n| source = [[Goat]]s\n| pasteurized = No\n| texture = Soft-ripened\n| fat =\n| protein =\n| dimensions =\n| weight =\n| aging = 6 months (conventional)\n| certification = \n}}\n[[File:Tulum cheese.jpg|thumb|Tulum peyniri from [[Erzincan]], [[Turkey]].]]\n[[File:Otlu tulum peyniri.jpg|thumb|Varieties of tulum, center \"Otlu tulum peyniri\", or Tulum with herbs, in [[Ankara]]]]\n'''Tulum cheese''' ({{lang-tr|tulum peyniri}}) is a traditional [[Turkey|Turkish]] [[goat cheese|goat's milk cheese]] ripened in a goatskin casing, called ''tulum'' in Turkish. Due to its unique flavor, it is preferred as [[meze]] to [[rak\u0131]] in Turkey.{{Clarify|date=June 2015}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gurmerehberi.com/gurme-rehberi/yiyecekler/raki-mezeleri/ |publisher=Gurme Rehberi |title=Rak\u0131 Mezeleri |language=Turkish |accessdate=2011-11-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401035633/http://www.gurmerehberi.com/gurme-rehberi/yiyecekler/raki-mezeleri/ |archivedate=2012-04-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Cheesemaking==\n\n===Conventional===\nTulum cheese is made by heating high-fat goat's milk to a temperature of {{convert|30|C|F}} and subsequently [[souring]] it through addition a starter culture. The milk then starts to coagulate. After about an hour, the milk is entirely converted into [[curd]]s and [[whey]].<ref name=\"l\">{{cite web |url=http://lezzetler.com/tulum-peyniri-vt10020.html |publisher=Lezzetler |title=Tulum Peyniri |author=Atabay, Banu |language=Turkish |accessdate=2011-11-12 }}</ref>\n\nThe curd is drained and repeatedly cut by special knives into smaller cubes allowing the whey to drain. The temperature is kept constant throughout this process. The curds are collected in hemp [[cheesecloth]], which have been cleaned, cooled and wetted before use. The bundles of curd are then hung for eight hours to allow them to drain and cure. The curds in the cheesecloth are then pressed into a form with a wooden cover. A weight is placed on the cover for several hours allowing more whey to be expressed. The curd is subsequently cut in pieces the size of bar of soap and immersed in [[brine]]. The pieces are then arranged on a counter, and cured for 24 hours.<ref name=\"l\"/>\n\nThe next day, the curds are crushed by hand, kneaded with raw goat's milk and then tightly stuffed into a goatskin casing, which has been cleaned and salted. The curd filling is topped with salt, and the casing's opening is fastened with a cord. The goatskin casing is stored in a cool place such as a cave or cellar at temperatures of {{convert|10|to|12|C|F}} for about six months to ripen. The casing may be perforated at its sides to allow any residual whey to drain.<ref name=\"l\"/>\n\n===Commercial===\nContrary to homemade cheese, commercial tulum is made of goat's milk with a lower fat content, and kneaded with [[water buffalo]] or [[sheep milk]], ripened in cowskin casings, and produced in an accelerated process that makes it, however, less durable. Its flavor is slightly different and it may become [[mold]]y.<ref name=\"l\"/> Ripening of commercially produced tulum is commonly also carried out in plastic barrels.<ref name=\"h\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.hayyam.com/haberler/cesitli-yerli-peynirler/ |publisher=Hayyam |journal=G\u0131da Dergisi |title=\u00dclkemizde \u00fcretilen \u00e7e\u015fitli tip yerli peynirler |date=March 1999 |author=Anar, \u015eahsene |language=Turkish |accessdate=2011-11-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130125170033/http://www.hayyam.com/haberler/cesitli-yerli-peynirler/ |archivedate=2013-01-25 }}</ref>\n\n==Tulum cheese by location==\nTulum cheese is differentiated in Turkey by location. Cheese originating from different parts of the country differs in taste due to variation in production techniques. The most notable tulum cheeses are:<ref name=\"h\"/>\n\n;Tulum cheese of [[Erzincan]]:\nMade in [[Erzincan Province]] in [[Eastern Anatolia Region]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tarimziraat.com/gida/peynir_cesitleri/erzincan_tulum_peyniri/erzincan_tulum_peyniri_nasil_yapilir/ |publisher=Tar\u0131m ve Ziraat Bilgi Bankas\u0131 |title=Erzincan Tulum Peyniri - Erzincan Tulum Peyniri Nas\u0131l Yap\u0131l\u0131r |language=Turkish |accessdate=2011-11-12 }}</ref>\n\n;Tulum cheese of [[Izmir]]:\nThe tulum cheese of Izmir differs from other regional tulum cheese varieties in processing and characteristic.\nProduced in [[Aegean Region]] provinces like \u0130zmir, [[Ayd\u0131n]], [[Manisa]], [[Mu\u011fla]] and [[Bal\u0131kesir]], it is made of raw milk heated to {{convert|60|-|65|C|F}}, and cooled immediately down to acidifying temperature. Curds are brined in 16-percentage solution and cured for one night. The curd is filled then in cans with 12-percentage solution of brine for ripening.<ref>{{citation |author=K\u0131l\u0131\u00e7, S. |author2=G\u00f6n\u00e7, S. |author3=Uysal, H. |publisher=V. S\u00fct ve S\u00fct \u00dcr\u00fcnleri Semp. Geleneksel S\u00fct \u00dcr\u00fcnleri |title=Geleneksel Y\u00f6ntemle ve K\u00fclt\u00fcr Kullan\u0131larak Yap\u0131lan \u0130zmir Tulum Peynirinin Olgunla\u015fma S\u00fcrecinde Meydana Gelen De\u011fi\u015fikliklerin K\u0131yaslanmas\u0131 |date=1998-05-22 |place=Tekirda\u011f |language=Turkish |display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n;Tulum cheese of Divle\nDivle is a village in the [[Ayranc\u0131]] district of [[Karaman Province]] in [[Central Anatolia Region]].\n\n;Tulum cheese of \u00c7imi:\n\u00c7imi is a village in the [[Akseki]] district of [[Antalya Province]] in [[Mediterranean Region]].\n\n;Tulum chese of Karg\u0131:\nProduced in [[Karg\u0131]] of [[\u00c7orum province]] in [[Black Sea Region]], this variety comes closest to conventional{{Clarify|date=June 2015}} tulum cheese. The annual production of 25 tons is mostly consumed in [[\u00c7orum]] and its neighbouring provinces [[Kastamonu]], [[Samsun]] and [[Ankara]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goletkargi.tr.gg/TULUM-PEYNiRi.htm |publisher=G\u00f6let Karg\u0131 |title=Tulum Peyniri |language=Turkish |accessdate=2011-11-12 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food}}\n* {{annotated link|Brined cheese}}\n* {{annotated link|List of cheeses}}\n* {{annotated link|List of goat milk cheeses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Cuisine of Turkey}}\n{{Turkish cheeses}}\n\n[[Category:Goat's-milk cheeses]]\n[[Category:Turkish cheeses]]\n[[Category:Meze]]\n[[Category:Brined cheeses]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link changed toMold (fungus)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tulum_cheese"}
{"title_page": "Yoshihiko Aramaki", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n{{moslow|date=April 2020}}\n{{copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{short description|Japanese actor and voice actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Yoshihiko Aramaki\n| image         = \n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1990|2|5}}\n| birth_place   = [[Tokyo]], Japan\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Japanese\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = {{flatlist|\n*[[Actor]]}}\n| years_active  = 2011\u2013present\n| agent         = Freelancer\n| height        = 176 cm\n| alma_mater    = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Yoshihiko Aramaki'''|\u8352\u7267 \u6176\u5f66|Aramaki Yoshihiko|born February 5, 1990}} is a [[Japan]]ese actor and voice actor, who currently works as a freelancer.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n* Raspberry boy (2013)\n* Love Concierge Season 2 (2017)- cameo appearance\n* TV Theater Success Sou (2019) - Sir\n* REAL\u21d4FAKE (2019)- Makino Nagisa\n\n===Movies===\n* DANCE!DANCEDANCE!! (2014) - Ikegami Takumi\n* Youth discovery film - always youth edition - Pure love stalker (2015)- Sawashima\n* Article 9 (2016)\n* MOONBOW - Itsuki\n* Oedo no candy 2 - The birds of Paradise (2017) - Tsuge Takeshi\n* Unusual occupation (2017) - Shinya\n* Shuukatsu 3 - Episode 2 \"Heritage\"\n* ''[[Touken Ranbu (film)|Touken Ranbu]]'' (2019) - Yamanbagiri Kunihiro<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-11-19/live-action-touken-ranbu-film-1st-teaser-highlights-characters/.139730|title=Live-Action Touken Ranbu Film's 1st Teaser Highlights Characters|date=November 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Stage Play===\n* Musical \"The Prince of Tennis\" Second Season - Kai Yuujirou\n** Seigaku vs. Higa (2012) \n** Nationals: Sekigaku Vs Hyoutei (2013)\n* Raspberry boy (2013)\n* Ogre Slayer Chapter 2 - Day to come (2013)\n* Musical \"Nintama Ranta