{"title_page": "HTC Vive", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox\n| title = HTC Vive\n| image = [[File:Vive pre.jpeg|upright=1.1|frameless]]\n| caption = An HTC Vive head-mounted display with a camera near the bottom rim; two wireless handheld controllers; and two 'Lighthouse' basestations\n| label1 = Type\n| data1 = [[Virtual reality headset]] for room scale virtual reality\n| label2 = Release date\n| data2 = 5 April 2016\n| label4 = Manufacturer\n| data4 = [[HTC]], with technology by [[Valve Corporation|Valve]]\n| label5 = Display technology\n| data5 = [[PenTile matrix family|PenTile]]<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/03/ask-ars-i-cant-choose-between-oculus-rift-htc-vive-and-playstation-vr/ | first = Lee | last = Hutchinson | title = Ask Ars: I can\u2019t choose between Oculus Rift, HTC Vive, and PlayStation VR! | date = 22 March 2016 | access-date = 24 September 2016 | work = Ars Technica}}</ref> [[OLED]]\n| label6 = Resolution\n| data6 = 2160\u00d71200 (1080\u00d71200 per eye)<ref name=\"HTC Re Vive\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vive.com/us/|title=VIVE\u2122 &#124; Discover Virtual Reality Beyond Imagination|website=www.vive.com}}</ref>\n| label7 = Refresh rate\n| data7 = 90 Hz<ref name=\"HTC Re Vive\"/>\n| label8 = Field of view (Nominal)\n| data8 = About 110 degrees<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alex.vlachos.com/graphics/Alex_Vlachos_Advanced_VR_Rendering_GDC2015.pdf|title=Advanced VR Rendering, Alex Vlachos, Valve}}</ref>\n| label9 = Tracking system\n| data9 = Lighthouse (2 base stations emitting pulsed IR lasers)\n| label10 = Input\n| data10 = Video/data/Bluetooth\n| label11 = Weight\n| data11 = 470 grams (previously 555 grams)\n| label12 = Platform/operating system\n| data12 = SteamVR running on [[Microsoft Windows]] in addition to [[Linux]] support, with [[macOS]] support coming<ref name=\"Machkovech\">{{Cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2017/06/steamvr-is-coming-to-mac-and-apple-says-it-will-actually-work/ | title = SteamVR is coming to Mac\u2014and Apple says it will actually work | first = Sam | last= Machkovech | date =5 June 2017 | accessdate = 5 June 2017 | work = [[Ars Technica]] }}</ref>\n| label13 = Connection\n| data13 = 1\u00d7 [[HDMI|HDMI 1.4]] or DisplayPort 1.2 and 1\u00d7 [[USB 3.0]]\n| label14 = Website\n| data14 = {{url|http://www.vive.com/}}\n| label15 = Introductory price\n| data15 = [[United States dollar|US$]]799/[[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]689\n| label16 = Sound\n| data16 = {{plainlist|\n* 3.5 mm [[audio jack]] for headphones\n* Built-in microphone\n* Headphones will be sold separately from June 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/htcs-deluxe-audio-strap-is-a-huge-improvement-over-the-vives-elastic-straps/|title=HTC's Deluxe Audio Strap is a huge improvement over the Vive's elastic straps|first=Wes|last=Fenlon|date=1 March 2017}}</ref>}}\n| label17 = Controller input\n| data17 = SteamVR wireless motion tracked controllers\n| label18 = Camera\n| data18 = Front-facing camera - enabling users to view the external world and a key component of the device\u2019s 'chaperone' safety system.\n}}\n\nThe '''HTC Vive''' is a [[virtual reality headset]] developed by [[HTC]] and [[Valve Corporation|Valve]]. The headset uses \"[[room scale]]\" tracking technology, allowing the user to move in 3D space and use motion-tracked handheld controllers to interact with the environment.<ref name=verge-vive>{{cite web|title=Valve's VR headset is called the Vive and it's made by HTC|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/3/1/8127445/htc-vive-valve-vr-headset|website=The Verge|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe HTC Vive was unveiled during HTC's [[Mobile World Congress]] keynote in March 2015. Development kits were sent out in August and September 2015,{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} and the first consumer version of the device was released in April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.htc.com/us/newsroom/2016-06-07/|title=VIVE NOW SHIPPING IMMEDIATELY FROM HTC, RETAIL PARTNERS EXPAND DEMO LOCATIONS|last=|first=|date=|website=www.htc.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nPrototypes of a Valve-produced virtual reality system were demonstrated during 2014. On 23 February 2015, Valve announced SteamVR and that it would demonstrate a \"SteamVR hardware system\" at the 2015 [[Game Developers Conference]].<ref name=engadget-steamvr>{{cite web|title=Valve is making a VR headset and its own Steam Machine|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/02/23/steamvr-valve-virtual-reality-gdc/|website=Engadget|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=verge-gdcsteamvr>{{cite web|title=Valve showing off new virtual reality hardware and updated Steam controller next week|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/2/23/8094817/valve-virtual-reality-hardware-gdc-2015|website=The Verge|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=verge-valvevr>{{cite web|title=Valve's VR headset revealed with Oculus-like features|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/6/3/5775220/valve-vr-headset-pictures-concept-features|website=The Verge|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref> HTC officially unveiled its device, Vive, during its [[Mobile World Congress]] keynote on 1 March 2015.<ref name=verge-vive/>  Preorders started on 29 February 2016 at 10:00&nbsp;a.m. EST.<ref>{{Cite web|title = HTC Vive pre-orders to start on February 29|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/12092607/HTC-Vive-pre-orders-to-start-on-February-29.html|website = Telegraph.co.uk|access-date = 22 January 2016}}</ref> Valve and HTC have since announced that the headset will be free for selected developers.<ref name=theverge-steamvrfree>{{cite web|title=Valve, HTC Offering Free Vive VR to Developers|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2479252,00.asp|website=The Verge|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Consumer Electronics Show]] 2016, HTC and Valve unveiled a near-final hardware revision of the device, known as HTC Vive Pre.<ref name=ars-vivepre>{{cite web|title=HTC Vive Pre impressions: A great VR system has only gotten better|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/01/htc-vive-pre-impressions-a-great-vr-system-has-only-gotten-better/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=28 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDuring his Immersed 2015 keynote, Phil Chen, Chief Content Officer for HTC and founder of the HTC Vive, explained that he \"stumbled upon VR\" and later, HTC met Valve, which turned out to be \"serendipity\".<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KZS6nCKPUDs&t=11m55s|time=11m55s|title=MTBS-TV: Conversing With Phil Chen, Chief Content Officer, HTC|via=YouTube|author=Neil Schneider|date= 8 October 2015}}</ref> Chen also explained that HTC and Valve don't have a clear dividing line between each of their responsibilities, and HTC is very much a partner in the research and development process.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KZS6nCKPUDs&t=16m46s|time=16m46s|title=MTBS-TV: Conversing With Phil Chen, Chief Content Officer, HTC|via=YouTube|author=Neil Schneider|date= 8 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, HTC announced the release of their 'Business Edition' of the Vive for US$1,200 which would include a Professional Use License, a 12-month Commercial Warranty, access to an exclusive support line, a 5-meter (16&nbsp;ft) cable extension kit, and it included the [https://xinreality.com/wiki/HTC_Vive_Deluxe_Audio_Strap Deluxe Audio Strap].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.roadtovr.com/htc-announces-vive-business-edition-for-1200/ |title=HTC Announces Vive 'Business Edition' for $1200 |last=Hayden|first=Scott|date=2016-06-09|work=Road to VR|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vive.com/us/enterprise/|title=VIVE {{!}} Business Edition and Commercial VR|website=www.vive.com|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, HTC announced a tether-less VR upgrade kit made by TPCAST. A public model was shown at [http://www.techradar.com/news/ces-dates-news-reviews-and-videos CES 2017] and had a price of $249.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uploadvr.com/tpcast-wireless-vive-kit-works/|title=Hands-on: TPCAST's Wireless Vive Kit Really Works|date=2016-12-19|newspaper=UploadVR|access-date=2017-02-24|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/ces/2017/1/4/14172296/htc-vive-wireless-adapter-tpcast-ces-2017|title=HTC\u2019s wireless Vive add-on actually works|last=Byford|first=Sam|newspaper=The Verge|access-date=2017-02-24}}</ref>\n\nAt Google I/O in May 2017, Google announced a new, all in-built 'Standalone VR' system that would be made by the Vive team and also by Lenovo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vrfocus.com/2017/05/google-announces-standalone-headset-to-be-made-by-htc-and-lenovo/|title=Google Announces Standalone Headset to be Made by HTC and Lenovo|date=2017-05-17|website=VRFocus|access-date=2017-05-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Whilst in June 2017 Valve revealed details of a second variation of Vive controller which utilizes finger tracking called the Knuckles Vive controller.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vrfocus.com/2017/06/valve-provides-details-on-upcoming-knuckles-vive-controllers/|title=Valve Provides Details on Upcoming Knuckles Vive Controllers|date=2017-06-22|website=VRFocus|access-date=2017-06-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Hardware and accessories ==\n* '''Vive Headset''': The Vive headset has a [[refresh rate]] of 90&nbsp;[[Hertz|Hz]] and a 110 degree field of view. The device uses two [[OLED]] panels, one per eye, each having a [[display resolution]] of 1080\u00d71200 (2160\u00d71200 combined pixels).<ref name=\"gamespot-steamvr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/valve-and-htc-reveal-vive-vr-headset/1100-6425606/|title=Valve and HTC reveal Vive VR headset|website=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref> Safety features include a front-facing camera that allows the user to observe their surroundings without removing their headset. The software can also use the camera to identify any moving or static objects in a room; this functionality can be used as part of a \"Chaperone\" safety system, which will automatically display a virtual wall or a feed from the camera to safely guide users from obstacles or real-world walls.<ref name=\"ars-vivepre\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomsguide.com/us/htc-vive-interview,news-21356.html|title=HTC: Why Vive Will Beat Oculus VR at Its Own Game|website=Tom's Guide|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref> Inside the headset's outer-shell divots are dozens of infrared sensors that detect the base stations' IR pulses to determine the headset's current location in a space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gizmodo.com/this-is-how-valve-s-amazing-lighthouse-tracking-technol-1705356768|title=This Is How Valve\u2019s Amazing Lighthouse Tracking Technology Works|last=Buckley|first=Sean|work=Gizmodo|access-date=2017-11-21|language=en-US}}</ref> Other sensors include a [[G-Sensor]], [[gyroscope]] and [[Proximity sensor|proximity]] sensor.<ref name=\"vive.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vive.com/us/product/vive-virtual-reality-system/|title=VIVE\u2122 {{!}} VIVE Virtual Reality System|website=www.vive.com|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref>\n* '''Vive Controllers''': The controllers have multiple input methods including a track pad, grip buttons, and a dual-stage trigger and a use per charge of about 6 hours.<ref name=\"vive.com\"/> Across the ring of the controller are 24 infrared sensors that detect the base stations to determine the location of the controller.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vrheads.com/exposing-magic-behind-htc-vive-controller|title=Exploring the magic behind the HTC Vive controller|work=VRHeads|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref> The SteamVR Tracking system is used to track the controller location to a fraction of a millimeter, with update rates ranging from 250&nbsp;Hz to 1&nbsp;kHz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://partner.steamgames.com/vrlicensing|title=Welcome to Steamworks|website=partner.steamgames.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref>\n* '''Vive Base Stations''': Also known as the Lighthouse tracking system are two black boxes that create a 360 degree virtual space. The base stations emit timed infrared pulses at 60 pulses per second that are then picked up by the headset and controllers with sub-millimeter precision.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.roadtovr.com/latest-vive-shipping-with-tweaked-base-stations-redesigned-packaging/|title=Latest HTC Vives Are Shipping with Tweaked Base Stations, Redesigned Packaging |last=Lang|first=Ben|date=2017-04-13|work=Road to VR|access-date=2017-11-21|language=en-US}}</ref> Wireless syncing lowers the amount of wires as well standard threading making the base stations practical to use in a home.<ref name=\"vive.com\"/>\n* '''Vive Tracker''': A motion tracking accessory; it is designed to be attached to physical accessories and controllers, so that they can be tracked via the Lighthouse system. Vive Trackers feature a connector that can be used to communicate with the accessory it is attached to. On launch, the Vive Tracker was sold as a standalone product, and in bundles with accessories and games designed to integrate with it, such as the Hyper Blaster (a [[light gun]]-style controller), and a [[racquet]] designed for sports games. Other third-party accessories have been developed for use with Vive Trackers, such as bands designed to be attached to a user's arms or legs to enable body tracking.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/11/16/16664916/htc-vive-tracker-bundles-date-price|title=HTC launches Vive tracker bundles|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vrheads.com/everything-we-know-about-vive-tracker|title=Everything you need to know about the Vive Tracker|work=VRHeads|access-date=2017-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/16/htc-vive-tracker-hands-on/|title=HTC's Vive Tracker adds much-needed tactile control to VR|work=Engadget|access-date=2017-11-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* '''Vive Deluxe Audio Strap''': In June 2017, HTC released the Deluxe Audio Strap for US$99. It added integrated over-ear headphones as well as improved the HMD's comfort through better weight distribution.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/2/27/14748876/htc-vive-deluxe-audio-strap-tracker-price-availability|title=HTC\u2019s Vive Deluxe Audio Strap is coming in June for $99.99|work=The Verge|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vive.com/us/vive-deluxe-audio-strap/|title=VIVE\u2122 {{!}} Vive Deluxe Audio Strap|website=www.vive.com|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref>\n* '''Vive Wireless Adapter''': The Vive Wireless Adapter was launched as an accessory in September 2018 for the original Vive and Vive Pro. It allows to connect the Headset with the Computer wirelessly. The Wireless Adapter is priced at $300 for Vive and $360 for Vive Pro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vive.com/us/wireless-adapter/|title=Wirelss Adapter on Vive Webpage|website=www.vive.com|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.roadtovr.com/htc-vive-wireless-adapter-release-date-price/ |title=Vive Wireless Adapter now available |last=Lang|first=Ben|date=2018-09-24|work=Road to VR|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n* '''Valve Index Controllers''': The Vive can use the [[Valve Index]] controllers (known during development as Knuckle Controllers) developed by [[Valve Corporation|Valve]].\n\nThe Vive initially required computers running [[Microsoft Windows]]. In February 2017, support was added for [[Linux]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/02/22/valve-launches-steamvr-support-for-linux/|title=Valve launches SteamVR support for Linux|website=Engadget|access-date=2017-06-26}}</ref> followed by support for [[MacOS]] in June 2017.<ref name=\"Machkovech\"/>\n\n== Games ==\n{{main|List of HTC Vive games}}\nBy March 2016, the time at which the pre-orders for the HTC Vive opened, 107 games were known to be coming to the virtual reality format.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Finder|url=http://www.finder.com.au/gaming/complete-list-of-htc-vive-vr-games/|title=107 games revealed ahead of HTC Vive pre-order launch|date=29 March 2015|accessdate=29 February 2016|first=Chris|last=Stead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619210337/https://www.finder.com.au/gaming/complete-list-of-htc-vive-vr-games|archive-date=19 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017 Valve CEO [[Gabe Newell]] announced via Reddit AMA 'ask me anything'  session Valve is developing three AAA VR IPs. Ultimately, in November 2019, Valve announced ''[[Half-Life: Alyx]]'' as its flagship VR title for the Vive and its own [[Valve Index]] headset, to be released in March 2020, though the game will support all headsets compatible with the SteamVR protocol.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2019/11/21/20975860/valve-half-life-alyx-release-date-vr-announcement-first-screens-trailer | title = Half-Life: Alyx is Valve\u2019s VR-exclusive, full-length prequel to Half-Life 2 | first=  Michael | last = McWhertor | date = November 21, 2019 | accessdate = November 21, 2019 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\nAn open source third party program called ''Revive'' allows for [[Oculus Rift]] games to be used with the HTC Vive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20160624/10114434814/oculus-reverses-drm-course-after-public-backlash.shtml|title=Oculus Reverses DRM Course After Public Backlash|newspaper=Techdirt.|access-date=2017-02-24}}</ref>\n\n== Adoption ==\n[[File:HTC Vive (2).jpg|thumb|right|An unmounted development unit.]]\nValve released its [[OpenVR]] [[software development kit]] (SDK), an updated version of its [[Steamworks]] VR [[Application programming interface|API]] with documentation and examples of how to build software that supports SteamVR hardware.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/04/30/valve-launches-openvr-dev-kit-for-virtaul-reality-hardware-makers/|title=Valve launches OpenVR dev kit for virtual reality hardware makers|publisher=[[VentureBeat]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first=Dean|last=Takahashi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/242401/Valve_launches_new_OpenVR_SDK_to_expand_SteamVR_development.php|title=Valve launches new OpenVR SDK to expand SteamVR development|work=[[Gamasutra]]|publisher=[[UBM plc]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015|first=Alex|last=Wawro}}</ref> It provides support for the HTC Vive Developer Edition, including the SteamVR controller and Lighthouse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vrfocus.com/archives/14559/valve-launches-openvr-sdk/|title=Valve Launches OpenVR SDK|publisher=VRFocus|date=1 May 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first=Jamie|last=Feltham}}</ref>\n\nSteamVR was launched with native support for [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]] on its platform.<ref name=\"unity-vive\">{{cite web|url=http://uploadvr.com/valve-is-bringing-native-unity-support-to-steamvr/|title=Valve Is Bringing Native Unity Support To SteamVR|website=uploadvr|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2015, [[Epic Games]] announced support for Valve's SteamVR technology, allowing developers to create VR projects with [[Unreal Engine 4]] for the HTC Vive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/4/30/8521469/steamvr-epic-unreal-engine-4-ue4-free|title=Now anyone can build for SteamVR with Epic's Unreal Engine 4|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first=Charlie|last=Hall}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/4/30/8519631/unreal-engine-4-steamvr-vive-support|title=Steam's virtual reality just got a boost from the maker of Unreal Tournament|work=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first1=Jacob|first2=Adi|last1=Kastrenakes|last2=Robertson}}</ref> Epic said that SteamVR is completely integrated into Unreal Engine 4 across Blueprint visual scripting and native code, meaning projects can be built without being dependent on programmer support if needed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unrealengine.com/blog/unreal-engine-4-releases-with-steamvr-support|title=Unreal Engine 4 Releases With SteamVR Support|website=Unreal Engine|publisher=[[Epic Games]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first=Dana|last=Cowley}}</ref> Epic's own ''Showdown'' tech demo can already be experienced on SteamVR using the Vive headset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/epic-unreal-engine-steamvr-valve,29023.html|title=Epic's Unreal Engine 4 Will Support Valve's SteamVR|work=[[Tom's Hardware]]|publisher=[[Purch]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=9 May 2015|first=Kevin|last=Parrish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadtovr.com/htc-vive-enabled-unreal-engine-4-8-coming-next-week-devs-can-start-work-with-rift-dk2/ |title=HTC Vive-enabled Unreal Engine 4.8 Coming next Week, Devs Can Start Work with Rift DK2|work=Road To VR|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first=Ben|last=Lang}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, VR news website Road to VR used game session figures from the Steam VR platform to estimate that approximately 100,000 Vive headsets had been shipped since launch.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Ben|title=HTC Vive Headset Nearing 100,000 Install Base, Steam Data Suggests |url=http://www.roadtovr.com/htc-vive-sales-figures-data-100000-steamspy-data/ |accessdate=4 August 2016|work=Road to VR|date=4 July 2016}}</ref> In the same month, [[SensoMotoric Instruments|SensoMotoric Instruments (SMI)]], a computer vision company, integrated its eye tracking technology in the HTC Vive to turn it into a dedicated eye tracking solution for research and professional applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uploadvr.com/smi-releases-eye-tracking-dev-kit-htc-vive/|title=SMI Releases Eye Tracking Developer Kit For The HTC Vive|publisher=[[UploadVR]]|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=26 September 2016|first=Joe|last=Durbin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vrfocus.com/2016/07/smi-reveals-eye-tracking-developer-kit-for-htc-vive/|title=SMI Reveals Eye Tracking Developer Kit for HTC Vive|publisher=VRFocus|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=26 September 2016|first=Peter|last=Graham}}</ref> In November 2016, Vive announced that it would begin the first retail sales of its headsets at JB Hi-Fi and Harvey Norman stores in Australia later that month.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bogle|first1=Ariel|title=HTC Vive's virtual reality headset is opening stores in Australia|url=http://mashable.com/2016/11/03/htc-vive-retail-stores/#F4EIJ2GKXOq7|accessdate=4 November 2016|publisher=Mashable|date=4 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 November 2016, HTC announced that the Vive was sold at a profit and that HTC Vive sales were \"much higher\" than 140,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadtovr.com/htc-vive-sold-at-profit-sales-figures-data-units-more-than-140000/|title=HTC Confirms Each Vive is Sold at Profit, \"Much More\" Than 140,000 Units in Sales|first=Ben|last=Lang|date=23 November 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Vive Pro ==\nOn 8 January 2018, HTC unveiled an upgraded Vive model known as '''HTC Vive Pro'''. It features higher-resolution displays, now at 1440x1600 resolution per eye, along with a second outward-facing camera, attachable headphones, a microphone for noise cancellation analysis, and a refreshed design with a more \"balanced\" form, lighter weight, and a sizing dial. The Vive Pro uses a [[USB 3.0]] (USB Type A) and a [[DisplayPort]] connector to connect to the PC.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vive.com/us/support/vive-pro-hmd/category_howto/connecting-the-headset-to-your-computer.html|title=Connecting the Vive Pro to the PC|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> A hidden [[USB-C]] connector can be used to connect an additional USB device to the Vive Pro HMD.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vive.com/us/support/vive-pro-hmd/category_howto/connecting-a-usb-device.html|title=Connecting a USB device to the Vive Pro|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> The Vive Pro is sold alongside the original as a high-end model, either as a full bundle or headset-only. The Vive Pro headset-only package is targeted towards existing Vive users, as Lighthouse base stations are required to use the headset, but not included in the package.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vive.com/us/product/vive-pro/|title=Website of HTC Vive Pro|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> Two different bundles are sold since April 2018:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vive.com/us/comparison/#|title=Product Comparison on Vive Website|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Vive Pro Starter Kit includes a Vive Pro Headset and the original SteamVR 1.0 Lighthouse base stations, as well as controllers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/04/03/vive-pro-starter-kit/|title=$1,099 Vive Pro Starter Kit has everything you need for VR but the PC|work=Engadget|access-date=2018-05-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe Vive Pro Full Kit includes a Vive Pro Headset and the more recent SteamVR 2.0 Lighthouse base stations, as well as controllers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.roadtovr.com/vive-pro-bundle-2-0-base-stations-controllers-priced-1500-japan-pre-tax/ |title=Vive Pro Bundle With 2.0 Base Stations & Controllers Now Available at $1400|last=Hayden|first=Scott|date=2018-04-23|work=Road to VR|access-date=2018-05-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe Vive Pro, that can be used both with SteamVR 1.0 and SteamVR 2.0 Lighthouse base stations, is compatible with all existing Vive accessories. However, not all Vive accessories support both available versions of the Lighthouse base stations. SteamVR 2.0 base stations can not be used in combination with the controllers shipped with the standard Vive Package and the initial Vive Trackers (before \"Vive Tracker 2018\").\nSteamVR 2.0 base stations enable the use of more than two base stations in one (optically undivided) room, allowing for a tracked space of up to 10 x 10 m in size.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2017/10/valve-announces-the-first-big-steamvr-2-0-feature-waaay-more-space/|title=Valve announces the first big SteamVR 2.0 feature: waaay more space|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2018-01-09 |language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/9/16866240/htc-vive-pro-vr-headset-hands-on-ces-2018|title=A closer look at HTC\u2019s new higher-resolution Vive Pro|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2018/01/htcs-vive-pro-will-add-more-pixels-to-an-otherwise-familiar-looking-vr-system/|title=HTC\u2019s Vive Pro will add more pixels to an otherwise familiar-looking VR system [Updated]|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2018-01-09|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n== Vive Pro Eye ==\nIn January 2019, at CES 2019 HTC unveiled an upgraded variant of HTC Vive Pro called Vive Pro Eye. The new device features built-in [[eye tracking]] that enables [[foveated rendering]] and hands-free interaction in VR and accessibility options for users who can't use regular motion controllers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/7/18172700/htc-vive-pro-eye-tracking-virtual-reality-headset-features-pricing-release-date-ces-2019|title=HTC announces new Vive Pro Eye virtual reality headset with native eye tracking|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2019-01-07|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref>\n\n== Vive Focus ==\nVive Focus is a self-contained (as opposed to tethered to a computer) headset first launched in China and then worldwide (in 37 countries) in November 2018. The headset introductory price in US was [[United States dollar|US$]]599.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/8/18075560/htc-vive-focus-standalone-vr-headset-pricing-release-date-shipping|title=HTC\u2019s China-exclusive Vive Focus VR headset is now launching worldwide|last=Robertson|first=Adi|date=2018-11-08|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref>\n\n== Vive Cosmos ==\nIn November 2018 HTC filed a \"Vive Cosmos\" trademark application.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uploadvr.com/htc-files-trademark-for-vive-cosmos-vr-equipment/|title=HTC Files Trademark For 'Vive Cosmos' VR Equipment|date=2018-11-19|website=UploadVR|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref> The headset was officially unveiled on January 7 in a very brief announcement at [[Consumer Electronics Show|CES]] 2019<ref name=\"The Verge 2019-01-07\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/7/18172740/htc-vive-cosmos-vr-headset-announce-ces-2019|title=HTC announces a PC-powered VR headset called the Vive Cosmos |last=Robertson |first=Adi |date=2019-01-07|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref> and via [https://twitter.com/htcvive/status/1082388742168403968 Twitter]. The presentation video showed a headset with a flip-up screen enabling user to see the real world without taking off the headset completely, four inside-out tracking cameras (two in the front and one on each side) and two handset motion controllers, built in headphones, and a removable faceplate containing two cameras.<ref name=\"The Verge 2019-01-07\" /> In late 2019, it was revealed that HTC will be making two additional Vive Cosmos models, alongside the original, the Vive Cosmos Play, a lower cost version of the Cosmos with a faceplate without any cameras, lowering the tracking ability of the headset, and no headphones, and the HTC Vive Cosmos Elite which featured a faceplate that supports SteamVR 2.0 tracking and included two original Vive controllers and base stations. In March 2020 HTC released a version of the Vive Cosmos Elite which only included the headset, without the controllers and basestations, and in April 2020, HTC released the HTC Vive Cosmos External Tracking Faceplate, which would allow users to use SteamVR 2.0 on a Vive Cosmos or Vive Cosmos Play, without replacing the entire headset.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coming Soon: Cosmos Elite Headset (HMD Only) and External Tracking Faceplate, both with Half-Life: Alyx |url=https://blog.vive.com/us/2020/03/30/cosmoselite/?site=uk |website=VIVE Blog |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|HTC Vive}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.htcvive.com/}}\n\n{{Mixed reality}}\n{{Valve}}\n\n[[Category:Computer peripherals]]\n[[Category:HTC Corporation]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2016]]\n[[Category:Valve Corporation]]\n[[Category:Virtual reality headsets]]\n[[Category:HTC Vive]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox\n| title = HTC Vive\n| image = [[File:Vive pre.jpeg|upright=1.1|frameless]]\n| caption = An HTC Vive head-mounted display with a camera near the bottom rim; two wireless handheld controllers; and two 'Lighthouse' basestations\n| label1 = Type\n| data1 = [[Virtual reality headset]] for room scale virtual reality\n| label2 = Release date\n| data2 = 5 April 2016\n| label4 = Manufacturer\n| data4 = [[HTC]], with technology by [[Valve Corporation|Valve]]\n| label5 = Display technology\n| data5 = [[PenTile matrix family|PenTile]]<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/03/ask-ars-i-cant-choose-between-oculus-rift-htc-vive-and-playstation-vr/ | first = Lee | last = Hutchinson | title = Ask Ars: I can\u2019t choose between Oculus Rift, HTC Vive, and PlayStation VR! | date = 22 March 2016 | access-date = 24 September 2016 | work = Ars Technica}}</ref> [[OLED]]\n| label6 = Resolution\n| data6 = 2160\u00d71200 (1080\u00d71200 per eye)<ref name=\"HTC Re Vive\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vive.com/us/|title=VIVE\u2122 &#124; Discover Virtual Reality Beyond Imagination|website=www.vive.com}}</ref>\n| label7 = Refresh rate\n| data7 = 90 Hz<ref name=\"HTC Re Vive\"/>\n| label8 = Field of view (Nominal)\n| data8 = About 110 degrees<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alex.vlachos.com/graphics/Alex_Vlachos_Advanced_VR_Rendering_GDC2015.pdf|title=Advanced VR Rendering, Alex Vlachos, Valve}}</ref>\n| label9 = Tracking system\n| data9 = Lighthouse (2 base stations emitting pulsed IR lasers)\n| label10 = Input\n| data10 = Video/data/Bluetooth\n| label11 = Weight\n| data11 = 470 grams (previously 555 grams)\n| label12 = Platform/operating system\n| data12 = SteamVR running on [[Microsoft Windows]] in addition to [[Linux]] support, with [[macOS]] support coming<ref name=\"Machkovech\">{{Cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2017/06/steamvr-is-coming-to-mac-and-apple-says-it-will-actually-work/ | title = SteamVR is coming to Mac\u2014and Apple says it will actually work | first = Sam | last= Machkovech | date =5 June 2017 | accessdate = 5 June 2017 | work = [[Ars Technica]] }}</ref>\n| label13 = Connection\n| data13 = 1\u00d7 [[HDMI|HDMI 1.4]] or DisplayPort 1.2 and 1\u00d7 [[USB 3.0]]\n| label14 = Website\n| data14 = {{url|http://www.vive.com/}}\n| label15 = Introductory price\n| data15 = [[United States dollar|US$]]799/[[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]689\n| label16 = Sound\n| data16 = {{plainlist|\n* 3.5 mm [[audio jack]] for headphones\n* Built-in microphone\n* Headphones will be sold separately from June 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/htcs-deluxe-audio-strap-is-a-huge-improvement-over-the-vives-elastic-straps/|title=HTC's Deluxe Audio Strap is a huge improvement over the Vive's elastic straps|first=Wes|last=Fenlon|date=1 March 2017}}</ref>}}\n| label17 = Controller input\n| data17 = SteamVR wireless motion tracked controllers\n| label18 = Camera\n| data18 = Front-facing camera - enabling users to view the external world and a key component of the device\u2019s 'chaperone' safety system.\n}}\n\nThe '''HTC Vive''' is a [[virtual reality headset]] developed by [[HTC]] and [[Valve Corporation|Valve]]. The headset uses \"[[room scale]]\" tracking technology, allowing the user to move in 3D space and use motion-tracked handheld controllers to interact with the environment.<ref name=verge-vive>{{cite web|title=Valve's VR headset is called the Vive and it's made by HTC|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/3/1/8127445/htc-vive-valve-vr-headset|website=The Verge|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe HTC Vive was unveiled during HTC's [[Mobile World Congress]] keynote in March 2015. Development kits were sent out in August and September 2015,{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} and the first consumer version of the device was released in April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.htc.com/us/newsroom/2016-06-07/|title=VIVE NOW SHIPPING IMMEDIATELY FROM HTC, RETAIL PARTNERS EXPAND DEMO LOCATIONS|last=|first=|date=|website=www.htc.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nPrototypes of a Valve-produced virtual reality system were demonstrated during 2014. On 23 February 2015, Valve announced SteamVR and that it would demonstrate a \"SteamVR hardware system\" at the 2015 [[Game Developers Conference]].<ref name=engadget-steamvr>{{cite web|title=Valve is making a VR headset and its own Steam Machine|url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/02/23/steamvr-valve-virtual-reality-gdc/|website=Engadget|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=verge-gdcsteamvr>{{cite web|title=Valve showing off new virtual reality hardware and updated Steam controller next week|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/2/23/8094817/valve-virtual-reality-hardware-gdc-2015|website=The Verge|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=verge-valvevr>{{cite web|title=Valve's VR headset revealed with Oculus-like features|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/6/3/5775220/valve-vr-headset-pictures-concept-features|website=The Verge|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref> HTC officially unveiled its device, Vive, during its [[Mobile World Congress]] keynote on 1 March 2015.<ref name=verge-vive/>  Preorders started on 29 February 2016 at 10:00&nbsp;a.m. EST.<ref>{{Cite web|title = HTC Vive pre-orders to start on February 29|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/12092607/HTC-Vive-pre-orders-to-start-on-February-29.html|website = Telegraph.co.uk|access-date = 22 January 2016}}</ref> Valve and HTC have since announced that the headset will be free for selected developers.<ref name=theverge-steamvrfree>{{cite web|title=Valve, HTC Offering Free Vive VR to Developers|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2479252,00.asp|website=The Verge|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Consumer Electronics Show]] 2016, HTC and Valve unveiled a near-final hardware revision of the device, known as HTC Vive Pre.<ref name=ars-vivepre>{{cite web|title=HTC Vive Pre impressions: A great VR system has only gotten better|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2016/01/htc-vive-pre-impressions-a-great-vr-system-has-only-gotten-better/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=28 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDuring his Immersed 2015 keynote, Phil Chen, Chief Content Officer for HTC and founder of the HTC Vive, explained that he \"stumbled upon VR\" and later, HTC met Valve, which turned out to be \"serendipity\".<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KZS6nCKPUDs&t=11m55s|time=11m55s|title=MTBS-TV: Conversing With Phil Chen, Chief Content Officer, HTC|via=YouTube|author=Neil Schneider|date= 8 October 2015}}</ref> Chen also explained that HTC and Valve don't have a clear dividing line between each of their responsibilities, and HTC is very much a partner in the research and development process.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KZS6nCKPUDs&t=16m46s|time=16m46s|title=MTBS-TV: Conversing With Phil Chen, Chief Content Officer, HTC|via=YouTube|author=Neil Schneider|date= 8 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, HTC announced the release of their 'Business Edition' of the Vive for US$1,200 which would include a Professional Use License, a 12-month Commercial Warranty, access to an exclusive support line, a 5-meter (16&nbsp;ft) cable extension kit, and it included the [https://xinreality.com/wiki/HTC_Vive_Deluxe_Audio_Strap Deluxe Audio Strap].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.roadtovr.com/htc-announces-vive-business-edition-for-1200/ |title=HTC Announces Vive 'Business Edition' for $1200 |last=Hayden|first=Scott|date=2016-06-09|work=Road to VR|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vive.com/us/enterprise/|title=VIVE {{!}} Business Edition and Commercial VR|website=www.vive.com|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, HTC announced a tether-less VR upgrade kit made by TPCAST. A public model was shown at [http://www.techradar.com/news/ces-dates-news-reviews-and-videos CES 2017] and had a price of $249.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uploadvr.com/tpcast-wireless-vive-kit-works/|title=Hands-on: TPCAST's Wireless Vive Kit Really Works|date=2016-12-19|newspaper=UploadVR|access-date=2017-02-24|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/ces/2017/1/4/14172296/htc-vive-wireless-adapter-tpcast-ces-2017|title=HTC\u2019s wireless Vive add-on actually works|last=Byford|first=Sam|newspaper=The Verge|access-date=2017-02-24}}</ref>\n\nAt Google I/O in May 2017, Google announced a new, all in-built 'Standalone VR' system that would be made by the Vive team and also by Lenovo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vrfocus.com/2017/05/google-announces-standalone-headset-to-be-made-by-htc-and-lenovo/|title=Google Announces Standalone Headset to be Made by HTC and Lenovo|date=2017-05-17|website=VRFocus|access-date=2017-05-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Whilst in June 2017 Valve revealed details of a second variation of Vive controller which utilizes finger tracking called the Knuckles Vive controller.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vrfocus.com/2017/06/valve-provides-details-on-upcoming-knuckles-vive-controllers/|title=Valve Provides Details on Upcoming Knuckles Vive Controllers|date=2017-06-22|website=VRFocus|access-date=2017-06-22|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Hardware and accessories ==\n* '''Vive Headset''': The Vive headset has a [[refresh rate]] of 90&nbsp;[[Hertz|Hz]] and a 110 degree field of view. The device uses two [[OLED]] panels, one per eye, each having a [[display resolution]] of 1080\u00d71200 (2160\u00d71200 combined pixels).<ref name=\"gamespot-steamvr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/valve-and-htc-reveal-vive-vr-headset/1100-6425606/|title=Valve and HTC reveal Vive VR headset|website=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref> Safety features include a front-facing camera that allows the user to observe their surroundings without removing their headset. The software can also use the camera to identify any moving or static objects in a room; this functionality can be used as part of a \"Chaperone\" safety system, which will automatically display a virtual wall or a feed from the camera to safely guide users from obstacles or real-world walls.<ref name=\"ars-vivepre\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomsguide.com/us/htc-vive-interview,news-21356.html|title=HTC: Why Vive Will Beat Oculus VR at Its Own Game|website=Tom's Guide|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref> Inside the headset's outer-shell divots are dozens of infrared sensors that detect the base stations' IR pulses to determine the headset's current location in a space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gizmodo.com/this-is-how-valve-s-amazing-lighthouse-tracking-technol-1705356768|title=This Is How Valve\u2019s Amazing Lighthouse Tracking Technology Works|last=Buckley|first=Sean|work=Gizmodo|access-date=2017-11-21|language=en-US}}</ref> Other sensors include a [[G-Sensor]], [[gyroscope]] and [[Proximity sensor|proximity]] sensor.<ref name=\"vive.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vive.com/us/product/vive-virtual-reality-system/|title=VIVE\u2122 {{!}} VIVE Virtual Reality System|website=www.vive.com|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref>\n* '''Vive Controllers''': The controllers have multiple input methods including a track pad, grip buttons, and a dual-stage trigger and a use per charge of about 6 hours.<ref name=\"vive.com\"/> Across the ring of the controller are 24 infrared sensors that detect the base stations to determine the location of the controller.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vrheads.com/exposing-magic-behind-htc-vive-controller|title=Exploring the magic behind the HTC Vive controller|work=VRHeads|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref> The SteamVR Tracking system is used to track the controller location to a fraction of a millimeter, with update rates ranging from 250&nbsp;Hz to 1&nbsp;kHz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://partner.steamgames.com/vrlicensing|title=Welcome to Steamworks|website=partner.steamgames.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-21}}</ref>\n* '''Vive Base Stations''': Also known as the Lighthouse tracking system are two black boxes that create a 360 degree virtual space. The base stations emit timed infrared pulses at 60 pulses per second that are then picked up by the headset and controllers with sub-millimeter precision.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.roadtovr.com/latest-vive-shipping-with-tweaked-base-stations-redesigned-packaging/|title=Latest HTC Vives Are Shipping with Tweaked Base Stations, Redesigned Packaging |last=Lang|first=Ben|date=2017-04-13|work=Road to VR|access-date=2017-11-21|language=en-US}}</ref> Wireless syncing lowers the amount of wires as well standard threading making the base stations practical to use in a home.<ref name=\"vive.com\"/>\n* '''Vive Tracker''': A motion tracking accessory; it is designed to be attached to physical accessories and controllers, so that they can be tracked via the Lighthouse system. Vive Trackers feature a connector that can be used to communicate with the accessory it is attached to. On launch, the Vive Tracker was sold as a standalone product, and in bundles with accessories and games designed to integrate with it, such as the Hyper Blaster (a [[light gun]]-style controller), and a [[racquet]] designed for sports games. Other third-party accessories have been developed for use with Vive Trackers, such as bands designed to be attached to a user's arms or legs to enable body tracking.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/11/16/16664916/htc-vive-tracker-bundles-date-price|title=HTC launches Vive tracker bundles|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vrheads.com/everything-we-know-about-vive-tracker|title=Everything you need to know about the Vive Tracker|work=VRHeads|access-date=2017-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/16/htc-vive-tracker-hands-on/|title=HTC's Vive Tracker adds much-needed tactile control to VR|work=Engadget|access-date=2017-11-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* '''Vive Deluxe Audio Strap''': In June 2017, HTC released the Deluxe Audio Strap for US$99. It added integrated over-ear headphones as well as improved the HMD's comfort through better weight distribution.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/2/27/14748876/htc-vive-deluxe-audio-strap-tracker-price-availability|title=HTC\u2019s Vive Deluxe Audio Strap is coming in June for $99.99|work=The Verge|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vive.com/us/vive-deluxe-audio-strap/|title=VIVE\u2122 {{!}} Vive Deluxe Audio Strap|website=www.vive.com|access-date=2017-12-19}}</ref>\n* '''Vive Wireless Adapter''': The Vive Wireless Adapter was launched as an accessory in September 2018 for the original Vive and Vive Pro. It allows to connect the Headset with the Computer wirelessly. The Wireless Adapter is priced at $300 for Vive and $360 for Vive Pro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vive.com/us/wireless-adapter/|title=Wirelss Adapter on Vive Webpage|website=www.vive.com|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.roadtovr.com/htc-vive-wireless-adapter-release-date-price/ |title=Vive Wireless Adapter now available |last=Lang|first=Ben|date=2018-09-24|work=Road to VR|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n* '''Valve Index Controllers''': The Vive can use the [[Valve Index]] controllers (known during development as Knuckle Controllers) developed by [[Valve Corporation|Valve]].\n\nThe Vive initially required computers running [[Microsoft Windows]]. In February 2017, support was added for [[Linux]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/02/22/valve-launches-steamvr-support-for-linux/|title=Valve launches SteamVR support for Linux|website=Engadget|access-date=2017-06-26}}</ref> followed by support for [[MacOS]] in June 2017.<ref name=\"Machkovech\"/>\n\n== Games ==\n{{main|List of HTC Vive games}}\nBy March 2016, the time at which the pre-orders for the HTC Vive opened, 107 games were known to be coming to the virtual reality format.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Finder|url=http://www.finder.com.au/gaming/complete-list-of-htc-vive-vr-games/|title=107 games revealed ahead of HTC Vive pre-order launch|date=29 March 2015|accessdate=29 February 2016|first=Chris|last=Stead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619210337/https://www.finder.com.au/gaming/complete-list-of-htc-vive-vr-games|archive-date=19 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017 Valve CEO [[Gabe Newell]] announced via Reddit AMA 'ask me anything'  session Valve is developing three AAA VR IPs. Ultimately, in November 2019, Valve announced ''[[Half-Life: Alyx]]'' as its flagship VR title for the Vive and its own [[Valve Index]] headset, to be released in March 2020, though the game will support all headsets compatible with the SteamVR protocol.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2019/11/21/20975860/valve-half-life-alyx-release-date-vr-announcement-first-screens-trailer | title = Half-Life: Alyx is Valve\u2019s VR-exclusive, full-length prequel to Half-Life 2 | first=  Michael | last = McWhertor | date = November 21, 2019 | accessdate = November 21, 2019 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\nAn open source third party program called ''Revive'' allows for [[Oculus Rift]] games to be used with the HTC Vive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20160624/10114434814/oculus-reverses-drm-course-after-public-backlash.shtml|title=Oculus Reverses DRM Course After Public Backlash|newspaper=Techdirt.|access-date=2017-02-24}}</ref>\n\n== Adoption ==\n[[File:HTC Vive (2).jpg|thumb|right|An unmounted development unit.]]\nValve released its [[OpenVR]] [[software development kit]] (SDK), an updated version of its [[Steamworks]] VR [[Application programming interface|API]] with documentation and examples of how to build software that supports SteamVR hardware.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/04/30/valve-launches-openvr-dev-kit-for-virtaul-reality-hardware-makers/|title=Valve launches OpenVR dev kit for virtual reality hardware makers|publisher=[[VentureBeat]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first=Dean|last=Takahashi}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/242401/Valve_launches_new_OpenVR_SDK_to_expand_SteamVR_development.php|title=Valve launches new OpenVR SDK to expand SteamVR development|work=[[Gamasutra]]|publisher=[[UBM plc]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=8 May 2015|first=Alex|last=Wawro}}</ref> It provides support for the HTC Vive Developer Edition, including the SteamVR controller and Lighthouse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vrfocus.com/archives/14559/valve-launches-openvr-sdk/|title=Valve Launches OpenVR SDK|publisher=VRFocus|date=1 May 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first=Jamie|last=Feltham}}</ref>\n\nSteamVR was launched with native support for [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]] on its platform.<ref name=\"unity-vive\">{{cite web|url=http://uploadvr.com/valve-is-bringing-native-unity-support-to-steamvr/|title=Valve Is Bringing Native Unity Support To SteamVR|website=uploadvr|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2015, [[Epic Games]] announced support for Valve's SteamVR technology, allowing developers to create VR projects with [[Unreal Engine 4]] for the HTC Vive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/4/30/8521469/steamvr-epic-unreal-engine-4-ue4-free|title=Now anyone can build for SteamVR with Epic's Unreal Engine 4|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first=Charlie|last=Hall}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/4/30/8519631/unreal-engine-4-steamvr-vive-support|title=Steam's virtual reality just got a boost from the maker of Unreal Tournament|work=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first1=Jacob|first2=Adi|last1=Kastrenakes|last2=Robertson}}</ref> Epic said that SteamVR is completely integrated into Unreal Engine 4 across Blueprint visual scripting and native code, meaning projects can be built without being dependent on programmer support if needed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unrealengine.com/blog/unreal-engine-4-releases-with-steamvr-support|title=Unreal Engine 4 Releases With SteamVR Support|website=Unreal Engine|publisher=[[Epic Games]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first=Dana|last=Cowley}}</ref> Epic's own ''Showdown'' tech demo can already be experienced on SteamVR using the Vive headset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/epic-unreal-engine-steamvr-valve,29023.html|title=Epic's Unreal Engine 4 Will Support Valve's SteamVR|work=[[Tom's Hardware]]|publisher=[[Purch]]|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=9 May 2015|first=Kevin|last=Parrish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadtovr.com/htc-vive-enabled-unreal-engine-4-8-coming-next-week-devs-can-start-work-with-rift-dk2/ |title=HTC Vive-enabled Unreal Engine 4.8 Coming next Week, Devs Can Start Work with Rift DK2|work=Road To VR|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|first=Ben|last=Lang}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, VR news website Road to VR used game session figures from the Steam VR platform to estimate that approximately 100,000 Vive headsets had been shipped since launch.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Ben|title=HTC Vive Headset Nearing 100,000 Install Base, Steam Data Suggests |url=http://www.roadtovr.com/htc-vive-sales-figures-data-100000-steamspy-data/ |accessdate=4 August 2016|work=Road to VR|date=4 July 2016}}</ref> In the same month, [[SensoMotoric Instruments|SensoMotoric Instruments (SMI)]], a computer vision company, integrated its eye tracking technology in the HTC Vive to turn it into a dedicated eye tracking solution for research and professional applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uploadvr.com/smi-releases-eye-tracking-dev-kit-htc-vive/|title=SMI Releases Eye Tracking Developer Kit For The HTC Vive|publisher=[[UploadVR]]|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=26 September 2016|first=Joe|last=Durbin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vrfocus.com/2016/07/smi-reveals-eye-tracking-developer-kit-for-htc-vive/|title=SMI Reveals Eye Tracking Developer Kit for HTC Vive|publisher=VRFocus|date=22 July 2016|accessdate=26 September 2016|first=Peter|last=Graham}}</ref> In November 2016, Vive announced that it would begin the first retail sales of its headsets at JB Hi-Fi and Harvey Norman stores in Australia later that month.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bogle|first1=Ariel|title=HTC Vive's virtual reality headset is opening stores in Australia|url=http://mashable.com/2016/11/03/htc-vive-retail-stores/#F4EIJ2GKXOq7|accessdate=4 November 2016|publisher=Mashable|date=4 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 November 2016, HTC announced that the Vive was sold at a profit and that HTC Vive sales were \"much higher\" than 140,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadtovr.com/htc-vive-sold-at-profit-sales-figures-data-units-more-than-140000/|title=HTC Confirms Each Vive is Sold at Profit, \"Much More\" Than 140,000 Units in Sales|first=Ben|last=Lang|date=23 November 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Vive Pro ==\nOn 8 January 2018, HTC unveiled an upgraded Vive model known as '''HTC Vive Pro'''. It features higher-resolution displays, now at 1440x1600 resolution per eye, along with a second outward-facing camera, attachable headphones, a microphone for noise cancellation analysis, and a refreshed design with a more \"balanced\" form, lighter weight, and a sizing dial. The Vive Pro uses a [[USB 3.0]] (USB Type A) and a [[DisplayPort]] connector to connect to the PC.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vive.com/us/support/vive-pro-hmd/category_howto/connecting-the-headset-to-your-computer.html|title=Connecting the Vive Pro to the PC|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> A hidden [[USB-C]] connector can be used to connect an additional USB device to the Vive Pro HMD.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vive.com/us/support/vive-pro-hmd/category_howto/connecting-a-usb-device.html|title=Connecting a USB device to the Vive Pro|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> The Vive Pro is sold alongside the original as a high-end model, either as a full bundle or headset-only. The Vive Pro headset-only package is targeted towards existing Vive users, as Lighthouse base stations are required to use the headset, but not included in the package.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vive.com/us/product/vive-pro/|title=Website of HTC Vive Pro|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> Two different bundles are sold since April 2018:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vive.com/us/comparison/#|title=Product Comparison on Vive Website|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Vive Pro Starter Kit includes a Vive Pro Headset and the original SteamVR 1.0 Lighthouse base stations, as well as controllers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/04/03/vive-pro-starter-kit/|title=$1,099 Vive Pro Starter Kit has everything you need for VR but the PC|work=Engadget|access-date=2018-05-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe Vive Pro Full Kit includes a Vive Pro Headset and the more recent SteamVR 2.0 Lighthouse base stations, as well as controllers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.roadtovr.com/vive-pro-bundle-2-0-base-stations-controllers-priced-1500-japan-pre-tax/ |title=Vive Pro Bundle With 2.0 Base Stations & Controllers Now Available at $1400|last=Hayden|first=Scott|date=2018-04-23|work=Road to VR|access-date=2018-05-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe Vive Pro, that can be used both with SteamVR 1.0 and SteamVR 2.0 Lighthouse base stations, is compatible with all existing Vive accessories. However, not all Vive accessories support both available versions of the Lighthouse base stations. SteamVR 2.0 base stations can not be used in combination with the controllers shipped with the standard Vive Package and the initial Vive Trackers (before \"Vive Tracker 2018\").\nSteamVR 2.0 base stations enable the use of more than two base stations in one (optically undivided) room, allowing for a tracked space of up to 10 x 10 m in size.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2017/10/valve-announces-the-first-big-steamvr-2-0-feature-waaay-more-space/|title=Valve announces the first big SteamVR 2.0 feature: waaay more space|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2018-01-09 |language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/9/16866240/htc-vive-pro-vr-headset-hands-on-ces-2018|title=A closer look at HTC\u2019s new higher-resolution Vive Pro|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2018/01/htcs-vive-pro-will-add-more-pixels-to-an-otherwise-familiar-looking-vr-system/|title=HTC\u2019s Vive Pro will add more pixels to an otherwise familiar-looking VR system [Updated]|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2018-01-09|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n== Vive Pro Eye ==\nIn January 2019, at CES 2019 HTC unveiled an upgraded variant of HTC Vive Pro called Vive Pro Eye. The new device features built-in [[eye tracking]] that enables [[foveated rendering]] and hands-free interaction in VR and accessibility options for users who can't use regular motion controllers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/7/18172700/htc-vive-pro-eye-tracking-virtual-reality-headset-features-pricing-release-date-ces-2019|title=HTC announces new Vive Pro Eye virtual reality headset with native eye tracking|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2019-01-07|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref>\n\n== Vive Focus ==\nVive Focus is a self-contained (as opposed to tethered to a computer) headset first launched in China and then worldwide (in 37 countries) in November 2018. The headset introductory price in US was [[United States dollar|US$]]599.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/8/18075560/htc-vive-focus-standalone-vr-headset-pricing-release-date-shipping|title=HTC\u2019s China-exclusive Vive Focus VR headset is now launching worldwide|last=Robertson|first=Adi|date=2018-11-08|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref>\n\n== Vive Cosmos ==\nIn November 2018 HTC filed a \"Vive Cosmos\" trademark application.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uploadvr.com/htc-files-trademark-for-vive-cosmos-vr-equipment/|title=HTC Files Trademark For 'Vive Cosmos' VR Equipment|date=2018-11-19|website=UploadVR|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref> The headset was officially unveiled on January 7 in a very brief announcement at [[Consumer Electronics Show|CES]] 2019<ref name=\"The Verge 2019-01-07\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/7/18172740/htc-vive-cosmos-vr-headset-announce-ces-2019|title=HTC announces a PC-powered VR headset called the Vive Cosmos |last=Robertson |first=Adi |date=2019-01-07|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref> and via [https://twitter.com/htcvive/status/1082388742168403968 Twitter]. The presentation video showed a headset with a flip-up screen enabling user to see the real world without taking off the headset completely, four inside-out tracking cameras (two in the front and one on each side) and two handset motion controllers, built in headphones, and a removable faceplate containing two cameras.<ref name=\"The Verge 2019-01-07\" /> In late 2019, it was revealed that HTC will be making two additional Vive Cosmos models, alongside the original, the Vive Cosmos Play, a lower cost version of the Cosmos with a faceplate without any cameras, lowering the tracking ability of the headset, and no headphones, and the HTC Vive Cosmos Elite which featured a faceplate that supports SteamVR 2.0 tracking and included two original Vive controllers and base stations. In March 2020 HTC released a version of the Vive Cosmos Elite which only included the headset, without the controllers and basestations, and in April 2020, HTC released the HTC Vive Cosmos External Tracking Faceplate, which would allow users to use SteamVR 2.0 on a Vive Cosmos or Vive Cosmos Play, without replacing the entire headset.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|HTC Vive}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.htcvive.com/}}\n\n{{Mixed reality}}\n{{Valve}}\n\n[[Category:Computer peripherals]]\n[[Category:HTC Corporation]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2016]]\n[[Category:Valve Corporation]]\n[[Category:Virtual reality headsets]]\n[[Category:HTC Vive]]\n", "name_user": "TheLMGN", "label": "safe", "comment": "cite my sources", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTC_Vive"}
{"title_page": "Stratification (seeds)", "text_new": "{{Missing information|different types of stratification, such as warm moist stratification|date=September 2016}}\n{{manual|date=September 2016}}\n{{refimprove| date=December 2009}}\n\nIn horticulture, '''stratification''' is a process of treating [[seeds]] to simulate natural conditions that the seeds must experience before [[germination]] can occur. Many seed species have an embryonic [[Seed dormancy|dormancy]] phase, and generally will not sprout until this dormancy is broken.<ref name=backyardagora>{{cite web\n | title = Stratification (botany)\n | url=http://www.backyardagora.com/glossary/stratification.htm \n | publisher=Backyard Agora\n | accessdate = June 20, 2017\n}}</ref>\n\nThe term '''stratification''' can be traced back to at least 1664 in ''[[Sylva, or A Discourse of Forest-Trees and the Propagation of Timber]]'',<ref>\n{{Citation\n| last1  = Evelyn\n| first1 = J.\n| title     = Sylva, or A Discourse of Forest-Trees and the Propagation of Timber in His Majesties Dominions\n| publisher = Arthur Doubleday & Co., Ltd\n| place     = London\n| orig-year = 1664\n| volume  = II\n| year    = 1908\n}}\n</ref> where seeds were layered (stratified) between layers of moist soil and exposing these strata to winter conditions. Thus, stratification became the process by which seeds were artificially exposed to conditions to encourage subsequent germination.\n\n==Cold stratification==\nCold stratification is the process of subjecting seeds to both cold and moist conditions. Seeds of many trees, shrubs and perennials require these conditions before germination will ensue.\n\n===In the wild===\nIn the wild, [[seed dormancy]] is usually overcome by the seed spending time in the ground through a winter period and having its hard seed coat softened up by frost and weathering action. By doing so the seed is undergoing a natural form of \"cold stratification\" or pretreatment. This cold moist period triggers the seed's [[embryo]]; its growth and subsequent expansion eventually break through the softened seed coat in its search for sun and nutrients.\n\n===Process===\nIn its most basic form, when the stratification process is controlled, the pretreatment amounts to nothing more than subjecting the seeds to storage in a cool (ideally +1\u00b0 to +3\u00b0C; not freezing) and moist environment for a period found to be sufficient for the species in question. This period of time may vary from one to three months.\n\nTo accomplish this seeds are placed in a sealed plastic bag with moistened [[vermiculite]] (or [[sand]] or even a moistened paper towel), which is refrigerated. Three times as much [[vermiculite]] as seeds is used. It is important to only slightly dampen the vermiculite, as excessive moisture can cause the seeds to [[Mold (fungus)|mold]] in the bag.<ref name=backyardagora/>\n\nSoaking the seeds in cold water for 6\u201312 hours immediately before placing them in cold stratification can cut down on the amount of time needed for stratification, as the seed needs to absorb some moisture to enable the chemical changes that take place.\n\nAfter undergoing the recommended period of stratification, the seeds are ready to be removed and sown in the nursery bed for germination.\n\nAlternatively, the seed may be sown in small pots filled with moist soil and then the whole thing enclosed inside a plastic bag before placing inside a common refrigerator.\n\n===Preparing a stratifying medium===\nMany sources recommend using [[peat]], a combination of peat and [[sand]], or [[vermiculite]] as the medium for cold stratifying seeds.<ref>{{cite web\n | last = Dan\n  | first = Meyer\n  | title = Growing Wisconsin Trees From Seed \n  | url=http://forest.wisc.edu/sites/default/files/pdfs/publications/66.PDF\n  | accessdate = 2008-07-01\n| publisher=University of Wisconsin College of Agricultural and Life Sciences}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n| url=http://www.ipm.iastate.edu/ipm/hortnews/2000/8-11-2000/germtreeseed.html\n| title=Germination of Tree Seed\n| publisher=University of Iowa Extension\n| accessdate= 2008-07-01\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.monarchlab.org/Lab/Rearing/GrowingMilkweed.aspx\n| publisher=University of Minnesota Monarch Lab\n| title=Growing Milkweed\n}}</ref> The medium must be sterile to prevent harm to the [[seed]] by [[pathogens]] including [[fungi]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.actahort.org/members/showpdf?booknrarnr=574_50\n| title=Dependency of Lingonberry Seed Germinating Ability on Seed Age and Storage Method\n| first=T.\n| last=Paal\n| publisher=International Society for Horticultural Science\n}}</ref>\n\n==Preparing the seed==\nThe seeds should be cleaned of any additional material ([[fruit]] pulp, [[leaf]] and seed-pod fragments, [[conifer cone|cone]] scales, etc.), but the shells of [[nut (fruit)|nuts]] should not be removed.\n\n==Warm and cold stratification==\nAny seeds that are indicated as needing a period of warm stratification followed by cold stratification should be subjected to the same measures, but the seeds should additionally be stratified in a warm area first, followed by the cold period in a refrigerator later. Warm stratification requires temperatures of 15-20\u00b0C (59-68\u00b0F). In many instances, warm stratification followed by cold stratification requirements can also be met by planting the seeds in summer in a mulched bed for expected germination the following spring. Some seeds may not germinate until the second spring.\n\n==Use of fungicide==\nUse of a [[fungicide]] to moisten the stratifying vermiculite will help prevent fungal diseases. [[Chinosol]] ([[8-quinolyl potassium sulfate]]<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/23672298\n| publisher=National Center for Biotechnology Information\n| title=Chinosol [German]\n| accessdate = June 21, 2017\n}}</ref>) is one such fungicide used to inhibit ''Botrytis cinerea'' infections.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.piwine.com/chinosol.html\n| publisher=Presque Isle Wine Cellars \n| title=Chinosol Fungicide\n| accessdate = June 21, 2017\n}}</ref> \n\nDifferent seeds should be placed in different bags rather than putting them all into one bag, and large quantities are also best split into several small bags. That way any fungal outbreak will be restricted to only some seeds. If no fungicide is used, a close check should be kept on the seeds, removing any which show signs of mold or become soft and with a decaying smell.\n\nIf an outbreak of fungus occurs, remove the seeds and re-apply fungicide, then place them in a new bag with new slightly moistened [[vermiculite]]. Always keep the bag sealed. The stratifying seeds should be checked on a regular basis for either fungus or germination. If any seeds germinate while in the refrigerator, they should be removed and sown.\n\n==Sowing and seedlings==\nThe medium/soil is not critical as long as the soil is light as well as lightly firmed down but not heavily compacted. Sterilized potting soil will minimize problems with ''[[Botryotinia|Botrytis]]'' or ''[[Pythium]]'' fungal disease. These problems are much more likely to occur if air circulation is poor.\n\nMost seeds need only be planted at a depth equal to their own thickness in order to germinate. Seeds planted outdoors are best planted a little deeper to avoid disturbance caused by heavy rainfall. The soil should be slightly damp but never soaking wet, nor allowed to dry out completely.\n\nMost [[seedling]]s, whether grown in pots or beds, benefit from good air circulation which discourages fungus growth and promotes sturdy stems.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Scarification (botany)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stratification (Botany)}}\n[[Category:Horticulture and gardening]]\n[[Category:Plant reproduction]]\n", "text_old": "{{Missing information|different types of stratification, such as warm moist stratification|date=September 2016}}\n{{manual|date=September 2016}}\n{{refimprove| date=December 2009}}\n\nIn horticulture, '''stratification''' is a process of treating [[seeds]] to simulate natural conditions that the seeds must experience before [[germination]] can occur. Many seed species have an embryonic [[Seed dormancy|dormancy]] phase, and generally will not sprout until this dormancy is broken.<ref name=backyardagora>{{cite web\n | title = Stratification (botany)\n | url=http://www.backyardagora.com/glossary/stratification.htm \n | publisher=Backyard Agora\n | accessdate = June 20, 2017\n}}</ref>\n\nThe term '''stratification''' can be traced back to at least 1664 in ''[[Sylva, or A Discourse of Forest-Trees and the Propagation of Timber]]'',<ref>\n{{Citation\n| last1  = Evelyn\n| first1 = J.\n| title     = Sylva, or A Discourse of Forest-Trees and the Propagation of Timber in His Majesties Dominions\n| publisher = Arthur Doubleday & Co., Ltd\n| place     = London\n| orig-year = 1664\n| volume  = II\n| year    = 1908\n}}\n</ref> where seeds were layered (stratified) between layers of moist soil and exposing these strata to winter conditions. Thus, stratification became the process by which seeds were artificially exposed to conditions to encourage subsequent germination.\n\n==Cold stratification==\nCold stratification is the process of subjecting seeds to both cold and moist conditions. Seeds of many trees, shrubs and perennials require these conditions before germination will ensue.\n\n===In the wild===\nIn the wild, [[seed dormancy]] is usually overcome by the seed spending time in the ground through a winter period and having its hard seed coat softened up by frost and weathering action. By doing so the seed is undergoing a natural form of \"cold stratification\" or pretreatment. This cold moist period triggers the seed's [[embryo]]; its growth and subsequent expansion eventually break through the softened seed coat in its search for sun and nutrients.\n\n===Process===\nIn its most basic form, when the stratification process is controlled, the pretreatment amounts to nothing more than subjecting the seeds to storage in a cool (ideally +1\u00b0 to +3\u00b0C; not freezing) and moist environment for a period found to be sufficient for the species in question. This period of time may vary from one to three months.\n\nTo accomplish this seeds are placed in a sealed plastic bag with moistened [[vermiculite]] (or [[sand]] or even a moistened paper towel), which is refrigerated. Three times as much [[vermiculite]] as seeds is used. It is important to only slightly dampen the vermiculite, as excessive moisture can cause the seeds to [[mold]] in the bag.<ref name=backyardagora/>\n\nSoaking the seeds in cold water for 6\u201312 hours immediately before placing them in cold stratification can cut down on the amount of time needed for stratification, as the seed needs to absorb some moisture to enable the chemical changes that take place.\n\nAfter undergoing the recommended period of stratification, the seeds are ready to be removed and sown in the nursery bed for germination.\n\nAlternatively, the seed may be sown in small pots filled with moist soil and then the whole thing enclosed inside a plastic bag before placing inside a common refrigerator.\n\n===Preparing a stratifying medium===\nMany sources recommend using [[peat]], a combination of peat and [[sand]], or [[vermiculite]] as the medium for cold stratifying seeds.<ref>{{cite web\n | last = Dan\n  | first = Meyer\n  | title = Growing Wisconsin Trees From Seed \n  | url=http://forest.wisc.edu/sites/default/files/pdfs/publications/66.PDF\n  | accessdate = 2008-07-01\n| publisher=University of Wisconsin College of Agricultural and Life Sciences}}</ref><ref>{{cite web \n| url=http://www.ipm.iastate.edu/ipm/hortnews/2000/8-11-2000/germtreeseed.html\n| title=Germination of Tree Seed\n| publisher=University of Iowa Extension\n| accessdate= 2008-07-01\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.monarchlab.org/Lab/Rearing/GrowingMilkweed.aspx\n| publisher=University of Minnesota Monarch Lab\n| title=Growing Milkweed\n}}</ref> The medium must be sterile to prevent harm to the [[seed]] by [[pathogens]] including [[fungi]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.actahort.org/members/showpdf?booknrarnr=574_50\n| title=Dependency of Lingonberry Seed Germinating Ability on Seed Age and Storage Method\n| first=T.\n| last=Paal\n| publisher=International Society for Horticultural Science\n}}</ref>\n\n==Preparing the seed==\nThe seeds should be cleaned of any additional material ([[fruit]] pulp, [[leaf]] and seed-pod fragments, [[conifer cone|cone]] scales, etc.), but the shells of [[nut (fruit)|nuts]] should not be removed.\n\n==Warm and cold stratification==\nAny seeds that are indicated as needing a period of warm stratification followed by cold stratification should be subjected to the same measures, but the seeds should additionally be stratified in a warm area first, followed by the cold period in a refrigerator later. Warm stratification requires temperatures of 15-20\u00b0C (59-68\u00b0F). In many instances, warm stratification followed by cold stratification requirements can also be met by planting the seeds in summer in a mulched bed for expected germination the following spring. Some seeds may not germinate until the second spring.\n\n==Use of fungicide==\nUse of a [[fungicide]] to moisten the stratifying vermiculite will help prevent fungal diseases. [[Chinosol]] ([[8-quinolyl potassium sulfate]]<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/23672298\n| publisher=National Center for Biotechnology Information\n| title=Chinosol [German]\n| accessdate = June 21, 2017\n}}</ref>) is one such fungicide used to inhibit ''Botrytis cinerea'' infections.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.piwine.com/chinosol.html\n| publisher=Presque Isle Wine Cellars \n| title=Chinosol Fungicide\n| accessdate = June 21, 2017\n}}</ref> \n\nDifferent seeds should be placed in different bags rather than putting them all into one bag, and large quantities are also best split into several small bags. That way any fungal outbreak will be restricted to only some seeds. If no fungicide is used, a close check should be kept on the seeds, removing any which show signs of mold or become soft and with a decaying smell.\n\nIf an outbreak of fungus occurs, remove the seeds and re-apply fungicide, then place them in a new bag with new slightly moistened [[vermiculite]]. Always keep the bag sealed. The stratifying seeds should be checked on a regular basis for either fungus or germination. If any seeds germinate while in the refrigerator, they should be removed and sown.\n\n==Sowing and seedlings==\nThe medium/soil is not critical as long as the soil is light as well as lightly firmed down but not heavily compacted. Sterilized potting soil will minimize problems with ''[[Botryotinia|Botrytis]]'' or ''[[Pythium]]'' fungal disease. These problems are much more likely to occur if air circulation is poor.\n\nMost seeds need only be planted at a depth equal to their own thickness in order to germinate. Seeds planted outdoors are best planted a little deeper to avoid disturbance caused by heavy rainfall. The soil should be slightly damp but never soaking wet, nor allowed to dry out completely.\n\nMost [[seedling]]s, whether grown in pots or beds, benefit from good air circulation which discourages fungus growth and promotes sturdy stems.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Scarification (botany)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stratification (Botany)}}\n[[Category:Horticulture and gardening]]\n[[Category:Plant reproduction]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link changed toMold (fungus)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stratification_(seeds)"}
{"title_page": "Our Lady of Victory Cathedral (Victoria, Texas)", "text_new": "{{Infobox church\n|name                   = Cathedral of Our Lady of Victory\n|fullname               = \n|image                  = Cath\u00e9drale ND Victoire ext\u00e9rieur 01.jpg\n|imagesize              = 250px\n|imagelink              = \n|imagealt               = \n|landscape              = \n|caption                =\n\n|pushpin map            = USA Texas\n|pushpin label position = none\n|pushpin map alt        = \n|pushpin mapsize        = \n|map caption            = Location in Texas\n|coordinates            = {{coord|28.8243|-96.9919|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-TX|display=inline,title}}\n|osgraw                 =  <!--  TEXT -->\n|osgridref              =  <!-- {{gbmappingsmall|TEXT}} -->\n|location               = 1309 Mesquite Lane<br>[[Victoria, Texas]]\n|country                = [[United States]]\n|denomination           = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n|previous denomination  =\n|churchmanship          = \n|membership             = \n|attendance             = \n|website                = [http://www.olvcathedral.org/ www.olvcathedral.org]\n|former name            = \n|bull date              = \n|founded date           = 1958\n|founder                = \n|dedication             = [[Our Lady of Victory]]\n|dedicated date         = \n|consecrated date       = \n|cult                   = \n|relics                 = \n|events                 = \n|past bishop            = \n|people                 =\n\n|status                 = [[Cathedral]]/[[Parish church]]\n|functional status      = \n|heritage designation   = \n|designated date        = \n|architect              = \n|architectural type     = \n|style                  = [[Modern architecture|Modern]]\n|groundbreaking         = \n|completed date         = 1958\n|construction cost      = \n|closed date            = \n|demolished date        =\n\n|capacity               = \n|length                 = \n|width                  = \n|width nave             = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|height                 = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|diameter               = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|other dimensions       = \n|floor count            = \n|floor area             = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome quantity          = \n|dome height outer      = \n|dome height inner      = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome dia outer         = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome dia inner         = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|spire quantity         = One\n|spire height           = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|materials              = [[Brick]]\n|bells                  = \n|bells hung             = \n|bell weight            = <!-- {{CwtQtrLb to kg|}} -->\n\n|diocese                = [[Diocese of Victoria in Texas|Victoria in Texas]]\n\n|bishop                 = Most Rev. [[Brendan J. Cahill]]\n|rector                 = Rev. Gary W. Janak \n|vicar                  = \n|deacon                 = \n}}\n'''The Cathedral of Our Lady of Victory''' is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[cathedral]] and [[parish church]] located in [[Victoria, Texas]], United States. It is the seat of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Victoria in Texas|Diocese of Victoria in Texas]].\n\n==History==\nOur Lady of Victory Parish can trace its roots to 1956 when the families of Thomas O'Connor Sr. and Martin O'Connor donated {{convert|20|acres}} of land for a new Catholic parish.<ref name=Cathedral>{{cite web|url=http://www.olvcathedral.org/history-of-olv|title=History of OLV|publisher=Our Lady of Victory Cathedral|accessdate=2011-10-05|author=}}</ref> The [[cornerstone]] for the present church was laid on April 7, 1957 by Archbishop [[Robert Emmet Lucey|Robert E. Lucey]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Antonio|San Antonio]] and it was consecrated on November 4 the following year. Our Lady of Victory Catholic School opened in September 1957.\n\nThe initial planning for the parish and the construction of the buildings was done by Msgr. Frederick O'Beck who was the pastor at [[Saint Mary's Catholic Church (Victoria, Texas)|St. Mary's]] in Victoria. The Rev. Henry Rolf was named the first pastor on July 12, 1958. The parish was officially established the following day.<ref name=Cathedral/>\n\n[[Pope John Paul II]] established the Diocese of Victoria in Texas on April 13, 1982.<ref name=hierarchy>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dvict.html|title=Diocese of Victoria in Texas|publisher=Catholic-Hierarchy|accessdate=2011-10-05|author=}}</ref> Our Lady of Victory became the cathedral for the diocese at that time.<ref name=Cathedral/>\n\nIn 2009 the parish acquired the former Town Plaza Mall located next door to the parish property.<ref name=Cargo>{{cite news|url=https://www.victoriaadvocate.com/news/2016/aug/14/our-lady-of-victory-expands-into-old-mall/|title=Our Lady of Victory expands into old mall|newspaper=[[Victoria Advocate]]|location=[[Victoria, Texas|Victoria]]|date=August 14, 2016|accessdate=2018-02-20|author=Kathryn Cargo}}</ref> The former [[J.C. Penney]] store was converted into the Cathedral Center. It houses the parish hall and meeting rooms that are used for receptions, conferences, and various parish programs. Victoria architectural firm Rawley McCoy & Associates was the architect for the project that was completed in 2017. The rest of the mall was sold to the [[University of Houston\u2013Victoria]] the same year.<ref name=Joseph>{{cite news|url=https://www.crossroadstoday.com/news/uhv-purchases-large-portion-of-town-plaza-mall/914414525|title=UHV purchases large portion of Town Plaza Mall|publisher=[[KAVU-TV]]|location=[[Victoria, Texas|Victoria]]|date=July 13, 2017|accessdate=2019-08-30|author=Amber Joseph}}</ref> A driveway and green space will separate the parish building from the University's facility.\n\nThe cathedral suffered water damage during [[Hurricane Harvey]] in 2017.<ref name=Lighthouse1>{{cite news|url=https://d2y1pz2y630308.cloudfront.net/2809/documents/2017/10/October%20Issue%202017%20FINAL.pdf|title=Hurricane Harvey|newspaper=The Catholic Lighthouse|location=[[Victoria, Texas|Victoria]]|date=October 2017|accessdate=2019-08-30|author=}}</ref> Repairs to the roof and the wooden rafters were made at that time. In the summer of 2019, the cathedral was closed for interior renovations necessitated by the water damage from the hurricane. The work included the removal of the murals near the ceiling that had to be re-created on new panels. Other projects included refurbishing the pews, reconditioning the statues, cleaning the walls of [[Mold (fungus)|mold]], restoring the interior woodwork, and repainting the walls while maintaining the integrity of the original [[mural]]s.<ref name=Lighthouse2>{{cite news|url=https://d2y1pz2y630308.cloudfront.net/2809/documents/2019/7/August%202019%20Issue%2020%20pg%20sm.pdf|title=Two Years After Harvey: Cathedral Continues With Renovations|newspaper=The Catholic Lighthouse|location=[[Victoria, Texas|Victoria]]|date=August 2019|accessdate=2019-08-30|author=}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nCath\u00e9drale ND Victoire choeur.jpg|View from the organ tribune to the choir\nCath\u00e9drale ND Victoire Nef.jpg|View to the nave\nCath\u00e9drale ND Victoire d\u00e9tail autel.jpg|Detail of the altar's mosaics\nCath\u00e9drale ND Victoire chapelle sacr\u00e9 coeur.jpg|The Sacred Heart chapel\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Catholic cathedrals in the United States]]\n*[[List of cathedrals in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.olvcathedral.org/ Cathedral Website]\n*[http://www.victoriadiocese.org/ Diocese of Victoria Website]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Victoria in Texas|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1958]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1958]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic cathedrals in Texas|Our Lady of Victory]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture in Texas]]\n[[Category:Churches in Victoria County, Texas]]\n\n\n{{Texas-church-stub}}\n{{US-RC-cathedral-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox church\n|name                   = Cathedral of Our Lady of Victory\n|fullname               = \n|image                  = Cath\u00e9drale ND Victoire ext\u00e9rieur 01.jpg\n|imagesize              = 250px\n|imagelink              = \n|imagealt               = \n|landscape              = \n|caption                =\n\n|pushpin map            = USA Texas\n|pushpin label position = none\n|pushpin map alt        = \n|pushpin mapsize        = \n|map caption            = Location in Texas\n|coordinates            = {{coord|28.8243|-96.9919|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-TX|display=inline,title}}\n|osgraw                 =  <!--  TEXT -->\n|osgridref              =  <!-- {{gbmappingsmall|TEXT}} -->\n|location               = 1309 Mesquite Lane<br>[[Victoria, Texas]]\n|country                = [[United States]]\n|denomination           = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n|previous denomination  =\n|churchmanship          = \n|membership             = \n|attendance             = \n|website                = [http://www.olvcathedral.org/ www.olvcathedral.org]\n|former name            = \n|bull date              = \n|founded date           = 1958\n|founder                = \n|dedication             = [[Our Lady of Victory]]\n|dedicated date         = \n|consecrated date       = \n|cult                   = \n|relics                 = \n|events                 = \n|past bishop            = \n|people                 =\n\n|status                 = [[Cathedral]]/[[Parish church]]\n|functional status      = \n|heritage designation   = \n|designated date        = \n|architect              = \n|architectural type     = \n|style                  = [[Modern architecture|Modern]]\n|groundbreaking         = \n|completed date         = 1958\n|construction cost      = \n|closed date            = \n|demolished date        =\n\n|capacity               = \n|length                 = \n|width                  = \n|width nave             = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|height                 = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|diameter               = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|other dimensions       = \n|floor count            = \n|floor area             = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome quantity          = \n|dome height outer      = \n|dome height inner      = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome dia outer         = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome dia inner         = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|spire quantity         = One\n|spire height           = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|materials              = [[Brick]]\n|bells                  = \n|bells hung             = \n|bell weight            = <!-- {{CwtQtrLb to kg|}} -->\n\n|diocese                = [[Diocese of Victoria in Texas|Victoria in Texas]]\n\n|bishop                 = Most Rev. [[Brendan J. Cahill]]\n|rector                 = Rev. Gary W. Janak \n|vicar                  = \n|deacon                 = \n}}\n'''The Cathedral of Our Lady of Victory''' is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[cathedral]] and [[parish church]] located in [[Victoria, Texas]], United States. It is the seat of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Victoria in Texas|Diocese of Victoria in Texas]].\n\n==History==\nOur Lady of Victory Parish can trace its roots to 1956 when the families of Thomas O'Connor Sr. and Martin O'Connor donated {{convert|20|acres}} of land for a new Catholic parish.<ref name=Cathedral>{{cite web|url=http://www.olvcathedral.org/history-of-olv|title=History of OLV|publisher=Our Lady of Victory Cathedral|accessdate=2011-10-05|author=}}</ref> The [[cornerstone]] for the present church was laid on April 7, 1957 by Archbishop [[Robert Emmet Lucey|Robert E. Lucey]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Antonio|San Antonio]] and it was consecrated on November 4 the following year. Our Lady of Victory Catholic School opened in September 1957.\n\nThe initial planning for the parish and the construction of the buildings was done by Msgr. Frederick O'Beck who was the pastor at [[Saint Mary's Catholic Church (Victoria, Texas)|St. Mary's]] in Victoria. The Rev. Henry Rolf was named the first pastor on July 12, 1958. The parish was officially established the following day.<ref name=Cathedral/>\n\n[[Pope John Paul II]] established the Diocese of Victoria in Texas on April 13, 1982.<ref name=hierarchy>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dvict.html|title=Diocese of Victoria in Texas|publisher=Catholic-Hierarchy|accessdate=2011-10-05|author=}}</ref> Our Lady of Victory became the cathedral for the diocese at that time.<ref name=Cathedral/>\n\nIn 2009 the parish acquired the former Town Plaza Mall located next door to the parish property.<ref name=Cargo>{{cite news|url=https://www.victoriaadvocate.com/news/2016/aug/14/our-lady-of-victory-expands-into-old-mall/|title=Our Lady of Victory expands into old mall|newspaper=[[Victoria Advocate]]|location=[[Victoria, Texas|Victoria]]|date=August 14, 2016|accessdate=2018-02-20|author=Kathryn Cargo}}</ref> The former [[J.C. Penney]] store was converted into the Cathedral Center. It houses the parish hall and meeting rooms that are used for receptions, conferences, and various parish programs. Victoria architectural firm Rawley McCoy & Associates was the architect for the project that was completed in 2017. The rest of the mall was sold to the [[University of Houston\u2013Victoria]] the same year.<ref name=Joseph>{{cite news|url=https://www.crossroadstoday.com/news/uhv-purchases-large-portion-of-town-plaza-mall/914414525|title=UHV purchases large portion of Town Plaza Mall|publisher=[[KAVU-TV]]|location=[[Victoria, Texas|Victoria]]|date=July 13, 2017|accessdate=2019-08-30|author=Amber Joseph}}</ref> A driveway and green space will separate the parish building from the University's facility.\n\nThe cathedral suffered water damage during [[Hurricane Harvey]] in 2017.<ref name=Lighthouse1>{{cite news|url=https://d2y1pz2y630308.cloudfront.net/2809/documents/2017/10/October%20Issue%202017%20FINAL.pdf|title=Hurricane Harvey|newspaper=The Catholic Lighthouse|location=[[Victoria, Texas|Victoria]]|date=October 2017|accessdate=2019-08-30|author=}}</ref> Repairs to the roof and the wooden rafters were made at that time. In the summer of 2019, the cathedral was closed for interior renovations necessitated by the water damage from the hurricane. The work included the removal of the murals near the ceiling that had to be re-created on new panels. Other projects included refurbishing the pews, reconditioning the statues, cleaning the walls of [[mold]], restoring the interior woodwork, and repainting the walls while maintaining the integrity of the original [[mural]]s.<ref name=Lighthouse2>{{cite news|url=https://d2y1pz2y630308.cloudfront.net/2809/documents/2019/7/August%202019%20Issue%2020%20pg%20sm.pdf|title=Two Years After Harvey: Cathedral Continues With Renovations|newspaper=The Catholic Lighthouse|location=[[Victoria, Texas|Victoria]]|date=August 2019|accessdate=2019-08-30|author=}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nCath\u00e9drale ND Victoire choeur.jpg|View from the organ tribune to the choir\nCath\u00e9drale ND Victoire Nef.jpg|View to the nave\nCath\u00e9drale ND Victoire d\u00e9tail autel.jpg|Detail of the altar's mosaics\nCath\u00e9drale ND Victoire chapelle sacr\u00e9 coeur.jpg|The Sacred Heart chapel\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Catholic cathedrals in the United States]]\n*[[List of cathedrals in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.olvcathedral.org/ Cathedral Website]\n*[http://www.victoriadiocese.org/ Diocese of Victoria Website]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Victoria in Texas|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1958]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1958]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic cathedrals in Texas|Our Lady of Victory]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture in Texas]]\n[[Category:Churches in Victoria County, Texas]]\n\n\n{{Texas-church-stub}}\n{{US-RC-cathedral-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMold(link changed toMold (fungus)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Our_Lady_of_Victory_Cathedral_(Victoria,_Texas)"}
{"title_page": "Sid Barnes", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian cricketer}}\n{{about||the similarly named English cricketer|Sydney Barnes|the American singer and songwriter|Sidney Barnes (musician)}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Sid Barnes\n| image = SidBarnesHeadshot.jpg\n| caption = Barnes in cricket whites\n| alt = Barnes wearing his Australian cricket cap and sweater\n| country = Australia\n| fullname = Sidney George Barnes\n| nickname = Bagga<ref name=\"grandpa\">{{cite journal\n | last = Frith\n | first = David\n | author1-link = David Frith\n | title = What did you do at Lord's, Grandpa?\n | journal = [[Wisden Cricket Monthly]]\n | year = 1987\n | url = http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/wcm/content/story/70460.html\n | accessdate = 3 December 2007 }}</ref><br>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1916|6|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Annandale, New South Wales]], Australia\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1973|12|16|1916|6|5|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Collaroy, New South Wales]], Australia\n| heightft =\n| heightinch =\n| heightm =\n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[leg break]]\n| role = Batsman, occasional [[wicket-keeper]]\n| international = true\n| testdebutdate = 20 August\n| testdebutyear = 1938\n| testdebutagainst = England\n| testcap = 163\n| lasttestdate = 14 August\n| lasttestyear = 1948\n| lasttestagainst = England\n| club1 = [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]]\n| year1 = {{nowrap|1936/37\u20131952/53}}\n| columns = 2\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Tests]]\n| matches1 = 13\n| runs1 = 1,072\n| bat avg1 = 63.05\n| 100s/50s1 = 3/5\n| top score1 = 234\n| deliveries1 = 564\n| wickets1 = 4\n| bowl avg1 = 54.50\n| fivefor1 = 0\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 2/25\n| catches/stumpings1 = 14/\u2013\n| column2 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n| matches2 = 110\n| runs2 = 8,333\n| bat avg2 = 54.11\n| 100s/50s2 = 26/37\n| top score2 = 234\n| deliveries2 = 4,451\n| wickets2 = 57\n| bowl avg2 = 32.21\n| fivefor2 = 0\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 3/0\n| catches/stumpings2 = 80/4\n| date= 28 November\n| year = 2007\n| source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/0/711/711.html CricketArchive\n}}\n'''Sidney George Barnes''' (5 June 1916 \u2013 16 December 1973) was an Australian [[cricket]]er and cricket writer, who played 13&nbsp;[[Test cricket|Test matches]] between 1938 and 1948. Able to [[Batting order (cricket)#Opening batsmen|open the innings]] or [[Batting order (cricket)#Top order|bat down the order]], Barnes was regarded as one of Australia's finest batsmen in the period immediately following the [[World War II|Second World War]]. He helped create an enduring record when scoring 234&nbsp;in the second Test against England at Sydney in December 1946; exactly the same score as his captain, [[Donald Bradman|Don Bradman]], in the process setting a world-record 405-run [[wicket#Partnership|fifth wicket]] [[partnership (cricket)|partnership]]. Barnes averaged 63.05 over 19 innings in a career that, like those of most of his contemporaries, was interrupted by the Second World War.\n\nHe made his [[First-class cricket|first-class]] debut at the end of the 1936\u201337 season when selected for [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]], and he was later included in the team for the [[Australian cricket team in England in 1938|1938 Australian tour of England]], making his Test debut in the final international of the series. On the resumption of Test cricket after the war, he was picked as the opening partner to [[Arthur Morris]]. Barnes was a member of [[Australian cricket team in England in 1948|''The Invincibles'']], the 1948 Australian team that toured England without losing a single match. Retiring from cricket at the end of that tour, Barnes attempted a comeback to Test cricket in the 1951\u201352 season that was ultimately and controversially unsuccessful.<ref>As a convention, cricket seasons are denoted as a single year to represent northern hemisphere summer, or dashed for southern hemisphere. See [[Cricket season]] for more information.</ref>\n\nBarnes had a reputation as an eccentric and was frequently the subject of controversy. This included a celebrated [[Defamation|libel]] case, following his exclusion from the national team in 1951\u201352 for \"reasons other than cricket ability\". He was later involved in an incident where, acting as [[List of cricket terms#T|twelfth man]], he performed his duties on the ground in a suit and tie (rather than [[Flannels|'whites']]), carrying a bizarre range of superfluous items. Despite this reputation, Barnes was a shrewd businessman who used the opportunities afforded by cricket to supplement his income through trading, journalism and [[Real-estate developer|property development]]. Increasing [[paranoia]] brought about by [[bipolar disorder]] saw Barnes lose many of the friends he had made through the game as he sought treatment for his depression. On 16 December 1973, he was found dead at his home in the Sydney suburb of [[Collaroy, New South Wales|Collaroy]]; he had ingested [[barbiturate]]s and [[bromide]] in a probable suicide.\n\n==Early years==\nBarnes was born in 1916 in [[Annandale, New South Wales|Annandale]], an inner suburb of Sydney.<ref>Smith, p.3. \"was born in Annandale on 5 June 1916. She christened him Sidney George after the city of his birth and his maternal grandfather. Sid's place of birth would remain a problem for many years to come. He always thought it was [[Charters Towers, Queensland|Charters Towers]] in [[Queensland]] and said so in his autobiography. He also confessed confusion over the year citing 1918 or 1919, rather than 1916.\"</ref> However, in his autobiography, he claims to have been born in 1918 or 1919 in [[Queensland]],<ref>Barnes, p. 13.</ref> and his military service record has his date of birth as 5 June 1917.<ref>[http://naa12.naa.gov.au/scripts/ItemDetail.asp?M=0&B=5659359 Military service record], National Archives</ref> He was the third child of Alfred Percival Barnes and Hilda May Barnes (n\u00e9e Jeffery), both from farming families near [[Tamworth, New South Wales|Tamworth]] in northern [[New South Wales]]. After marrying, the couple left Tamworth to take up a lease on a remote [[sheep station]] near [[Hughenden, Queensland|Hughenden]] in North Queensland. Before Sid was born, Alfred died from [[typhoid fever]], caused by drinking contaminated water on the family property. After his death, Hilda, widowed and pregnant with her latest child, moved to Sydney with her children and stayed with her sister, where Sid was born. From her husband's estate, Hilda Barnes mother was able to purchase and renovate real estate in [[Stanmore, New South Wales|Stanmore]] and [[Leichhardt, New South Wales|Leichhardt]],&nbsp;New South Wales, to let or sell. Later in life, Barnes would recount how, as a child, he used to collect the rents for his mother.<ref>Smith, pp. 2\u20133.</ref>\n\n===Childhood and club cricket===\n[[File:Sid Barnes, 16 Petersham.jpg|thumb|left|Barnes, aged 16, as a Petersham player]]\nBarnes attended [[Stanmore, New South Wales#Schools|Stanmore Public School]] and, although not a scholar, was a keen participant in sporting activities.<ref>Smith, p. 5.</ref> His introduction to cricket came via his older brother, Horrie; Horrie was a useful batsman who played in the local Western Suburbs Churches league and paid Sid [[Sixpence (Australian)|sixpence]] to bowl to him after he finished work. Taking an interest in the game, Sid had trials for the school team and was eventually selected in the first XI. An early controversy saw Barnes suspended for three weeks for disputing an [[umpire (cricket)|umpire]]'s decision.<ref name=\"smith10\">Smith, p. 10.</ref> Successes for both his school team and his local club team, St. Augustine, saw him acquire the nickname ''The Governor-General''\u2014the nickname of Australian Test player, [[Charlie Macartney]], and he was selected for New South Wales Schoolboys to play teams from [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and [[Queensland]].<ref name=\"smith10\"/>\n\nIn 1932\u201333, Barnes joined the [[Petersham, New South Wales|Petersham]] club, and began playing in the third XI. Former Test batsman [[Tommy Andrews (cricketer)|Tommy Andrews]] became his mentor at the club and in 1933\u201334, Barnes made his [[Sydney Grade Cricket|first-grade cricket]] debut as a [[batsman]]/[[wicket-keeper]] against Paddington, facing the bowling of [[Hunter Hendry]] and [[Alan McGilvray]].<ref>Smith, pp. 11\u201313.</ref> He was soon successful, scoring a century against Manly in February. Even as a young and inexperienced cricketer, he showed a \"brash confidence in his own ability.\"<ref name=\"adb\">{{cite journal\n|last = Stoddart\n|first = Brian\n|year = 2002\n|title = 'Barnes, Sidney George (Sid) (1916\u20131973)'\n|journal = Australian Dictionary of Biography\n|volume = 13\n|pages =118\u2013119\n|location = Melbourne\n|publisher = Melbourne University Press\n|url = http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A130142b.htm\n|accessdate = 4 December 2007}}</ref>\nWhen praised for his batting by the great Test bowler [[Bill O'Reilly (cricketer)|Bill O'Reilly]], Barnes responded \"Thanks very much, you didn't bowl too badly yourself\", leaving O'Reilly speechless.<ref>Smith, p. 13.</ref>\n\nThis success led Barnes to consider cricket as a potential career. However, his mother and stepfather were concerned about the likelihood of cricket providing him with a living. In response, Barnes took a job with a [[Automobile repair shop|garage]] in [[Mosman, New South Wales|Mosman]] but after finding that the necessary travel interfered too much with playing cricket, he found alternative employment, demonstrating motorbikes in the city.<ref>Smith, pp. 13\u201314.</ref>\n\n===First-class cricket===\nBarnes had come to the attention of the [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]] selectors by the 1936\u201337 season and was included as [[List of cricket terms#T|twelfth man]] in the side to play the [[English cricket team in Australia in 1936-37|visiting English side]], taking a catch on the boundary to dismiss [[Stan Worthington]].<ref>Smith, p. 15.</ref> He made his [[First-class cricket|first-class]] debut in the final [[Pura Cup|Sheffield Shield]] match of the season, against [[Southern Redbacks|South Australia]] at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref name=\"Debut\">Smith, pp. 7\u20138.</ref> Batting at [[Batting order (cricket)#Middle order|number five]], Barnes scored 31&nbsp;and 44, twice being dismissed [[leg before wicket|LBW]] by the [[leg spin]]ner [[Frank Ward (cricketer, born 1906)|Frank Ward]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/16/16093.html\n|title = New South Wales v South Australia\u2013Sheffield Shield 1936/37\n|date = 23 February 1937\n|publisher = CricketArchive\n|accessdate = 3 December 2007}}</ref> Whilst fielding, Barnes managed to find himself in controversy again, [[run out|running out]] [[Vic Richardson]], the opposition captain, after the end of the [[over (cricket)|over]] was called. The square leg umpire had not heard the call of \"Over\" and upheld the [[appeal (cricket)|appeal]], much to the disgust of Richardson. The New South Wales captain [[Stan McCabe]], whom Barnes idolised, withdrew the appeal.<ref name=\"Debut\"/>\n\nBarnes was selected for New South Wales for the opening match of the 1937\u201338 season against [[Queensland Bulls|Queensland]] making 68 in a rain-affected match. Against the touring [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealanders]], Barnes fell just short of his maiden first-class century, scoring 97.<ref name=\"1937 season\">Smith, pp. 17\u201318.</ref> He appeared to have reached the landmark when scoring 127&nbsp;[[not out]] against [[Western Warriors|Western Australia]], but the [[New South Wales Cricket Association]] retrospectively deemed the match to be not of first-class status, angering Barnes.<ref name=\"1937 season\"/> He finally scored his maiden first-class century (110) against Victoria in the final game of the season, completing his hundred while bleeding profusely after being struck on the jaw by a ball delivered by [[Ernie McCormick]].<ref>Smith, p. 20.</ref> As a result of his performances over the season (scoring over 800 [[run (cricket)|runs]], averaging 50.56),<ref name=\"seasonbyseason\">{{cite web\n|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/0/711/f_Batting_by_Season.html\n|title =First-class Batting and Fielding in Each Season by Sid Barnes\n|publisher= CricketArchive\n|accessdate=3 December 2007}}</ref> Barnes was selected as the youngest member of the [[Australian cricket team in England in 1938|Australian cricket team to tour England in 1938]].<ref>Smith, p. 21.</ref>\n\n==Test cricket==\n[[File:Sid Barnes.jpg|thumb|Cigarette card showing Barnes as a New South Wales representative]]\n\n===Pre-war debut===\nUnfortunately for Barnes, he broke his wrist while exercising on the sea voyage to England for the 1938 tour,<ref name=\"insideedge\">{{cite magazine|author= |title=The 50 Greatest Australian Cricketers |magazine=[[Inside Edge (magazine)|Inside Edge]]|publisher=ACP |year=2001|page=56 }}</ref> keeping the injury secret until the tourists had departed [[Gibraltar]], for fear of being sent home.<ref>Smith p. 26., quoting Barnes \"I had jog-trotted six times around the ship the morning we were due to land in Gibraltar and I started stretching exercises. I leapt to catch the steel rope running across the deck to hold up the sun awnings but the early morning mist had made the stachion slippery and I couldn't hold it. I slipped back and, in falling, threw out my left hand to break the fall. I fell with all my weight on the left hand&nbsp;...\" Smith continues, \"A few hours later the pain increased and the hand started to swell. He said nothing just in case there was a ship in Gibraltar on its way back to Australia&nbsp;...\"</ref> On arrival in England, he therefore did not play an innings until the last day of June, missing exactly half of the 30&nbsp;first-class matches scheduled for the tour, including the first two Tests, both of which were drawn. His first innings was 42 against [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] and he shared in a fourth&nbsp;wicket stand of 176 with [[Bill Brown (cricketer)|Bill Brown]], who made an unbeaten 265.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1939\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Australians in England in 1938\n| page = 227\n}}</ref> The third Test was a wash-out and he was not picked for the fourth, which the Australians won, although in his autobiography he claimed that he was considered as a candidate to be wicketkeeper, having deputised for [[Ben Barnett]] in that role in tour matches against [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]] and [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]].<ref>Barnes, p. 78.</ref> In the event, his Test debut came in the final Test, played at [[The Oval]].<ref name=\"testlist\"/> Barnes had to field for 16 hours as England amassed a total of 903&nbsp;for seven&nbsp;declared, then the highest Test score.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283966.html\n| title = Test matches Highest innings totals\n| accessdate = 12 December 2007\n| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]\n}}</ref> Barnes bowled 38&nbsp;overs in the innings and took the seventh wicket, that of [[Arthur Wood (cricketer, born 1898)|Arthur Wood]], for 84&nbsp;runs. With both [[Donald Bradman|Don Bradman]] and [[Jack Fingleton]] injured and unable to bat, Australia struggled \u2013 England won by an innings and 579&nbsp;runs \u2013 still the largest winning margin in Test cricket history;<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/210099.html\n| title = Test matches Largest margin of victory (by an innings)\n| accessdate = 12 December 2007\n| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]\n}}</ref> but Barnes played innings of 41 and 33 and, according to ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]'', \"well justified his choice\".<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1939\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Australians in England in 1938\n| pages = 243\u2013246\n}}</ref> In all first-class matches on the tour, Barnes scored 720&nbsp;runs, and reached 90 three times, though without going on to a first-class century. He scored 140 in a two-day match against [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]], which was not considered first-class.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1939\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Australians in England in 1938\n| pages = 195\u2013253\n}}</ref>\n\nHis international career was then put on hold, as all foreign tours were suspended during the Second World War. He continued to play first-class cricket in Australia, before enlisting in the [[Second Australian Imperial Force]] in May 1942.<ref name=\"cricinfo\">{{cite journal\n|url=http://content-www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/player/4098.html\n|title= Sid Barnes Obituary\n|journal= [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n|year= 1974\n|accessdate= 4 December 2007}}</ref> Barnes's time in the military was short. A man who was proud of his appearance, he had a uniform made to measure when the one issued did not fit. He met champion golfer [[Norman Von Nida]] early into his enlistment and the two were assigned to the [[1st Armoured Division (Australia)|1st Armoured Division]] in [[Greta, New South Wales|Greta]]. A shortage of tanks and the military regimen led to boredom and Barnes used his hitherto ignored trade background to his advantage, seeking a release to join a tank-making company, which was granted. Von Nida and Barnes remained friends and business partners for many years afterwards.<ref>Smith, p. 47.</ref>\n\n===Post-war series===\nAfter scoring 1,050&nbsp;runs (including six centuries) at an average of 75.00 in the 1940\u201341 season,<ref name=\"seasonbyseason\"/> Barnes played little cricket until 1945\u201346, when he scored centuries in five successive matches for New South Wales.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/Seasonal_Averages/AUS/1945-46_f_Match_List.html\n|publisher=CricketArchive\n|title= First-Class matches in Australia in 1945/46\n|accessdate=29 November 2007}}</ref> He was picked for the [[History of cricket in New Zealand from 1945-46 to 1970#Australia 1945-46|1945\u201346 Australian tour of New Zealand]] and played in the representative match that was later designated as the first Test match between the two countries: he made 54 as Australia won easily.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1947\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Overseas Cricket\n| page = 629\n}}</ref> The post-war period also saw a new approach to batting on the part of Barnes. He discarded his aggressive and flamboyant shot-making and re-invented himself as a watchful, more defensive player, which made his scoring more prolific, although less crowd pleasing.<ref name=\"az\"/>\n\nBarnes was made captain of New South Wales for the 1946\u201347 Australian season, though he only managed to play three matches for the state team. One of those was the match against [[MCC tour of Australia in 1946\u201347|the touring MCC team]], and Barnes was approached during the match about becoming an [[Batting order (cricket)#Opening batsmen|opening batsman]] for the [[1946-47 Ashes series|forthcoming Test series]]. He wrote in his autobiography: \"I had never opened before and was a little dubious. I had, however, struck new balls at different periods of innings and was not afraid of that.\"<ref>Barnes, p. 115. Barnes does not identify who it was that approached him.</ref> He also liked the idea of batting ahead of Bradman in the batting order: \"Much better, I thought, to get in before him than to come later, like flat beer after champagne.\"\n\nBarnes was first-choice as an opener with [[Arthur Morris]] throughout the Test series, although it was not until the [[1946-47 Ashes series#Third Test \u2013 Melbourne|Third Test]] that they had a first-wicket partnership of any substance. Morris had broken into the team as an opener after an injury sidelined Bill Brown for the entire season.<ref>{{cite book | author = Cashman | author2 = Franks | author3 = Maxwell | author4 = Sainsbury | author5 = Stoddart | author6 = Weaver | author7 = Webster | year = 1997 | title = The A-Z of Australian cricketers|page =67}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1946-47 Ashes series#First Test \u2013 Brisbane|First Test at Brisbane]] was dominated by Australia, a pattern that was to be a feature of the series, although Barnes contributed only 31 to the total of 645 which brought an innings victory.<ref name=\"Teamin\">{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1948\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = M.C.C. Team in Australia and New Zealand, 1946\u201347\n| pages = 728\u2013730\n}}</ref> Barnes displayed his liking for slightly aggressive practical jokes in this match: during a break for a particularly ferocious thunderstorm, he <blockquote>got a huge block of ice out of the tub in which our drinks were kept, staggered to the side of the dressing-room and tossed it on to the roof over the English dressing-room. It caused a noise for a start that brought all the Englishmen running and then it came over the side of the gutter, crashed on to the lawn and slithered down the grass. Those English eyes certainly did stand out.<ref>Barnes, p. 117.</ref></blockquote>\n\nBradman had words with Barnes after this match about his new role as an opener. Barnes later wrote: <blockquote>He asked me how I liked it. I said it suited me. 'You batted very well in this game,' he said, 'but not quite as an opener. You were looking for runs all the time. I think what you want to watch as an opener is not getting out&nbsp;... What is needed from my openers, and is most important, is patience and plenty of it.' I was completely willing to be guided by anything that Bradman wanted me to do.<ref>Barnes, p. 118.</ref></blockquote>\n\nYears later, Barnes wrote about the effect this had on his batting style. <blockquote>There was one angle about this change of batting position that didn't appeal to me. I am, by nature, a forcing batsman. I like to take the shine out of a bowler [sic] and I love to hear the ball rattling the pickets, or soaring over the fence&nbsp;... My footwork was quick and I often caused delight by stepping back feet outside the leg stump and square-cutting&nbsp;... If I were to become an Australian Test opening batsman I would have to conform to standard. I would have to put up the shutters&nbsp;... And so I came to the [[1946-47 Ashes series#Second Test \u2013 Sydney|Second Test in Sydney]] ready to drape myself in the gloomy colors of a Test opening batsman.<ref>Barnes, pp. 121\u2013122.</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Bradman Barnes 234.jpg|thumb|Bradman and Barnes leave the field for an adjournment as both head towards 234.]]\nIt was during the [[1946-47 Ashes series#Second Test \u2013 Sydney|Second Test at Sydney]] in December 1946, that Barnes made a lasting impression on the world game. Having [[Batting order (cricket)#Opening batsmen|opened the innings]], he made his top Test score of 234 and helped to set a world-record 405&nbsp;run [[wicket#Partnership|fifth wicket]] [[partnership (cricket)|partnership]] with [[Donald Bradman|Don Bradman]], a record that still stands today.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://content-www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/62666.html\n| title = The Ashes \u2013 2nd Test \u2013 1946/47 season\n| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]\n| accessdate = 28 November 2007\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283583.html\n| title = Test Matches \u2013 Highest partnership for the fifth wicket\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n| accessdate = 28 November 2007\n}}</ref>\nOn a rain-affected pitch [[Arthur Morris]] was out at 1/24 and [[Ian Johnson (cricketer)|Ian Johnson]] came out as a [[Nightwatchman (cricket)|nightwatchman]] He and Barnes angered the crowd by launching into a [[Umpiring in the 1946\u201347 Ashes series#Bad Light|series of bad light appeals]] \u2013 up to 12 were counted \u2013 before the umpires gave way and play was ended with an hour to spare.<ref>pp32-33, [[Clif Cary]], ''Cricket Controversy, Test matches in Australia 1946\u201347'', T. Werner Laurie Ltd., 1948</ref> This ensured that Australia would not have to play on a sticky wicket and allowed Bradman to rest his leg until play resumed on the Monday. After the series Barnes said on radio:\n<blockquote>\nWe could have played on, but it was a Test match and we just had to win. I realised something drastic had to be done or three wickets might be lost. So I appealed after every second ball. I complained of the people moving about, the light, and, in fact, anything, in an effort to get the appeal upheld. [[Wally Hammond|Hammond]] and [[Norman Yardley|Yardley]] were inspecting the wet pitch. I knew there was a chance of losing valuable wickets so I just kept on appealing until the umpires answered me.<ref>p32, [[Clif Cary]], ''Cricket Controversy, Test matches in Australia 1946\u201347'', T. Werner Laurie Ltd., 1948</ref>\n</blockquote>\nBarnes played carefully on the still-suspect pitch the following day, and, late in the afternoon, Bradman, lower in the order than usual due to a leg injury, joined Barnes with the score at 4/159.<ref>Score given in Australian convention, i.e. four wickets down with the score at 159.</ref> Over six and a half hours later, Bradman was out for 234. Barnes was dismissed just four balls later, also for 234, having batted for over ten hours.<ref name=\"200seasons\">{{cite book\n| last=Hutchinson\n| first= Garrie\n| editor= Ross, John\n| title = 200 Seasons of Australian Cricket\n| year = 1997\n| location= Sydney\n| publisher = Macmillan\n| isbn =0-330-36034-5\n|page= 287}}</ref> In his autobiography, Barnes stated that the coincidence of scores was intended. \"Lots of people have asked me whether I deliberately threw my wicket away at 234. The answer is yes.\"<ref>Barnes, p. 125.</ref> He confirmed to an interviewer many years later that \"it wouldn't be right for someone to make more runs than Sir Donald Bradman\".<ref>{{cite book\n|title=Legends of the Baggy Green\n|year=2004\n|last=Buzo\n|first=Alexander\n|authorlink=Alex Buzo\n|page=81\n|publisher= [[Allen & Unwin]]\n|location= St. Leonard's, New South Wales\n|isbn=1-74114-385-3}}</ref>\n[[E.W. Swanton]] wrote that this \"could well have been so for he was a man of [[Quixotism|quixotic]] mood and temperament\".<ref>p63, [[E.W. Swanton]], ''Swanton in Australia with MCC 1946\u20131975'', Fontana/Collins, 1975</ref> However the England bowler, [[Alec Bedser]] wrote \"It was when I was bowling to Sid at Sydney that I first discovered that I could move the ball to leg by use of my wrist and fingers...I held the ball in the same manner as a [[wrist spin|leg-break bowler]] with the fingers across the seam...and on pitching I was surprised to see the ball go away like a leg-break. It also surprised Sid Barnes\".<ref>pp7-8, [[Alec Bedser]], ''May's Men in Australia, The M.C.C. Tour 1958\u201359'', Stanley Paul, 1959</ref> This would make Barnes the first batsman to be dismissed by Bedser's \"Special Ball\" which would claim Bradman for a duck in the [[1946-47 Ashes series#Fourth Test \u2013 Adelaide|Fourth Test at Adelaide]].\n\nBarnes injured his hand during fielding practice before the [[1946-47 Ashes series#Third Test \u2013 Melbourne|Third Test]], and although he went on to play in that game (scoring 45 and 32), he opted out of batting in a state game \u2013 according to his autobiography, this cost him the New South Wales captaincy \u2013<ref>Barnes, p. 127.</ref> and he missed the fourth Test. He returned for the final Test and top-scored with 71 in Australia's first innings, adding 30 in the second.<ref name=\"Teamin\" />\n\nBarnes went to England in 1947. In his autobiography, he claimed that he went as a representative for a wine and spirits company, although after the initial mention of that there is no further word and he appears also to have dealt in commodities that were in short supply because of rationing in England.<ref>Barnes, pp. 139\u2013147.</ref> Once in England, he was approached by [[Burnley Cricket Club|Burnley]] to play as a professional in [[Lancashire League (cricket)|Lancashire League]] cricket, which he did for a while before finding it \"too much of a drag\" and resigning.<ref>Barnes, pp. 146.</ref>\n\nBarnes returned to Australia for the 1947\u201348 season, keen to win a place on the 1948 tour to England. He was worried that having played as a professional in the Lancashire League would damage his chance of further Test cricket, but at the same time suggested that he had offers from other Lancashire League teams to fall back on should he not be picked. There was also concern that, with his wife now living in Scotland, he would breach the Australian rule that wives were not allowed to travel with Test cricketers.<ref>Barnes, pp. 151\u2013158.</ref> In fact, lack of form and opportunity were greater threats to Barnes's continued Test career. Arriving back with several state games having already been played, he failed to make runs for New South Wales and was not picked for the first two Tests against [[Indian cricket team in Australia in 1947-48|the Indian tourists]], Bill Brown taking over as opener with Morris.\n\nThe match between Victoria and New South Wales was Barnes's chance to redeem himself. ''Wisden'' reported it thus: <blockquote>\nBarnes needed a score to rehabilitate himself in the eyes of the Test Selectors and he spent all Saturday over 131&nbsp;runs while 20,000 impatient spectators barracked loudly. His dismissal on the third day evoked cheers all round the ground.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1949\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Overseas Cricket\n| page = 793\n}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHe followed that century (158 in total) with a similarly plodding 80&nbsp;not out in the second innings, and was picked for the third Test, with Brown dropped after a series of low scores in the first two Tests.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/guru?sdb=player;playerid=636;class=testplayer;filter=basic;team=0;opposition=0;notopposition=0;season=0;homeaway=0;continent=0;country=0;notcountry=0;groundid=0;startdefault=1934-06-08;start=1934-06-08;enddefault=1948-06-29;end=1948-06-29;tourneyid=0;finals=0;daynight=0;toss=0;scheduledovers=0;scheduleddays=0;innings=0;result=0;followon=0;seriesresult=0;captain=0;keeper=0;dnp=0;recent=;viewtype=aro_list;runslow=;runshigh=;batposition=0;dismissal=0;bowposition=0;ballslow=;ballshigh=;bpof=0;overslow=;overshigh=;conclow=;conchigh=;wicketslow=;wicketshigh=;dismissalslow=;dismissalshigh=;caughtlow=;caughthigh=;caughttype=0;stumpedlow=;stumpedhigh=;csearch=;submit=1;.cgifields=viewtype\n| title = Bill Brown Test performances\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n| accessdate = 11 December 2007\n}}</ref> Barnes made only 12 and 15, jeopardising his place, but what ''Wisden'' termed \"another of his dour, determined but faultless innings for top score\" in the New South Wales game against South Australia ensured a second chance.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1949\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Overseas Cricket\n| page = 794\n}}</ref> In the fourth Test at [[Adelaide Oval|Adelaide]] he made 112 and put on 236 with Bradman for the second wicket.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1949\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = India in Australia, 1947\u201348\n| page = 780\n}}</ref> With 33 in the final match of the series, his place on the 1948 tour was secure, though he had to give assurances about the amount of contact he would have with his wife, still living in Scotland, before he was confirmed.<ref>Barnes, p. 158.</ref>\n\n===''The Invincibles'' tour===\n{{main|Sid Barnes with the Australian cricket team in England in 1948}}\n{{see also|Australian cricket team in England in 1948|1948 Ashes series}}\nThe 1948 Australia team that toured England has become known as ''The Invincibles'', because they did not lose a single game.<ref>{{Cite web\n |url=http://www.cultureandrecreation.gov.au/articles/sportinggreats/ \n |title=Sporting greats \u2013 Australia reveres and treasures its sporting heroes \n |accessdate=18 December 2007 \n |publisher=Australian Government \u2013 Culture and Recreation Portal \n |quote=The 1948 Australian cricket team captained by Don Bradman, for example, became known as 'The Invincibles' for their unbeaten eight-month tour of England. This team is one of Australia's most cherished sporting legends. \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408184025/http://www.cultureandrecreation.gov.au/articles/sportinggreats/ \n |archivedate=8 April 2011 \n}}</ref> Following their performances during the Australian [[Cricket season|season]], Barnes and Morris were favoured as Australia's first-choice opening pair, while Brown batted out of position in the middle order in the first two Tests.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1940S/1948/AUS_IN_ENG/AUS_ENG_T1_10-15JUN1948.html\n| title = The Ashes, 1948, 1st Test \u2013 England v Australia -Trent Bridge, Nottingham \u2013 10,11,12,14,15 June 1948 (5-day match)\n| accessdate = 11 December 2007\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1940S/1948/AUS_IN_ENG/AUS_ENG_T2_24-29JUN1948.html\n| title = The Ashes, 1948, 2nd Test \u2013 England v Australia \u2013 Lord's, London \u2013 24,25,26,28,29 June 1948 (5-day match)\n| accessdate = 11 December 2007\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n}}</ref>\n\nBefore the second Test at [[Lord's]], Barnes wagered \u00a38 at 15/1 on himself to score a century.<ref name=\"insideedge\"/> He made a [[duck (cricket)|duck]] in the first innings but ensured success in the second, making 141.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/18/18500.html\n| title = England v Australia, 1948, 1st Test\n| publisher = CricketArchive\n| date= 15 June 1948\n| accessdate = 28 November 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nBarnes and Morris shared century opening partnerships at Lord's and [[The Oval]], where their 117&nbsp;run stand dwarfed the 52&nbsp;[[List of cricket terms#A|all out]] made by the entire England team.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/62689.html\n| title = The Ashes, 1948, 5th Test \u2013 England v Australia \u2013 The Oval, London \u2013 14,16,17,18 August 1948 (5-day match)\n| accessdate = 15 April 2008\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n}}</ref> In addition to his century at Lord's, Barnes made three other scores over 60 in the series.<ref name=\"testlist\"/>\n\nWhen fielding, Barnes stationed himself as close to the bat as possible at either [[Fielding (cricket)#Fielding position names and locations|forward short-leg or point]]. The report of the tour in the 1949 edition of [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]], stated that Barnes's fielding was as important a factor as his batting in ''The Invincibles''' success: <blockquote>Probably a number of batsmen were sufficiently affected by his close attendance to cause them to lose concentration on the bowler running up, but equally important was the fact that the knowledge of his presence influenced opponents to avoid strokes in that direction. The Barnes<!-- This should probably be \"The Barnes' demeanour\" \u2013 can somebody check the source? --> demeanour in the field illustrated the general purposefulness of the Australians.<ref name=\"1949wisden\">Preston, 1949: pp. 240\u2013241.</ref></blockquote>\n\nHowever, he received criticism for this approach<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/player/4098.html\n| title = Sid Barnes player profile\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n| accessdate = 11 December 2007\n}}</ref> and it resulted in him missing the fourth Test at [[Headingley Cricket Ground|Headingley]] through injury.<ref name=\"testlist\"/> In England's first innings of the third Test, he was hit in the ribs by a full-blooded pull shot from [[Dick Pollard]] from the bowling of [[Ian Johnson (cricketer)|Ian Johnson]], and had to be carried from the pitch by four policemen. The following day, he collapsed while practising in the nets, and when he went in to bat at number six, he collapsed again and had to [[Substitute (cricket)#Retired hurt|retire hurt]].<ref name=\"1949wisden\"/> After this, he was taken to hospital where he spent 10 days before rejoining the tour for the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] match that followed the fourth Test.\n\nBarnes thus played in four of the five Tests, missing the fourth Test through injury.<ref name=\"testlist\"/> He scored 329&nbsp;runs, averaging 82.25.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/ENG/Australia_in_England_1948/t_Australia_Batting.html\n| title = Test Batting and Fielding for Australia in England 1948\n| publisher = CricketArchive\n| accessdate = 28 November 2007\n}}</ref> During the first-class tour matches, Barnes's performance was less spectacular. In all first-class matches on the tour, he amassed 1354&nbsp;runs, averaging 56.41.<ref name=\"cricinfo\"/> Barnes made 176 in 255 minutes against [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] early in the tour, but, apart from his Test hundred, his only other century came in the final tour match, when the final 50 runs of his 151 against the [[H. D. G. Leveson-Gower]] XI at the [[Scarborough Festival|Scarborough cricket festival]] came in just 25 minutes.<ref>Preston, 1949: p. 258.</ref>\n\n==Later playing career==\n[[File:BarnesMiniatureBat.jpg|thumb|Barnes plays a practical joke by using a miniature bat in [[Donald Bradman|Bradman]]'s testimonial match.]]\nAn important concern for Barnes, when returning from the United Kingdom to Australia, was to avoid paying customs [[Duty (economics)|duties]] on the enormous amount of goods he acquired through various deals during the tour. This included good quality English cloth, in very short supply in Australia at this time. Hearing a rumour that Customs officials were waiting in Sydney for him, Barnes disembarked at Melbourne and travelled to Sydney by train. The move worked and he sold his stock at a substantial profit, conservatively estimated to be equal to his tour fee.<ref>Smith, p. 130.</ref>\n\nBarnes played in Bradman's testimonial match at the MCG in December 1948, but otherwise made himself unavailable for first-class cricket, preferring to pursue business interests. He wrote a regular column for Sydney's ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]'', prosaically titled \"Like It or Lump It\", in which he often criticised the administration of the game and the amounts paid to Australia's leading cricketers.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\">Haigh and Frith, pp. 107\u2013111.</ref> Barnes was one of a number of cricket writers of the immediate post-war era who adopted a confrontational [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] style of journalism, in contrast to the more sedate reporting of the 1930s.<ref>Harte, pp. 401\u2013402.</ref>\n\n===Libel case===\n[[File:Barnes and lawyer.jpg|thumb|Barnes and his legal representative outside the venue of their libel case]]\nAt the beginning of the 1951\u201352 season, Barnes had a change of heart and returned to the New South Wales team in a bid to play Test cricket again. He approached [[Aubrey Oxlade]], the chairman of Australian cricket's [[Cricket Australia|Board of Control]], to ask if there was any impediment to his return to the Australian team. Oxlade told Barnes that he would be judged solely on his batting performances.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/>\n\nDuring his absence from the Test team, the Australian selectors had been unsuccessful in their attempts to find a reliable partner for Arthur Morris to open the batting. Barnes started the season solidly and, in the last match before the team for the third Test against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] was chosen, he hit 107 against Victoria. The selectors duly picked him for the match, then passed the team list to the Board of Control for ratification. The Board vetoed the inclusion of Barnes and requested the nomination of a replacement player. Unwilling to accept the blame for Barnes's omission, the selectors deliberately deferred their decision on the replacement.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> When the team was not announced at the scheduled time, journalists uncovered the story and Barnes became a ''[[cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre]]'' for many weeks, missing all of the remaining Tests. Speculation abounded as to the nature of his supposed misdeeds. These included jumping the turnstile at a ground when he forgot his player's pass; insulting the Royal Family; theft from team-mates; drunkenness; and stealing a car.<ref name=\"Harte1\">Harte, pp. 422\u2013423.</ref>\n\nThe Board of Control had granted themselves the power to exclude a player from the national team \"on grounds other than cricket ability\" following the poor behaviour of some members of the 1912 team that toured England.<ref>Harte, p. 256.</ref> They had a secret dossier, compiled during the season, documenting Barnes's behaviour and they doctored the minutes of the meeting at which they discussed his selection.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> Publicly, the Board remained silent on their policy and how it related to Barnes. On the field, Barnes responded with an innings of 128 in three hours against Queensland;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/20/20052.html\n|title= New South Wales v Queensland, Sheffield Shield 1951\u201352\n|date=1 January 1952\n|accessdate=3 December 2007}}</ref> off the field, he sought answers from the administrators, but was frustrated by their evasiveness. His form tapered off during the closing stages of the season and he finished with 433 first-class runs at an average of 39.36.<ref name=\"seasonbyseason\"/>\n\nJust as the furore appeared to have died down, in April 1952 Sydney's ''[[The Daily Mirror (Australia)|Daily Mirror]]'' published a letter from a reader, Jacob Raith.<ref>Smith, p. 155. \"Jacob Raith, a master baker, cricket lover from Sid's own suburb of Stanmore and a former president of Petersham Cricket Club&nbsp;...\" It continues down the same page, \"Rather than support the player, whom he did not know despite their associations with the same area, he decided to back the board.\"</ref> Responding to a letter in support of Barnes, Raith sided with the Board and suggested that his character was to blame for the omission.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> Acting on legal advice, Barnes sued Raith for [[Defamation|libel]] and engaged Sydney's leading [[barrister]], Jack Shand KC, as counsel.<ref>{{cite journal\n|last= Slee\n|first= John\n|year=2002\n|title=Shand, John Wentworth (1897\u20131959)'\n|journal= Australian Dictionary of Biography\n|volume=16\n|pages=216\u2013217\n|location= Melbourne\n|publisher=Melbourne University Press\n|url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A160257b.htm?hilite=Jack%3BShand\n|accessdate=4 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe case began in Sydney's District Court on 21 August 1952. Shand's examination of the various Board members appearing for the defendant revealed the Board's maladministration, pettiness and its acceptance of rumour as fact. No firm reason was put forward for the omission of Barnes and a division within the Board was evident when several of its members spoke highly of him.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> As Barnes began his testimony on the second day of proceedings, Raith's counsel announced settlement of the case and commented to the court, \"seldom in the history of libel actions has such a plea failed so completely and utterly\".<ref name=\"Harte1\"/> Barnes was vindicated with a full public apology.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/>\n\nAlthough the court case portrayed \"an awful image of the chaos and bigotry under which Australian cricket was administered\", it did little to alter the Board's culture. The next major court case involving Australian cricket, the [[World Series Cricket]] challenges of 1977\u201378 demonstrated that the Board was still run as a \"closed shop\", over 25 years later.<ref name=\"Harte1\"/> In an analysis of the Barnes libel case, [[Gideon Haigh]] wrote, \"far from becoming a watershed in player-administrator relations, it may even have discouraged players contemplating defiance of the Board but lacking the wherewithal to retain a hotshot criminal barrister.\"<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/>\n\n===Twelfth man incident===\n[[File:Sid Barnes, Adelaide Oval 1952.jpg|thumb|right|Barnes as twelfth man, dressed in suit and tie and carrying cigars, iced towels, a mirror and comb, a radio and a clothes brush]]\nResuming for New South Wales in 1952\u201353, Barnes scored 152 against Victoria in the last match before the beginning of the [[South African cricket team in Australia in 1952-53|Test series against South Africa]]. Nevertheless, the selectors overlooked him for the first Test and in the following state match, against South Australia at the [[Adelaide Oval]], Barnes offered to act as [[List of cricket terms#T|twelfth man]] to provide an opportunity for a younger player, [[Ray Flockton]]. During a drinks break on the second day of the match, he appeared on the ground in a suit and tie, (rather than [[Flannels|'whites']]) carrying superfluous items such as cigars, iced towels, a mirror and comb, a radio and a clothes brush. The crowd initially responded well to the joke, but their mood soured when the interval extended beyond its scheduled time and Barnes received criticism for delaying the game.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> The South Australian team, captained by Australian selector [[Phil Ridings]], officially complained to the [[New South Wales Cricket Association]] (NSWCA), which asked Barnes to express regret over the incident. Despite the association's support for Barnes during his problems of the previous season, he prevaricated. Eventually, the NSWCA forwarded a written apology on his behalf.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/>\n\nBarnes appeared just once more for New South Wales, against South Africa at New Year 1953, then made himself unavailable for selection, conceding that \"his card had been marked\".<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> The [[Australian cricket team in England in 1953|Australian team]] toured England in 1953 and lost the [[List of cricket terms#A|Ashes]] after holding them for 19 years. Barnes wrote ''Eyes on the Ashes'', a book about the tour that included trenchant criticism of the behaviour of the Australian team, which did not go down well with some of his former team-mates.<ref name=\"adb\"/>\n\n==Style and personality==\nBarnes gripped the bat very low on the handle and bent over so far in his stance that the knuckles of his right hand were level with his knees. He stood with his heels almost together and the toes of his left foot pointing toward extra cover, which left him open-chested when facing the bowler. A noticeable flourish in his backlift enabled him to follow the swinging delivery and play it late if necessary.<ref>Robinson, p. 78.</ref> His first movement was back and across the crease to cover the stumps from the view of the bowler, putting him in position to play the hook, leg glance, sweep and his favourite square cut shot.<ref>All of these terms are included in the [[List of cricket terms]].</ref>\n\nJournalist [[Ray Robinson (cricket writer)|Ray Robinson]] called Barnes the [[Artful Dodger]] of cricket, alluding to both his batting style and his off-field business dealings, and wrote that he \"would rather steal a run like a pickpocket than hit an honest four with a straightforward stroke.\"<ref>Robinson, p. 76.</ref> Robinson summarised his safety-first approach in going so far back as the bowler delivered:\n<blockquote>Though this routine made his play air-tight in one way, it simplified opposing captains' field-placing to curb his scoring, it left him with a back-foot addict's liability to go leg-before-wicket or be caught behind on either side, and it allowed his attackers to bowl their most awkward length&nbsp;... he could have made more runs since the war as a stroke-player, and won popular backing as a candidate for the title of world's best batsman, instead of the austere distinction of looking the hardest Australian to get out.<ref>Robinson, p. 79.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n[[David Frith]] wrote of [[Bill Brown (cricketer)|Bill Brown's]] memories of Barnes as a person, and his controversial fielding:\n<blockquote>\n'Bagga' Barnes was also Bill's room-mate, and his affection for his late lamented pal, a lovable rogue, was obvious. He recalled the furore over Barnes's provocative field positioning, extremely close at silly mid-on, and how criticism of his foot being too close to the mown pitch prompted him to plonk his boot a couple of feet into the forbidden territory \u2013 and a couple of feet more when the English crowd roared at him.<ref name=\"grandpa\"/></blockquote>\n\nHe was a part-time [[leg spin|leg break]] bowler, taking 57&nbsp;wickets in first-class cricket at a useful average of 32.21.<ref name=\"az\">Cashman, pp. 14\u201315.</ref> Barnes's leg break spun very little, but he had a [[topspinner]] which hurried onto the batsman and yielded him many wickets.<ref name=\"az\"/> Barnes was also a substitute wicket-keeper and a versatile fieldsman. During his career, he was noted for his disaffection for cricket administrators and umpires. On the 1948 tour of England, after an Australian [[appeal (cricket)|appeal]] was turned down by umpire [[Alec Skelding]], he grabbed a stray dog and presented it to Skelding, stating: \"Now all you want is a white stick\".<ref name=\"cricinfo\"/> A complex character, Barnes, \"rarely forgave a slight or forgot a good turn. Stocky, with blue eyes and powerful wrists, he had a passion for physical fitness, and was an enthusiastic big-game fisherman and golfer\".<ref name=\"adb\"/>\n\n==Life outside cricket==\n[[File:SidBarnesLaterLife.jpg|thumb|Barnes in later life]]\nBarnes married a schoolteacher, Alison Margaret Edward, on 11 June 1942. Alison was the daughter of Kenneth Edward, a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[Professor]] of [[Theology]] at the [[University of Sydney]]. The couple met at a country dance, when Barnes, on his way back from an [[exhibition match]] in [[Katoomba, New South Wales|Katoomba]], was bet the price of the meal that he could not get the young girl to dance with him. Within twelve months the pair were married.<ref>Smith, p. 44.</ref>\n\nOutside of cricket, Barnes followed his mother into [[real-estate developer|property development]] (see [[Sid Barnes#Early years|above]]) and at various times entered into partnerships with [[Keith Miller]] and [[Norman Von Nida]]. His suspicious nature, which grew as time passed, saw these partnerships and developments end in arguments and recriminations. While Barnes was not a millionaire, he was a successful and organised businessman.<ref>Smith, pp. 195\u2013196.</ref>\n\nAs a writer, Barnes had no claims to literary talent; his copy was [[ghostwriter|ghost-written]], in all likelihood by his friend Jack Tier and later by former professional [[rugby league]] footballer [[Peter Peters]].<ref>Smith, pp. 185\u2013186.</ref> His writing was of a provocative tone; his column in the ''[[Daily Express]]'' during the 1953 tour was called \"The Aussie They Couldn't Gag\". His forthright opinions certainly cost him friends and hardened the opinions of others about him.<ref>Smith, pp. 183\u2013184.</ref> At the end of the 1953 tour, he published ''Eyes on the Ashes'', and his autobiography, ''It Isn't Cricket''. He also wrote ''The Ashes Ablaze'' in 1955, and turned to full-time writing, mostly for Sydney's ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]''. His columns were perceived as being deliberately controversial, and, as time went by, increasingly regarded as carping.<ref name=\"az\"/>\n\nIn later life, Barnes suffered from depressive illness. He was diagnosed with [[bipolar disorder]] and treated with a combination of medication, mainly [[diazepam]], and [[electroconvulsive therapy]]. He spent much of his last years in and out of clinics seeking treatment for his condition.<ref>Smith, pp. 204\u2013205.</ref> In 1973, Barnes died at his home in [[Collaroy, New South Wales|Collaroy]], one of Sydney's northern beach suburbs, from [[barbiturate]] and [[bromide]] poisoning. Although the medications were certainly self-administered, the [[coroner]] could not \"determine intent\".<ref name=\"adb\"/> \n{{Clear}}\n\n==Statistical analysis==\n{{Cricket batting averages (10 innings)}}\nOnly six players with ten or more completed innings have achieved an end of career average in excess of 60. Barnes's 63.05 in 19&nbsp;innings ranks him as number three in the history of Test cricket, behind Sir [[Donald Bradman]] (99.94, 80&nbsp;innings) and [[Stewie Dempster]] (65.72, 15&nbsp;innings).<ref>There is no consensus within cricket on what is the appropriate minimum number of innings required when comparing career averages, to avoid statistical quirks caused by players of very short careers. [[Andy Ganteaume]], for example, played just one Test and scored a century. In Cricinfo's statistical analysis of leading career averages, ([http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/282910.html]) Barnes is omitted for having played just 19 (rather than the minimum of 20) innings. Likewise, there is no consensus on omitting current players, something which is done because when comparing career performances, most players experience a fall-off in average toward the end of their career; Cricinfo includes current players, including one ([[Mike Hussey]]) whose career average in December 2007 exceeded that of Barnes.</ref>\n\nBarnes's short career was dominated by his monumental double hundred, but he was a consistent performer, as the chart (left) reveals. Age did not seem to diminish his abilities; in his last eight Test innings, aged 31\u201332, he passed 50 five times and scored two of his three Test hundreds.<ref name=\"testlist\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/4098.html?class=1;template=results;type=allround;view=match |title= Statsguru \u2013 SG Barnes \u2013 Test matches \u2013 All-round analysis |accessdate=15 April 2008| publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref> [[File:Sid Barnes graph.png|thumb|left|300px|Sid Barnes's Test batting performances. The red bars indicate the runs that he scored in an innings, with the blue line indicating the [[batting average (cricket)|batting average]] in his last ten innings. The blue dots indicate an innings where he remained [[not out]].<ref name=\"testlist\"/>]]\n\nComparing players from Test cricket is an exercise usually flawed by the different conditions, rules of the day and oppositions faced. However, a useful comparison can be made between Barnes and Bradman because they were contemporaries in the same team. Bradman is generally acknowledged as the greatest [[batsman]] of all time,<ref name=\"Cricinfo1\">{{cite web\n|url = http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/content/player/4188.html\n|title = Sir Donald Bradman\n|publisher = [[Cricinfo]]\n|accessdate = 25 December 2007}}</ref> fully a third better (statistically) than the next best man in history (see completed career averages chart, right). Barnes and Bradman\nplayed together in three series.<ref>There was also a fourth, the 1938 Ashes, but Barnes played only one Test.</ref><ref name=\"Compare\">{{cite web\n|url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/guru?sdb=compare;playerid=711;class=testplayer;filter=basic;team=0;opposition=0;notopposition=0;season=0;homeaway=0;continent=0;country=0;notcountry=0;groundid=0;startdefault=1938-08-20;start=1938-08-20;enddefault=1948-08-18;end=1948-08-18;tourneyid=0;finals=0;daynight=0;toss=0;scheduledovers=0;scheduleddays=0;innings=0;result=0;followon=0;seriesresult=0;captain=0;keeper=0;dnp=0;recent=;runslow=;runshigh=;batposition=0;dismissal=0;bowposition=0;ballslow=;ballshigh=;bpof=0;overslow=;overshigh=;conclow=;conchigh=;wicketslow=;wicketshigh=;dismissalslow=;dismissalshigh=;caughtlow=;caughthigh=;caughttype=0;stumpedlow=;stumpedhigh=;viewtype=com_compare;csearch=bradman;cplayerid=492;comparetype=bat_series;compare=1;.cgifields=comparetype\n|title = Statsguru \u2013 SG Barnes \u2013 Test Batting \u2013 Comparison\n|publisher = [[Cricinfo]]\n|accessdate = 25 December 2007}}</ref> In those series, Barnes's averages bear comparison to Bradman's, particularly in the more combatitive [[The Ashes|Ashes]] series:<ref name=\"Compare\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n! width=15% | Barnes\n! width=15% | Bradman\n|-\n| [[English cricket team in Australia in 1946\u201347]]\n| align=right | 73.83\n| align=right | 97.14\n|-\n| [[Indian cricket team in Australia in 1947\u201348]]\n| align=right | 43.00\n| align=right | 178.75\n|-\n| [[Australian cricket team in England in 1948]]\n| align=right | 82.25\n| align=right | 72.57\n|}\n\nAnother way of viewing a player's performance without distortion is by using the [[ICC Player Rankings|world rankings]], which have been applied retrospectively to assess the careers of past players. However, the ratings employ a measure to \"damp down the oscillation of points of new players\".<ref name=\"Ratings\">{{cite web\n|url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/16/16093.html\n|title = Frequently Asked Questions\n|publisher = LG ICC Rankings\n|accessdate = 25 December 2007}}</ref> Because Barnes played only 19 Test innings, his performances are weighted to just under 85% of their full value.<ref name=\"Ratings\"/> Consequently, even in his own day, he is rated as no better than seventh in the world, at his peak.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.lgiccrankings.com/test/batting/player-display.php?id=562&graph=ranking\n|title = Sid Barnes Batting Test Ranking Statistics\n|publisher = LG ICC Rankings\n|accessdate = 25 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Test match performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" width=\"80%\"\n|-\n!colspan=2| &nbsp;\n!colspan=4| Batting<ref name=\"batsum\">{{cite web\n |url        = http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/4098.html?class=1;template=results;type=batting\n |title      = Statsguru \u2013 SG Barnes \u2013 Test matches \u2013 Batting analysis\n |accessdate = 19 June 2008\n |publisher  = [[Cricinfo]]\n}}</ref>\n!colspan=4| Bowling<ref name=\"bowlsum\">{{cite web\n| url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/4098.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling\n| accessdate = 19 June 2008\n| title = Statsguru \u2013 SG Barnes \u2013 Test Bowling \u2013 Bowling analysis\n| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Opposition\n!| Matches\n!| Runs\n!| Average\n!| High Score\n!| 100 / 50\n!| Runs\n!| Wickets\n!| Average\n!| Best (Inns)\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[England cricket team|England]]\n|| 9\n|| 846\n|| 70.50\n|| 234\n|| 2/4\n|| 118\n|| 1\n|| 118.00\n|| 1/84\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[India national cricket team|India]]\n|| 3\n|| 172\n|| 43.00\n|| 112\n|| 1/0\n|| 100\n|| 3\n|| 33.33\n|| 2/25\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]]\n|| 1\n|| 54\n|| 54.00\n|| 54\n|| 0/1\n|| \u2013\n|| \u2013\n|| \u2013\n|| \u2013\n|- style=\"text-align:right; border-top:solid 2px grey;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Overall\n|| 13\n|| 1072\n|| 63.05\n|| 234\n|| 3/5\n|| 218\n|| 4\n|| 54.50\n|| 2/25\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last = Barnes|first= Sid|year= 1953|title = It Isn't Cricket|publisher = Collins| location = London and Sydney}}\n* {{cite book|authorlink=Gideon Haigh| last=Haigh |first=Gideon|author2=Frith, David |authorlink2=David Frith  |year= 2007 |title=Inside Story: Unlocking Australian Cricket's Archives |location=Southbank, Victoria |publisher=News Custom Publishing |isbn= 1-921116-00-5}}\n* {{cite book|last=Harte |first=Chris |year=1993 |title=A History of Australian Cricket |publisher=Andre Deutsch |isbn=0-233-98825-4}}\n* Preston, Hubert (ed., 1949): ''Wisden Cricketers' Almanack, 1949'', London: John Wisden.\n* Robinson, Ray (1985): ''After Stumps Were Drawn\u2014the Best Of Ray Robinson's Cricket Writing'', Collins. {{ISBN|0-00-216583-X}}.\n* {{cite book |last=Smith |first=Rick |title=Cricket's Enigma: The Sid Barnes Story |year=1999 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |location=Sydney |isbn=0-7333-0787-6}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Sid Barnes}}\n* {{cricinfo|id=4098}}\n\n{{The Invincibles squad}}\n{{Australian first-class cricket season leading run-scorers (1900\u201301 to 1949\u201350)}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Sid}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:New South Wales cricketers]]\n[[Category:Australia Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:The Invincibles (cricket)]]\n[[Category:Drug-related deaths in Australia]]\n[[Category:Barbiturates-related deaths]]\n[[Category:People with bipolar disorder]]\n[[Category:Australian cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Sydney]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian cricketer}}\n{{about||the similarly named English cricketer|Sydney Barnes|the American singer and songwriter|Sidney Barnes (musician)}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Sid Barnes\n| image = SidBarnesHeadshot.jpg\n| caption = Barnes in cricket whites\n| alt = Barnes wearing his Australian cricket cap and sweater\n| country = Australia\n| fullname = Sidney George Barnes\n| nickname = Bagga<ref name=\"grandpa\">{{cite journal\n | last = Frith\n | first = David\n | author1-link = David Frith\n | title = What did you do at Lord's, Grandpa?\n | journal = [[Wisden Cricket Monthly]]\n | year = 1987\n | url = http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/wcm/content/story/70460.html\n | accessdate = 3 December 2007 }}</ref><br>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1916|6|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Annandale, New South Wales]], Australia\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1973|12|16|1916|6|5|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Collaroy, New South Wales]], Australia\n| heightft =\n| heightinch =\n| heightm =\n| batting = Right-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[leg break]]\n| role = Batsman, occasional [[wicket-keeper]]\n| international = true\n| testdebutdate = 20 August\n| testdebutyear = 1938\n| testdebutagainst = England\n| testcap = 163\n| lasttestdate = 14 August\n| lasttestyear = 1948\n| lasttestagainst = England\n| club1 = [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]]\n| year1 = {{nowrap|1936/37\u20131952/53}}\n| columns = 2\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Tests]]\n| matches1 = 13\n| runs1 = 1,072\n| bat avg1 = 63.05\n| 100s/50s1 = 3/5\n| top score1 = 234\n| deliveries1 = 564\n| wickets1 = 4\n| bowl avg1 = 54.50\n| fivefor1 = 0\n| tenfor1 = 0\n| best bowling1 = 2/25\n| catches/stumpings1 = 14/\u2013\n| column2 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n| matches2 = 110\n| runs2 = 8,333\n| bat avg2 = 54.11\n| 100s/50s2 = 26/37\n| top score2 = 234\n| deliveries2 = 4,451\n| wickets2 = 57\n| bowl avg2 = 32.21\n| fivefor2 = 0\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 3/0\n| catches/stumpings2 = 80/4\n| date= 28 November\n| year = 2007\n| source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/0/711/711.html CricketArchive\n}}\n'''Sidney George Barnes''' (5 June 1916 \u2013 16 December 1973) was an Australian [[cricket]]er and cricket writer, who played 13&nbsp;[[Test cricket|Test matches]] between 1938 and 1948. Able to [[Batting order (cricket)#Opening batsmen|open the innings]] or [[Batting order (cricket)#Top order|bat down the order]], Barnes was regarded as one of Australia's finest batsmen in the period immediately following the [[World War II|Second World War]]. He helped create an enduring record when scoring 234&nbsp;in the second Test against England at Sydney in December 1946; exactly the same score as his captain, [[Donald Bradman|Don Bradman]], in the process setting a world-record 405-run [[wicket#Partnership|fifth wicket]] [[partnership (cricket)|partnership]]. Barnes averaged 63.05 over 19 innings in a career that, like those of most of his contemporaries, was interrupted by the Second World War.\n\nHe made his [[First-class cricket|first-class]] debut at the end of the 1936\u201337 season when selected for [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]], and he was later included in the team for the [[Australian cricket team in England in 1938|1938 Australian tour of England]], making his Test debut in the final international of the series. On the resumption of Test cricket after the war, he was picked as the opening partner to [[Arthur Morris]]. Barnes was a member of [[Australian cricket team in England in 1948|''The Invincibles'']], the 1948 Australian team that toured England without losing a single match. Retiring from cricket at the end of that tour, Barnes attempted a comeback to Test cricket in the 1951\u201352 season that was ultimately and controversially unsuccessful.<ref>As a convention, cricket seasons are denoted as a single year to represent northern hemisphere summer, or dashed for southern hemisphere. See [[Cricket season]] for more information.</ref>\n\nBarnes had a reputation as an eccentric and was frequently the subject of controversy. This included a celebrated [[Defamation|libel]] case, following his exclusion from the national team in 1951\u201352 for \"reasons other than cricket ability\". He was later involved in an incident where, acting as [[List of cricket terms#T|twelfth man]], he performed his duties on the ground in a suit and tie (rather than [[Flannels|'whites']]), carrying a bizarre range of superfluous items. Despite this reputation, Barnes was a shrewd businessman who used the opportunities afforded by cricket to supplement his income through trading, journalism and [[Real-estate developer|property development]]. Increasing [[paranoia]] brought about by [[bipolar disorder]] saw Barnes lose many of the friends he had made through the game as he sought treatment for his depression. On 16 December 1973, he was found dead at his home in the Sydney suburb of [[Collaroy, New South Wales|Collaroy]]; he had ingested [[barbiturate]]s and [[bromide]] in a probable suicide.\n\n==Early years==\nBarnes was born in 1916 in [[Annandale, New South Wales|Annandale]], an inner suburb of Sydney.<ref>Smith, p.3. \"was born in Annandale on 5 June 1916. She christened him Sidney George after the city of his birth and his maternal grandfather. Sid's place of birth would remain a problem for many years to come. He always thought it was [[Charters Towers, Queensland|Charters Towers]] in [[Queensland]] and said so in his autobiography. He also confessed confusion over the year citing 1918 or 1919, rather than 1916.\"</ref> However, in his autobiography, he claims to have been born in 1918 or 1919 in [[Queensland]],<ref>Barnes, p. 13.</ref> and his military service record has his date of birth as 5 June 1917.<ref>[http://naa12.naa.gov.au/scripts/ItemDetail.asp?M=0&B=5659359 Military service record], National Archives</ref> He was the third child of Alfred Percival Barnes and Hilda May Barnes (n\u00e9e Jeffery), both from farming families near [[Tamworth, New South Wales|Tamworth]] in northern [[New South Wales]]. After marrying, the couple left Tamworth to take up a lease on a remote [[sheep station]] near [[Hughenden, Queensland|Hughenden]] in North Queensland. Before Sid was born, Alfred died from [[typhoid fever]], caused by drinking contaminated water on the family property. After his death, Hilda, widowed and pregnant with her latest child, moved to Sydney with her children and stayed with her sister, where Sid was born. From her husband's estate, Hilda Barnes mother was able to purchase and renovate real estate in [[Stanmore, New South Wales|Stanmore]] and [[Leichhardt, New South Wales|Leichhardt]],&nbsp;New South Wales, to let or sell. Later in life, Barnes would recount how, as a child, he used to collect the rents for his mother.<ref>Smith, pp. 2\u20133.</ref>\n\n===Childhood and club cricket===\n[[File:Sid Barnes, 16 Petersham.jpg|thumb|left|Barnes, aged 16, as a Petersham player]]\nBarnes attended [[Stanmore, New South Wales#Schools|Stanmore Public School]] and, although not a scholar, was a keen participant in sporting activities.<ref>Smith, p. 5.</ref> His introduction to cricket came via his older brother, Horrie; Horrie was a useful batsman who played in the local Western Suburbs Churches league and paid Sid [[Sixpence (Australian)|sixpence]] to bowl to him after he finished work. Taking an interest in the game, Sid had trials for the school team and was eventually selected in the first XI. An early controversy saw Barnes suspended for three weeks for disputing an [[umpire (cricket)|umpire]]'s decision.<ref name=\"smith10\">Smith, p. 10.</ref> Successes for both his school team and his local club team, St. Augustine, saw him acquire the nickname ''The Governor-General''\u2014the nickname of Australian Test player, [[Charlie Macartney]], and he was selected for New South Wales Schoolboys to play teams from [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and [[Queensland]].<ref name=\"smith10\"/>\n\nIn 1932\u201333, Barnes joined the [[Petersham, New South Wales|Petersham]] club, and began playing in the third XI. Former Test batsman [[Tommy Andrews (cricketer)|Tommy Andrews]] became his mentor at the club and in 1933\u201334, Barnes made his [[Sydney Grade Cricket|first-grade cricket]] debut as a [[batsman]]/[[wicket-keeper]] against Paddington, facing the bowling of [[Hunter Hendry]] and [[Alan McGilvray]].<ref>Smith, pp. 11\u201313.</ref> He was soon successful, scoring a century against Manly in February. Even as a young and inexperienced cricketer, he showed a \"brash confidence in his own ability.\"<ref name=\"adb\">{{cite journal\n|last = Stoddart\n|first = Brian\n|year = 2002\n|title = 'Barnes, Sidney George (Sid) (1916\u20131973)'\n|journal = Australian Dictionary of Biography\n|volume = 13\n|pages =118\u2013119\n|location = Melbourne\n|publisher = Melbourne University Press\n|url = http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A130142b.htm\n|accessdate = 4 December 2007}}</ref>\nWhen praised for his batting by the great Test bowler [[Bill O'Reilly (cricketer)|Bill O'Reilly]], Barnes responded \"Thanks very much, you didn't bowl too badly yourself\", leaving O'Reilly speechless.<ref>Smith, p. 13.</ref>\n\nThis success led Barnes to consider cricket as a potential career. However, his mother and stepfather were concerned about the likelihood of cricket providing him with a living. In response, Barnes took a job with a [[Automobile repair shop|garage]] in [[Mosman, New South Wales|Mosman]] but after finding that the necessary travel interfered too much with playing cricket, he found alternative employment, demonstrating motorbikes in the city.<ref>Smith, pp. 13\u201314.</ref>\n\n===First-class cricket===\nBarnes had come to the attention of the [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]] selectors by the 1936\u201337 season and was included as [[List of cricket terms#T|twelfth man]] in the side to play the [[English cricket team in Australia in 1936-37|visiting English side]], taking a catch on the boundary to dismiss [[Stan Worthington]].<ref>Smith, p. 15.</ref> He made his [[First-class cricket|first-class]] debut in the final [[Pura Cup|Sheffield Shield]] match of the season, against [[Southern Redbacks|South Australia]] at the [[Sydney Cricket Ground]].<ref name=\"Debut\">Smith, pp. 7\u20138.</ref> Batting at [[Batting order (cricket)#Middle order|number five]], Barnes scored 31&nbsp;and 44, twice being dismissed [[leg before wicket|LBW]] by the [[leg spin]]ner [[Frank Ward (cricketer, born 1906)|Frank Ward]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/16/16093.html\n|title = New South Wales v South Australia\u2013Sheffield Shield 1936/37\n|date = 23 February 1937\n|publisher = CricketArchive\n|accessdate = 3 December 2007}}</ref> Whilst fielding, Barnes managed to find himself in controversy again, [[run out|running out]] [[Vic Richardson]], the opposition captain, after the end of the [[over (cricket)|over]] was called. The square leg umpire had not heard the call of \"Over\" and upheld the [[appeal (cricket)|appeal]], much to the disgust of Richardson. The New South Wales captain [[Stan McCabe]], whom Barnes idolised, withdrew the appeal.<ref name=\"Debut\"/>\n\nBarnes was selected for New South Wales for the opening match of the 1937\u201338 season against [[Queensland Bulls|Queensland]] making 68 in a rain-affected match. Against the touring [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealanders]], Barnes fell just short of his maiden first-class century, scoring 97.<ref name=\"1937 season\">Smith, pp. 17\u201318.</ref> He appeared to have reached the landmark when scoring 127&nbsp;[[not out]] against [[Western Warriors|Western Australia]], but the [[New South Wales Cricket Association]] retrospectively deemed the match to be not of first-class status, angering Barnes.<ref name=\"1937 season\"/> He finally scored his maiden first-class century (110) against Victoria in the final game of the season, completing his hundred while bleeding profusely after being struck on the jaw by a ball delivered by [[Ernie McCormick]].<ref>Smith, p. 20.</ref> As a result of his performances over the season (scoring over 800 [[run (cricket)|runs]], averaging 50.56),<ref name=\"seasonbyseason\">{{cite web\n|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/0/711/f_Batting_by_Season.html\n|title =First-class Batting and Fielding in Each Season by Sid Barnes\n|publisher= CricketArchive\n|accessdate=3 December 2007}}</ref> Barnes was selected as the youngest member of the [[Australian cricket team in England in 1938|Australian cricket team to tour England in 1938]].<ref>Smith, p. 21.</ref>\n\n==Test cricket==\n[[File:Sid Barnes.jpg|thumb|Cigarette card showing Barnes as a New South Wales representative]]\n\n===Pre-war debut===\nUnfortunately for Barnes, he broke his wrist while exercising on the sea voyage to England for the 1938 tour,<ref name=\"insideedge\">{{cite magazine|author= |title=The 50 Greatest Australian Cricketers |magazine=[[Inside Edge (magazine)|Inside Edge]]|publisher=ACP |year=2001|page=56 }}</ref> keeping the injury secret until the tourists had departed [[Gibraltar]], for fear of being sent home.<ref>Smith p. 26., quoting Barnes \"I had jog-trotted six times around the ship the morning we were due to land in Gibraltar and I started stretching exercises. I leapt to catch the steel rope running across the deck to hold up the sun awnings but the early morning mist had made the stachion slippery and I couldn't hold it. I slipped back and, in falling, threw out my left hand to break the fall. I fell with all my weight on the left hand&nbsp;...\" Smith continues, \"A few hours later the pain increased and the hand started to swell. He said nothing just in case there was a ship in Gibraltar on its way back to Australia&nbsp;...\"</ref> On arrival in England, he therefore did not play an innings until the last day of June, missing exactly half of the 30&nbsp;first-class matches scheduled for the tour, including the first two Tests, both of which were drawn. His first innings was 42 against [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] and he shared in a fourth&nbsp;wicket stand of 176 with [[Bill Brown (cricketer)|Bill Brown]], who made an unbeaten 265.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1939\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Australians in England in 1938\n| page = 227\n}}</ref> The third Test was a wash-out and he was not picked for the fourth, which the Australians won, although in his autobiography he claimed that he was considered as a candidate to be wicketkeeper, having deputised for [[Ben Barnett]] in that role in tour matches against [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]] and [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]].<ref>Barnes, p. 78.</ref> In the event, his Test debut came in the final Test, played at [[The Oval]].<ref name=\"testlist\"/> Barnes had to field for 16 hours as England amassed a total of 903&nbsp;for seven&nbsp;declared, then the highest Test score.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283966.html\n| title = Test matches Highest innings totals\n| accessdate = 12 December 2007\n| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]\n}}</ref> Barnes bowled 38&nbsp;overs in the innings and took the seventh wicket, that of [[Arthur Wood (cricketer, born 1898)|Arthur Wood]], for 84&nbsp;runs. With both [[Donald Bradman|Don Bradman]] and [[Jack Fingleton]] injured and unable to bat, Australia struggled \u2013 England won by an innings and 579&nbsp;runs \u2013 still the largest winning margin in Test cricket history;<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/210099.html\n| title = Test matches Largest margin of victory (by an innings)\n| accessdate = 12 December 2007\n| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]\n}}</ref> but Barnes played innings of 41 and 33 and, according to ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]'', \"well justified his choice\".<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1939\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Australians in England in 1938\n| pages = 243\u2013246\n}}</ref> In all first-class matches on the tour, Barnes scored 720&nbsp;runs, and reached 90 three times, though without going on to a first-class century. He scored 140 in a two-day match against [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]], which was not considered first-class.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1939\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Australians in England in 1938\n| pages = 195\u2013253\n}}</ref>\n\nHis international career was then put on hold, as all foreign tours were suspended during the Second World War. He continued to play first-class cricket in Australia, before enlisting in the [[Second Australian Imperial Force]] in May 1942.<ref name=\"cricinfo\">{{cite journal\n|url=http://content-www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/player/4098.html\n|title= Sid Barnes Obituary\n|journal= [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n|year= 1974\n|accessdate= 4 December 2007}}</ref> Barnes's time in the military was short. A man who was proud of his appearance, he had a uniform made to measure when the one issued did not fit. He met champion golfer [[Norman Von Nida]] early into his enlistment and the two were assigned to the [[1st Armoured Division (Australia)|1st Armoured Division]] in [[Greta, New South Wales|Greta]]. A shortage of tanks and the military regimen led to boredom and Barnes used his hitherto ignored trade background to his advantage, seeking a release to join a tank-making company, which was granted. Von Nida and Barnes remained friends and business partners for many years afterwards.<ref>Smith, p. 47.</ref>\n\n===Post-war series===\nAfter scoring 1,050&nbsp;runs (including six centuries) at an average of 75.00 in the 1940\u201341 season,<ref name=\"seasonbyseason\"/> Barnes played little cricket until 1945\u201346, when he scored centuries in five successive matches for New South Wales.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Seasons/Seasonal_Averages/AUS/1945-46_f_Match_List.html\n|publisher=CricketArchive\n|title= First-Class matches in Australia in 1945/46\n|accessdate=29 November 2007}}</ref> He was picked for the [[History of cricket in New Zealand from 1945-46 to 1970#Australia 1945-46|1945\u201346 Australian tour of New Zealand]] and played in the representative match that was later designated as the first Test match between the two countries: he made 54 as Australia won easily.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1947\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Overseas Cricket\n| page = 629\n}}</ref> The post-war period also saw a new approach to batting on the part of Barnes. He discarded his aggressive and flamboyant shot-making and re-invented himself as a watchful, more defensive player, which made his scoring more prolific, although less crowd pleasing.<ref name=\"az\"/>\n\nBarnes was made captain of New South Wales for the 1946\u201347 Australian season, though he only managed to play three matches for the state team. One of those was the match against [[MCC tour of Australia in 1946\u201347|the touring MCC team]], and Barnes was approached during the match about becoming an [[Batting order (cricket)#Opening batsmen|opening batsman]] for the [[1946-47 Ashes series|forthcoming Test series]]. He wrote in his autobiography: \"I had never opened before and was a little dubious. I had, however, struck new balls at different periods of innings and was not afraid of that.\"<ref>Barnes, p. 115. Barnes does not identify who it was that approached him.</ref> He also liked the idea of batting ahead of Bradman in the batting order: \"Much better, I thought, to get in before him than to come later, like flat beer after champagne.\"\n\nBarnes was first-choice as an opener with [[Arthur Morris]] throughout the Test series, although it was not until the [[1946-47 Ashes series#Third Test \u2013 Melbourne|Third Test]] that they had a first-wicket partnership of any substance. Morris had broken into the team as an opener after an injury sidelined Bill Brown for the entire season.<ref>{{cite book | author = Cashman | author2 = Franks | author3 = Maxwell | author4 = Sainsbury | author5 = Stoddart | author6 = Weaver | author7 = Webster | year = 1997 | title = The A-Z of Australian cricketers|page =67}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1946-47 Ashes series#First Test \u2013 Brisbane|First Test at Brisbane]] was dominated by Australia, a pattern that was to be a feature of the series, although Barnes contributed only 31 to the total of 645 which brought an innings victory.<ref name=\"Teamin\">{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1948\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = M.C.C. Team in Australia and New Zealand, 1946\u201347\n| pages = 728\u2013730\n}}</ref> Barnes displayed his liking for slightly aggressive practical jokes in this match: during a break for a particularly ferocious thunderstorm, he <blockquote>got a huge block of ice out of the tub in which our drinks were kept, staggered to the side of the dressing-room and tossed it on to the roof over the English dressing-room. It caused a noise for a start that brought all the Englishmen running and then it came over the side of the gutter, crashed on to the lawn and slithered down the grass. Those English eyes certainly did stand out.<ref>Barnes, p. 117.</ref></blockquote>\n\nBradman had words with Barnes after this match about his new role as an opener. Barnes later wrote: <blockquote>He asked me how I liked it. I said it suited me. 'You batted very well in this game,' he said, 'but not quite as an opener. You were looking for runs all the time. I think what you want to watch as an opener is not getting out&nbsp;... What is needed from my openers, and is most important, is patience and plenty of it.' I was completely willing to be guided by anything that Bradman wanted me to do.<ref>Barnes, p. 118.</ref></blockquote>\n\nYears later, Barnes wrote about the effect this had on his batting style. <blockquote>There was one angle about this change of batting position that didn't appeal to me. I am, by nature, a forcing batsman. I like to take the shine out of a bowler [sic] and I love to hear the ball rattling the pickets, or soaring over the fence&nbsp;... My footwork was quick and I often caused delight by stepping back feet outside the leg stump and square-cutting&nbsp;... If I were to become an Australian Test opening batsman I would have to conform to standard. I would have to put up the shutters&nbsp;... And so I came to the [[1946-47 Ashes series#Second Test \u2013 Sydney|Second Test in Sydney]] ready to drape myself in the gloomy colors of a Test opening batsman.<ref>Barnes, pp. 121\u2013122.</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Bradman Barnes 234.jpg|thumb|Bradman and Barnes leave the field for an adjournment as both head towards 234.]]\nIt was during the [[1946-47 Ashes series#Second Test \u2013 Sydney|Second Test at Sydney]] in December 1946, that Barnes made a lasting impression on the world game. Having [[Batting order (cricket)#Opening batsmen|opened the innings]], he made his top Test score of 234 and helped to set a world-record 405&nbsp;run [[wicket#Partnership|fifth wicket]] [[partnership (cricket)|partnership]] with [[Donald Bradman|Don Bradman]], a record that still stands today.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://content-www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/62666.html\n| title = The Ashes \u2013 2nd Test \u2013 1946/47 season\n| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]\n| accessdate = 28 November 2007\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/283583.html\n| title = Test Matches \u2013 Highest partnership for the fifth wicket\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n| accessdate = 28 November 2007\n}}</ref>\nOn a rain-affected pitch [[Arthur Morris]] was out at 1/24 and [[Ian Johnson (cricketer)|Ian Johnson]] came out as a [[Nightwatchman (cricket)|nightwatchman]] He and Barnes angered the crowd by launching into a [[Umpiring in the 1946\u201347 Ashes series#Bad Light|series of bad light appeals]] \u2013 up to 12 were counted \u2013 before the umpires gave way and play was ended with an hour to spare.<ref>pp32-33, [[Clif Cary]], ''Cricket Controversy, Test matches in Australia 1946\u201347'', T. Werner Laurie Ltd., 1948</ref> This ensured that Australia would not have to play on a sticky wicket and allowed Bradman to rest his leg until play resumed on the Monday. After the series Barnes said on radio:\n<blockquote>\nWe could have played on, but it was a Test match and we just had to win. I realised something drastic had to be done or three wickets might be lost. So I appealed after every second ball. I complained of the people moving about, the light, and, in fact, anything, in an effort to get the appeal upheld. [[Wally Hammond|Hammond]] and [[Norman Yardley|Yardley]] were inspecting the wet pitch. I knew there was a chance of losing valuable wickets so I just kept on appealing until the umpires answered me.<ref>p32, [[Clif Cary]], ''Cricket Controversy, Test matches in Australia 1946\u201347'', T. Werner Laurie Ltd., 1948</ref>\n</blockquote>\nBarnes played carefully on the still-suspect pitch the following day, and, late in the afternoon, Bradman, lower in the order than usual due to a leg injury, joined Barnes with the score at 4/159.<ref>Score given in Australian convention, i.e. four wickets down with the score at 159.</ref> Over six and a half hours later, Bradman was out for 234. Barnes was dismissed just four balls later, also for 234, having batted for over ten hours.<ref name=\"200seasons\">{{cite book\n| last=Hutchinson\n| first= Garrie\n| editor= Ross, John\n| title = 200 Seasons of Australian Cricket\n| year = 1997\n| location= Sydney\n| publisher = Macmillan\n| isbn =0-330-36034-5\n|page= 287}}</ref> In his autobiography, Barnes stated that the coincidence of scores was intended. \"Lots of people have asked me whether I deliberately threw my wicket away at 234. The answer is yes.\"<ref>Barnes, p. 125.</ref> He confirmed to an interviewer many years later that \"it wouldn't be right for someone to make more runs than Sir Donald Bradman\".<ref>{{cite book\n|title=Legends of the Baggy Green\n|year=2004\n|last=Buzo\n|first=Alexander\n|authorlink=Alex Buzo\n|page=81\n|publisher= [[Allen & Unwin]]\n|location= St. Leonard's, New South Wales\n|isbn=1-74114-385-3}}</ref>\n[[E.W. Swanton]] wrote that this \"could well have been so for he was a man of [[Quixotism|quixotic]] mood and temperament\".<ref>p63, [[E.W. Swanton]], ''Swanton in Australia with MCC 1946\u20131975'', Fontana/Collins, 1975</ref> However the England bowler, [[Alec Bedser]] wrote \"It was when I was bowling to Sid at Sydney that I first discovered that I could move the ball to leg by use of my wrist and fingers...I held the ball in the same manner as a [[wrist spin|leg-break bowler]] with the fingers across the seam...and on pitching I was surprised to see the ball go away like a leg-break. It also surprised Sid Barnes\".<ref>pp7-8, [[Alec Bedser]], ''May's Men in Australia, The M.C.C. Tour 1958\u201359'', Stanley Paul, 1959</ref> This would make Barnes the first batsman to be dismissed by Bedser's \"Special Ball\" which would claim Bradman for a duck in the [[1946-47 Ashes series#Fourth Test \u2013 Adelaide|Fourth Test at Adelaide]].\n\nBarnes injured his hand during fielding practice before the [[1946-47 Ashes series#Third Test \u2013 Melbourne|Third Test]], and although he went on to play in that game (scoring 45 and 32), he opted out of batting in a state game \u2013 according to his autobiography, this cost him the New South Wales captaincy \u2013<ref>Barnes, p. 127.</ref> and he missed the fourth Test. He returned for the final Test and top-scored with 71 in Australia's first innings, adding 30 in the second.<ref name=\"Teamin\" />\n\nBarnes went to England in 1947. In his autobiography, he claimed that he went as a representative for a wine and spirits company, although after the initial mention of that there is no further word and he appears also to have dealt in commodities that were in short supply because of rationing in England.<ref>Barnes, pp. 139\u2013147.</ref> Once in England, he was approached by [[Burnley Cricket Club|Burnley]] to play as a professional in [[Lancashire League (cricket)|Lancashire League]] cricket, which he did for a while before finding it \"too much of a drag\" and resigning.<ref>Barnes, pp. 146.</ref>\n\nBarnes returned to Australia for the 1947\u201348 season, keen to win a place on the 1948 tour to England. He was worried that having played as a professional in the Lancashire League would damage his chance of further Test cricket, but at the same time suggested that he had offers from other Lancashire League teams to fall back on should he not be picked. There was also concern that, with his wife now living in Scotland, he would breach the Australian rule that wives were not allowed to travel with Test cricketers.<ref>Barnes, pp. 151\u2013158.</ref> In fact, lack of form and opportunity were greater threats to Barnes's continued Test career. Arriving back with several state games having already been played, he failed to make runs for New South Wales and was not picked for the first two Tests against [[Indian cricket team in Australia in 1947-48|the Indian tourists]], Bill Brown taking over as opener with Morris.\n\nThe match between Victoria and New South Wales was Barnes's chance to redeem himself. ''Wisden'' reported it thus: <blockquote>\nBarnes needed a score to rehabilitate himself in the eyes of the Test Selectors and he spent all Saturday over 131&nbsp;runs while 20,000 impatient spectators barracked loudly. His dismissal on the third day evoked cheers all round the ground.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1949\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Overseas Cricket\n| page = 793\n}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nHe followed that century (158 in total) with a similarly plodding 80&nbsp;not out in the second innings, and was picked for the third Test, with Brown dropped after a series of low scores in the first two Tests.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/guru?sdb=player;playerid=636;class=testplayer;filter=basic;team=0;opposition=0;notopposition=0;season=0;homeaway=0;continent=0;country=0;notcountry=0;groundid=0;startdefault=1934-06-08;start=1934-06-08;enddefault=1948-06-29;end=1948-06-29;tourneyid=0;finals=0;daynight=0;toss=0;scheduledovers=0;scheduleddays=0;innings=0;result=0;followon=0;seriesresult=0;captain=0;keeper=0;dnp=0;recent=;viewtype=aro_list;runslow=;runshigh=;batposition=0;dismissal=0;bowposition=0;ballslow=;ballshigh=;bpof=0;overslow=;overshigh=;conclow=;conchigh=;wicketslow=;wicketshigh=;dismissalslow=;dismissalshigh=;caughtlow=;caughthigh=;caughttype=0;stumpedlow=;stumpedhigh=;csearch=;submit=1;.cgifields=viewtype\n| title = Bill Brown Test performances\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n| accessdate = 11 December 2007\n}}</ref> Barnes made only 12 and 15, jeopardising his place, but what ''Wisden'' termed \"another of his dour, determined but faultless innings for top score\" in the New South Wales game against South Australia ensured a second chance.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1949\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = Overseas Cricket\n| page = 794\n}}</ref> In the fourth Test at [[Adelaide Oval|Adelaide]] he made 112 and put on 236 with Bradman for the second wicket.<ref>{{Cite book\n| title = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]\n| edition = 1949\n| publisher = [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]\n| chapter = India in Australia, 1947\u201348\n| page = 780\n}}</ref> With 33 in the final match of the series, his place on the 1948 tour was secure, though he had to give assurances about the amount of contact he would have with his wife, still living in Scotland, before he was confirmed.<ref>Barnes, p. 158.</ref>\n\n===''The Invincibles'' tour===\n{{main|Sid Barnes with the Australian cricket team in England in 1948}}\n{{see also|Australian cricket team in England in 1948|1948 Ashes series}}\nThe 1948 Australia team that toured England has become known as ''The Invincibles'', because they did not lose a single game.<ref>{{Cite web\n |url=http://www.cultureandrecreation.gov.au/articles/sportinggreats/ \n |title=Sporting greats \u2013 Australia reveres and treasures its sporting heroes \n |accessdate=18 December 2007 \n |publisher=Australian Government \u2013 Culture and Recreation Portal \n |quote=The 1948 Australian cricket team captained by Don Bradman, for example, became known as 'The Invincibles' for their unbeaten eight-month tour of England. This team is one of Australia's most cherished sporting legends. \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408184025/http://www.cultureandrecreation.gov.au/articles/sportinggreats/ \n |archivedate=8 April 2011 \n}}</ref> Following their performances during the Australian [[Cricket season|season]], Barnes and Morris were favoured as Australia's first-choice opening pair, while Brown batted out of position in the middle order in the first two Tests.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1940S/1948/AUS_IN_ENG/AUS_ENG_T1_10-15JUN1948.html\n| title = The Ashes, 1948, 1st Test \u2013 England v Australia -Trent Bridge, Nottingham \u2013 10,11,12,14,15 June 1948 (5-day match)\n| accessdate = 11 December 2007\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1940S/1948/AUS_IN_ENG/AUS_ENG_T2_24-29JUN1948.html\n| title = The Ashes, 1948, 2nd Test \u2013 England v Australia \u2013 Lord's, London \u2013 24,25,26,28,29 June 1948 (5-day match)\n| accessdate = 11 December 2007\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n}}</ref>\n\nBefore the second Test at [[Lord's]], Barnes wagered \u00a38 at 15/1 on himself to score a century.<ref name=\"insideedge\"/> He made a [[duck (cricket)|duck]] in the first innings but ensured success in the second, making 141.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/18/18500.html\n| title = England v Australia, 1948, 1st Test\n| publisher = CricketArchive\n| date= 15 June 1948\n| accessdate = 28 November 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nBarnes and Morris shared century opening partnerships at Lord's and [[The Oval]], where their 117&nbsp;run stand dwarfed the 52&nbsp;[[List of cricket terms#A|all out]] made by the entire England team.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/match/62689.html\n| title = The Ashes, 1948, 5th Test \u2013 England v Australia \u2013 The Oval, London \u2013 14,16,17,18 August 1948 (5-day match)\n| accessdate = 15 April 2008\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n}}</ref> In addition to his century at Lord's, Barnes made three other scores over 60 in the series.<ref name=\"testlist\"/>\n\nWhen fielding, Barnes stationed himself as close to the bat as possible at either [[Fielding (cricket)#Fielding position names and locations|forward short-leg or point]]. The report of the tour in the 1949 edition of [[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]], stated that Barnes's fielding was as important a factor as his batting in ''The Invincibles''' success: <blockquote>Probably a number of batsmen were sufficiently affected by his close attendance to cause them to lose concentration on the bowler running up, but equally important was the fact that the knowledge of his presence influenced opponents to avoid strokes in that direction. The Barnes<!-- This should probably be \"The Barnes' demeanour\" \u2013 can somebody check the source? --> demeanour in the field illustrated the general purposefulness of the Australians.<ref name=\"1949wisden\">Preston, 1949: pp. 240\u2013241.</ref></blockquote>\n\nHowever, he received criticism for this approach<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/player/4098.html\n| title = Sid Barnes player profile\n| publisher = Cricinfo\n| accessdate = 11 December 2007\n}}</ref> and it resulted in him missing the fourth Test at [[Headingley Cricket Ground|Headingley]] through injury.<ref name=\"testlist\"/> In England's first innings of the third Test, he was hit in the ribs by a full-blooded pull shot from [[Dick Pollard]] from the bowling of [[Ian Johnson (cricketer)|Ian Johnson]], and had to be carried from the pitch by four policemen. The following day, he collapsed while practising in the nets, and when he went in to bat at number six, he collapsed again and had to [[Substitute (cricket)#Retired hurt|retire hurt]].<ref name=\"1949wisden\"/> After this, he was taken to hospital where he spent 10 days before rejoining the tour for the [[Derbyshire County Cricket Club|Derbyshire]] match that followed the fourth Test.\n\nBarnes thus played in four of the five Tests, missing the fourth Test through injury.<ref name=\"testlist\"/> He scored 329&nbsp;runs, averaging 82.25.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/ENG/Australia_in_England_1948/t_Australia_Batting.html\n| title = Test Batting and Fielding for Australia in England 1948\n| publisher = CricketArchive\n| accessdate = 28 November 2007\n}}</ref> During the first-class tour matches, Barnes's performance was less spectacular. In all first-class matches on the tour, he amassed 1354&nbsp;runs, averaging 56.41.<ref name=\"cricinfo\"/> Barnes made 176 in 255 minutes against [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] early in the tour, but, apart from his Test hundred, his only other century came in the final tour match, when the final 50 runs of his 151 against the [[H. D. G. Leveson-Gower]] XI at the [[Scarborough Festival|Scarborough cricket festival]] came in just 25 minutes.<ref>Preston, 1949: p. 258.</ref>\n\n==Later playing career==\n[[File:BarnesMiniatureBat.jpg|thumb|Barnes plays a practical joke by using a miniature bat in [[Donald Bradman|Bradman]]'s testimonial match.]]\nAn important concern for Barnes, when returning from the United Kingdom to Australia, was to avoid paying customs [[Duty (economics)|duties]] on the enormous amount of goods he acquired through various deals during the tour. This included good quality English cloth, in very short supply in Australia at this time. Hearing a rumour that Customs officials were waiting in Sydney for him, Barnes disembarked at Melbourne and travelled to Sydney by train. The move worked and he sold his stock at a substantial profit, conservatively estimated to be equal to his tour fee.<ref>Smith, p. 130.</ref>\n\nBarnes played in Bradman's testimonial match at the MCG in December 1948, but otherwise made himself unavailable for first-class cricket, preferring to pursue business interests. He wrote a regular column for Sydney's ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]'', prosaically titled \"Like It or Lump It\", in which he often criticised the administration of the game and the amounts paid to Australia's leading cricketers.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\">Haigh and Frith, pp. 107\u2013111.</ref> Barnes was one of a number of cricket writers of the immediate post-war era who adopted a confrontational [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] style of journalism, in contrast to the more sedate reporting of the 1930s.<ref>Harte, pp. 401\u2013402.</ref>\n\n===Libel case===\n[[File:Barnes and lawyer.jpg|thumb|Barnes and his legal representative outside the venue of their libel case]]\nAt the beginning of the 1951\u201352 season, Barnes had a change of heart and returned to the New South Wales team in a bid to play Test cricket again. He approached [[Aubrey Oxlade]], the chairman of Australian cricket's [[Cricket Australia|Board of Control]], to ask if there was any impediment to his return to the Australian team. Oxlade told Barnes that he would be judged solely on his batting performances.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/>\n\nDuring his absence from the Test team, the Australian selectors had been unsuccessful in their attempts to find a reliable partner for Arthur Morris to open the batting. Barnes started the season solidly and, in the last match before the team for the third Test against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] was chosen, he hit 107 against Victoria. The selectors duly picked him for the match, then passed the team list to the Board of Control for ratification. The Board vetoed the inclusion of Barnes and requested the nomination of a replacement player. Unwilling to accept the blame for Barnes's omission, the selectors deliberately deferred their decision on the replacement.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> When the team was not announced at the scheduled time, journalists uncovered the story and Barnes became a ''[[cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre]]'' for many weeks, missing all of the remaining Tests. Speculation abounded as to the nature of his supposed misdeeds. These included jumping the turnstile at a ground when he forgot his player's pass; insulting the Royal Family; theft from team-mates; drunkenness; and stealing a car.<ref name=\"Harte1\">Harte, pp. 422\u2013423.</ref>\n\nThe Board of Control had granted themselves the power to exclude a player from the national team \"on grounds other than cricket ability\" following the poor behaviour of some members of the 1912 team that toured England.<ref>Harte, p. 256.</ref> They had a secret dossier, compiled during the season, documenting Barnes's behaviour and they doctored the minutes of the meeting at which they discussed his selection.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> Publicly, the Board remained silent on their policy and how it related to Barnes. On the field, Barnes responded with an innings of 128 in three hours against Queensland;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/20/20052.html\n|title= New South Wales v Queensland, Sheffield Shield 1951\u201352\n|date=1 January 1952\n|accessdate=3 December 2007}}</ref> off the field, he sought answers from the administrators, but was frustrated by their evasiveness. His form tapered off during the closing stages of the season and he finished with 433 first-class runs at an average of 39.36.<ref name=\"seasonbyseason\"/>\n\nJust as the furore appeared to have died down, in April 1952 Sydney's ''[[The Daily Mirror (Australia)|Daily Mirror]]'' published a letter from a reader, Jacob Raith.<ref>Smith, p. 155. \"Jacob Raith, a master baker, cricket lover from Sid's own suburb of Stanmore and a former president of Petersham Cricket Club&nbsp;...\" It continues down the same page, \"Rather than support the player, whom he did not know despite their associations with the same area, he decided to back the board.\"</ref> Responding to a letter in support of Barnes, Raith sided with the Board and suggested that his character was to blame for the omission.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> Acting on legal advice, Barnes sued Raith for [[Defamation|libel]] and engaged Sydney's leading [[barrister]], Jack Shand KC, as counsel.<ref>{{cite journal\n|last= Slee\n|first= John\n|year=2002\n|title=Shand, John Wentworth (1897\u20131959)'\n|journal= Australian Dictionary of Biography\n|volume=16\n|pages=216\u2013217\n|location= Melbourne\n|publisher=Melbourne University Press\n|url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A160257b.htm?hilite=Jack%3BShand\n|accessdate=4 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe case began in Sydney's District Court on 21 August 1952. Shand's examination of the various Board members appearing for the defendant revealed the Board's maladministration, pettiness and its acceptance of rumour as fact. No firm reason was put forward for the omission of Barnes and a division within the Board was evident when several of its members spoke highly of him.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> As Barnes began his testimony on the second day of proceedings, Raith's counsel announced settlement of the case and commented to the court, \"seldom in the history of libel actions has such a plea failed so completely and utterly\".<ref name=\"Harte1\"/> Barnes was vindicated with a full public apology.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/>\n\nAlthough the court case portrayed \"an awful image of the chaos and bigotry under which Australian cricket was administered\", it did little to alter the Board's culture. The next major court case involving Australian cricket, the [[World Series Cricket]] challenges of 1977\u201378 demonstrated that the Board was still run as a \"closed shop\", over 25 years later.<ref name=\"Harte1\"/> In an analysis of the Barnes libel case, [[Gideon Haigh]] wrote, \"far from becoming a watershed in player-administrator relations, it may even have discouraged players contemplating defiance of the Board but lacking the wherewithal to retain a hotshot criminal barrister.\"<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/>\n\n===Twelfth man incident===\n[[File:Sid Barnes, Adelaide Oval 1952.jpg|thumb|right|Barnes as twelfth man, dressed in suit and tie and carrying cigars, iced towels, a mirror and comb, a radio and a clothes brush]]\nResuming for New South Wales in 1952\u201353, Barnes scored 152 against Victoria in the last match before the beginning of the [[South African cricket team in Australia in 1952-53|Test series against South Africa]]. Nevertheless, the selectors overlooked him for the first Test and in the following state match, against South Australia at the [[Adelaide Oval]], Barnes offered to act as [[List of cricket terms#T|twelfth man]] to provide an opportunity for a younger player, [[Ray Flockton]]. During a drinks break on the second day of the match, he appeared on the ground in a suit and tie, (rather than [[Flannels|'whites']]) carrying superfluous items such as cigars, iced towels, a mirror and comb, a radio and a clothes brush. The crowd initially responded well to the joke, but their mood soured when the interval extended beyond its scheduled time and Barnes received criticism for delaying the game.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> The South Australian team, captained by Australian selector [[Phil Ridings]], officially complained to the [[New South Wales Cricket Association]] (NSWCA), which asked Barnes to express regret over the incident. Despite the association's support for Barnes during his problems of the previous season, he prevaricated. Eventually, the NSWCA forwarded a written apology on his behalf.<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/>\n\nBarnes appeared just once more for New South Wales, against South Africa at New Year 1953, then made himself unavailable for selection, conceding that \"his card had been marked\".<ref name=\"Haigh&Frith\"/> The [[Australian cricket team in England in 1953|Australian team]] toured England in 1953 and lost the [[List of cricket terms#A|Ashes]] after holding them for 19 years. Barnes wrote ''Eyes on the Ashes'', a book about the tour that included trenchant criticism of the behaviour of the Australian team, which did not go down well with some of his former team-mates.<ref name=\"adb\"/>\n\n==Style and personality==\nBarnes gripped the bat very low on the handle and bent over so far in his stance that the knuckles of his right hand were level with his knees. He stood with his heels almost together and the toes of his left foot pointing toward extra cover, which left him open-chested when facing the bowler. A noticeable flourish in his backlift enabled him to follow the swinging delivery and play it late if necessary.<ref>Robinson, p. 78.</ref> His first movement was back and across the crease to cover the stumps from the view of the bowler, putting him in position to play the hook, leg glance, sweep and his favourite square cut shot.<ref>All of these terms are included in the [[List of cricket terms]].</ref>\n\nJournalist [[Ray Robinson (cricket writer)|Ray Robinson]] called Barnes the [[Artful Dodger]] of cricket, alluding to both his batting style and his off-field business dealings, and wrote that he \"would rather steal a run like a pickpocket than hit an honest four with a straightforward stroke.\"<ref>Robinson, p. 76.</ref> Robinson summarised his safety-first approach in going so far back as the bowler delivered:\n<blockquote>Though this routine made his play air-tight in one way, it simplified opposing captains' field-placing to curb his scoring, it left him with a back-foot addict's liability to go leg-before-wicket or be caught behind on either side, and it allowed his attackers to bowl their most awkward length&nbsp;... he could have made more runs since the war as a stroke-player, and won popular backing as a candidate for the title of world's best batsman, instead of the austere distinction of looking the hardest Australian to get out.<ref>Robinson, p. 79.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n[[David Frith]] wrote of [[Bill Brown (cricketer)|Bill Brown's]] memories of Barnes as a person, and his controversial fielding:\n<blockquote>\n'Bagga' Barnes was also Bill's room-mate, and his affection for his late lamented pal, a lovable rogue, was obvious. He recalled the furore over Barnes's provocative field positioning, extremely close at silly mid-on, and how criticism of his foot being too close to the mown pitch prompted him to plonk his boot a couple of feet into the forbidden territory \u2013 and a couple of feet more when the English crowd roared at him.<ref name=\"grandpa\"/></blockquote>\n\nHe was a part-time [[leg spin|leg break]] bowler, taking 57&nbsp;wickets in first-class cricket at a useful average of 32.21.<ref name=\"az\">Cashman, pp. 14\u201315.</ref> Barnes's leg break spun very little, but he had a [[topspinner]] which hurried onto the batsman and yielded him many wickets.<ref name=\"az\"/> Barnes was also a substitute wicket-keeper and a versatile fieldsman. During his career, he was noted for his disaffection for cricket administrators and umpires. On the 1948 tour of England, after an Australian [[appeal (cricket)|appeal]] was turned down by umpire [[Alec Skelding]], he grabbed a stray dog and presented it to Skelding, stating: \"Now all you want is a white stick\".<ref name=\"cricinfo\"/> A complex character, Barnes, \"rarely forgave a slight or forgot a good turn. Stocky, with blue eyes and powerful wrists, he had a passion for physical fitness, and was an enthusiastic big-game fisherman and golfer\".<ref name=\"adb\"/>\n\n==Life outside cricket==\n[[File:SidBarnesLaterLife.jpg|thumb|Barnes in later life]]\nBarnes married a schoolteacher, Alison Margaret Edward, on 11 June 1942. Alison was the daughter of Kenneth Edward, a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[Professor]] of [[Theology]] at the [[University of Sydney]]. The couple met at a country dance, when Barnes, on his way back from an [[exhibition match]] in [[Katoomba, New South Wales|Katoomba]], was bet the price of the meal that he could not get the young girl to dance with him. Within twelve months the pair were married.<ref>Smith, p. 44.</ref>\n\nOutside of cricket, Barnes followed his mother into [[real-estate developer|property development]] (see [[Sid Barnes#Early years|above]]) and at various times entered into partnerships with [[Keith Miller]] and [[Norman Von Nida]]. His suspicious nature, which grew as time passed, saw these partnerships and developments end in arguments and recriminations. While Barnes was not a millionaire, he was a successful and organised businessman.<ref>Smith, pp. 195\u2013196.</ref>\n\nAs a writer, Barnes had no claims to literary talent; his copy was [[ghostwriter|ghost-written]], in all likelihood by his friend Jack Tier and later by former professional [[rugby league]] footballer [[Peter Peters]].<ref>Smith, pp. 185\u2013186.</ref> His writing was of a provocative tone; his column in the ''[[Daily Express]]'' during the 1953 tour was called \"The Aussie They Couldn't Gag\". His forthright opinions certainly cost him friends and hardened the opinions of others about him.<ref>Smith, pp. 183\u2013184.</ref> At the end of the 1953 tour, he published ''Eyes on the Ashes'', and his autobiography, ''It Isn't Cricket''. He also wrote ''The Ashes Ablaze'' in 1955, and turned to full-time writing, mostly for Sydney's ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]''. His columns were perceived as being deliberately controversial, and, as time went by, increasingly regarded as carping.<ref name=\"az\"/>\n\nIn later life, Barnes suffered from depressive illness. He was diagnosed with [[bipolar disorder]] and treated with a combination of medication, mainly [[diazepam]], and [[electroconvulsive therapy]]. He spent much of his last years in and out of clinics seeking treatment for his condition.<ref>Smith, pp. 204\u2013205.</ref> In 1973, Barnes died at his home in [[Collaroy, New South Wales|Collaroy]], one of Sydney's northern beach suburbs, from [[barbiturate]] and [[bromide]] poisoning. Although the medications were certainly self-administered, the [[coroner]] could not \"determine intent\".<ref name=\"adb\"/> \n{{Clear}}\n\n==Statistical analysis==\n{{Cricket batting averages (10 innings)}}\nOnly six players with ten or more completed innings have achieved an end of career average in excess of 60. Barnes's 63.05 in 19&nbsp;innings ranks him as number three in the history of Test cricket, behind Sir [[Donald Bradman]] (99.94, 80&nbsp;innings) and [[Stewie Dempster]] (65.72, 15&nbsp;innings).<ref>There is no consensus within cricket on what is the appropriate minimum number of innings required when comparing career averages, to avoid statistical quirks caused by players of very short careers. [[Andy Ganteaume]], for example, played just one Test and scored a century. In Cricinfo's statistical analysis of leading career averages, ([http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/content/records/282910.html]) Barnes is omitted for having played just 19 (rather than the minimum of 20) innings. Likewise, there is no consensus on omitting current players, something which is done because when comparing career performances, most players experience a fall-off in average toward the end of their career; Cricinfo includes current players, including one ([[Mike Hussey]]) whose career average in December 2007 exceeded that of Barnes.</ref>\n\nBarnes's short career was dominated by his monumental double hundred, but he was a consistent performer, as the chart (left) reveals. Age did not seem to diminish his abilities; in his last eight Test innings, aged 31\u201332, he passed 50 five times and scored two of his three Test hundreds.<ref name=\"testlist\">{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/4098.html?class=1;template=results;type=allround;view=match |title= Statsguru \u2013 SG Barnes \u2013 Test matches \u2013 All-round analysis |accessdate=15 April 2008| publisher=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref> [[File:Sid Barnes graph.png|thumb|left|300px|Sid Barnes's Test batting performances. The red bars indicate the runs that he scored in an innings, with the blue line indicating the [[batting average (cricket)|batting average]] in his last ten innings. The blue dots indicate an innings where he remained [[not out]].<ref name=\"testlist\"/>]]\n\nComparing players from Test cricket is an exercise usually flawed by the different conditions, rules of the day and oppositions faced. However, a useful comparison can be made between Barnes and Bradman because they were contemporaries in the same team. Bradman is generally acknowledged as the greatest [[batsman]] of all time,<ref name=\"Cricinfo1\">{{cite web\n|url = http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/content/player/4188.html\n|title = Sir Donald Bradman\n|publisher = [[Cricinfo]]\n|accessdate = 25 December 2007}}</ref> fully a third better (statistically) than the next best man in history (see completed career averages chart, right). Barnes and Bradman\nplayed together in three series.<ref>There was also a fourth, the 1938 Ashes, but Barnes played only one Test.</ref><ref name=\"Compare\">{{cite web\n|url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/guru?sdb=compare;playerid=711;class=testplayer;filter=basic;team=0;opposition=0;notopposition=0;season=0;homeaway=0;continent=0;country=0;notcountry=0;groundid=0;startdefault=1938-08-20;start=1938-08-20;enddefault=1948-08-18;end=1948-08-18;tourneyid=0;finals=0;daynight=0;toss=0;scheduledovers=0;scheduleddays=0;innings=0;result=0;followon=0;seriesresult=0;captain=0;keeper=0;dnp=0;recent=;runslow=;runshigh=;batposition=0;dismissal=0;bowposition=0;ballslow=;ballshigh=;bpof=0;overslow=;overshigh=;conclow=;conchigh=;wicketslow=;wicketshigh=;dismissalslow=;dismissalshigh=;caughtlow=;caughthigh=;caughttype=0;stumpedlow=;stumpedhigh=;viewtype=com_compare;csearch=bradman;cplayerid=492;comparetype=bat_series;compare=1;.cgifields=comparetype\n|title = Statsguru \u2013 SG Barnes \u2013 Test Batting \u2013 Comparison\n|publisher = [[Cricinfo]]\n|accessdate = 25 December 2007}}</ref> In those series, Barnes's averages bear comparison to Bradman's, particularly in the more combatitive [[The Ashes|Ashes]] series:<ref name=\"Compare\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n! width=15% | Barnes\n! width=15% | Bradman\n|-\n| [[English cricket team in Australia in 1946\u201347]]\n| align=right | 73.83\n| align=right | 97.14\n|-\n| [[Indian cricket team in Australia in 1947\u201348]]\n| align=right | 43.00\n| align=right | 178.75\n|-\n| [[Australian cricket team in England in 1948]]\n| align=right | 82.25\n| align=right | 72.57\n|}\n\nAnother way of viewing a player's performance without distortion is by using the [[ICC Player Rankings|world rankings]], which have been applied retrospectively to assess the careers of past players. However, the ratings employ a measure to \"damp down the oscillation of points of new players\".<ref name=\"Ratings\">{{cite web\n|url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/16/16093.html\n|title = Frequently Asked Questions\n|publisher = LG ICC Rankings\n|accessdate = 25 December 2007}}</ref> Because Barnes played only 19 Test innings, his performances are weighted to just under 85% of their full value.<ref name=\"Ratings\"/> Consequently, even in his own day, he is rated as no better than seventh in the world, at his peak.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://www.lgiccrankings.com/test/batting/player-display.php?id=562&graph=ranking\n|title = Sid Barnes Batting Test Ranking Statistics\n|publisher = LG ICC Rankings\n|accessdate = 25 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Test match performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" width=\"80%\"\n|-\n!colspan=2| &nbsp;\n!colspan=4| Batting<ref name=\"batsum\">{{cite web\n |url        = http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/4098.html?class=1;template=results;type=batting\n |title      = Statsguru \u2013 SG Barnes \u2013 Test matches \u2013 Batting analysis\n |accessdate = 19 June 2008\n |publisher  = [[Cricinfo]]\n}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n!colspan=4| Bowling<ref name=\"bowlsum\">{{cite web\n| url = http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/4098.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling\n| accessdate = 19 June 2008\n| title = Statsguru \u2013 SG Barnes \u2013 Test Bowling \u2013 Bowling analysis\n| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Opposition\n!| Matches\n!| Runs\n!| Average\n!| High Score\n!| 100 / 50\n!| Runs\n!| Wickets\n!| Average\n!| Best (Inns)\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[England cricket team|England]]\n|| 9\n|| 846\n|| 70.50\n|| 234\n|| 2/4\n|| 118\n|| 1\n|| 118.00\n|| 1/84\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n| style=\"text-align: